Subject: Re: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Tue)

Sorta the opposite when I'm at work and people don't like being told to 
stop what they're doing so they always say "I know, you're JUST doing 
your job...."  as if they assume I'm ok with what they're doing but I'm 
required to stop them and am unable to do otherwise.

It never occurs to them that the reason I'm telling them STOP HOLDING 
THE FUCKING DOOR OPEN" is because DJ Hearing loss thinks that because 
there's only 10 peopel in teh club teh solution is to tuirn the music up 
louder, and people want to hold the door open and ask me inane retarded 
questions like "I HAVE A HANDSTAMP, SO CAN I LEAVE AND COME BACK??" with 
the music blasting and they don't want to let the door close because 
until it shuts, they're not REALLY out the door.

I know everyone on this list clubs.  Please, try to keep a few things in 
mind though, especially with us working there...

1. It's my job.  I'm at work.  While you are enjoying time off, I'm 
clocked in.  Would you enjoy people coming to your job and start 
yelling, drinking, puking, draping themselves all over you and screaming 
drunkenly stupidity or having a g-seizure?  Ya well, neither do I. 

2.  Before asking some really stupid and obvious question, just think 
about it for one moment.  If you couldn't go in & out, why would they be 
hand stamping you?  You don't get a hand stamp at the movie theater do you?

2a.  Don't walk up talking on your cell phone and ask security what time 
it is. 
2b.  When getting you ID check, put away the cell phone.  Yapping in 
somebody face to your friends is rude.  many of us clubbed for many many 
years without cellphones and always managed to hookup and hang out with 
our friends.  It IS possible.
2c.  If it's 5pm and you ask security "what time do you close" and they 
say "4 O'clock" so not ask them "In the afternoon??"
2d.  If somebody is reading a book, do not
    1. Ask them if they're reading
    2. Ask them what they are reading
    3. Point out how surprised you are that bouncers can read
    4. bother them
2e. If there is a porta-pottie outside of a club, do not bother the 
security guy, asking him if it's ok if you use it.  That's what it's 
there for.  they would far rather you use a porta-pottie without 
expressed permission than to piss on the wall next to them.
2f . Don't show the guy on back door your handstamp while you are 
leaving, they don't give a shit and they think you are really stupid for 
doing so.
2g. Don't slap the arm of security while leaving unless you have been to 
his house, ate dinner with him, and took a shit in his bathroom.
2h. Doing anything other than walking out the back door and going about 
your business, will result in security thinking that you are a waste of 
skin.

3.  Security couldn't give a rats ass who's DJing at what time.  Don't 
ask, we don't know, we don't care.  If it's not posted near the DJ booth 
then we know as much as the customer.

4.  If you don't put your shit in coat check, don't get upset when you 
can't find and awe don't care.

5. You medical Marijuana does not mean you can bring weed into the club 
and smoke out.  It's still illegal.  Even if it were 100% legalized, the 
ABC (Alcohol Beverage Control) still says that you cannot smoke weed 
where alcohol is consumed. 

6.  If you get thrown out for whatever reason, just leave.  The faster 
you leave, the sooner everyone forgets about you.  If you stand around 
for 4 hours trying to talk your way back in, you just look liek a 
pathetic retard and we will laugh about you.  After work we will talk 
mad shit about you.  When you come back you will be referred to on radio 
as "that stupid guy last week that got thrown out and pissed off the 
door guy for 6 hours."

6a. yes, all customers that are a pain in the ass have pet names.  Some 
of which I have heard and used are:  Creepy African Guy, Creepy Indian 
Guy, Creep that is never on anyones guest list, The other creepy Indian 
guy, The Disciple (great story there), The Asian Leprechaun, No Balls, 
Miss Piggy, Garrets Girlfriend...  the list goes on.

7.  While staff is here to help, we are not here to serve, nor are we at 
your beck and call.  Keep this in mind when you get told something you 
don't like.

8.  Once security has made a decision, that will be the law.  No other 
security will over rule them, right or wrong.  Argueing, negotiating, 
and offer of chump change will not alter this decision.  If you are 
going to bribe, it had better be significant ($100 is a good starting 
point to not be insultive).  Keep in mind that the one who made the call 
is the one that needs to be bribed, not their co worker.

9.  When being a jackass after having been thrown out, it's usually a 
bad idea to talk about being friends with the owner, and when somebody 
walks up and says "what's going on" shoving them onto their ass, 
especially when it was the owner that you just shoved.


(hope this was somewhat entertaining)

I know everyone on this list clubs.  Please, try to keep a few things in 
mind though, especially with us working there...

1. It's my job.  I'm at work.  While you are enjoying time off, I'm 
clocked in.  Would you enjoy people coming to your job and start 
yelling, drinking, puking, draping themselves all over you and screaming 
drunkenly stupidity or having a g-seizure?  Ya well, neither do I.

about it for one moment.  If you couldn't go in & out, why would they be 
hand stamping you?  You don't get a hand stamp at the movie theater do you?

say "4 O'clock" so not ask them "In the afternoon??"

    1. Ask them if they're reading
    2. Ask them what they are reading
    3. Point out how surprised you are that bouncers can read
    4. bother them
2e. If there is a porta-pottie outside of a club, do not bother the 
security guy, asking him if it's ok if you use it.  That's what it's 
there for.  they would far rather you use a porta-pottie without 
expressed permission than to piss on the wall next to them.
2f . Don't show the guy on back door your handstamp while you are 
leaving, they don't give a shit and they think you are really stupid for 
doing so.
2g. Don't slap the arm of security while leaving unless you have been to 
his house, ate dinner with him, and took a shit in his bathroom.
2h. Doing anything other than walking out the back door and going about 
your business, will result in security thinking that you are a waste of 
skin.

3.  Security couldn't give a rats ass who's DJing at what time.  Don't 
ask, we don't know, we don't care.  If it's not posted near the DJ booth 
then we know as much as the customer.

4.  If you don't put your shit in coat check, don't get upset when you 
can't find and awe don't care.

5. You medical Marijuana does not mean you can bring weed into the club 
and smoke out.  It's still illegal.  Even if it were 100% legalized, the 
ABC (Alcohol Beverage Control) still says that you cannot smoke weed 
where alcohol is consumed. 

6.  If you get thrown out for whatever reason, just leave.  The faster 
you leave, the sooner everyone forgets about you.  If you stand around 
for 4 hours trying to talk your way back in, you just look liek a 
pathetic retard and we will laugh about you.  After work we will talk 
mad shit about you.  When you come back you will be referred to on radio 
as "that stupid guy last week that got thrown out and pissed off the 
door guy for 6 hours."

6a. yes, all customers that are a pain in the ass have pet names.  Some 
of which I have heard and used are:  Creepy African Guy, Creepy Indian 
Guy, Creep that is never on anyones guest list, The other creepy Indian 
guy, The Disciple (great story there), The Asian Leprechaun, No Balls, 
Miss Piggy, Garrets Girlfriend...  the list goes on.

7.  While staff is here to help, we are not here to serve, nor are we at 
your beck and call.  Keep this in mind when you get told something you 
don't like.

8.  Once security has made a decision, that will be the law.  No other 
security will over rule them, right or wrong.  Argueing, negotiating, 
and offer of chump change will not alter this decision.  If you are 
going to bribe, it had better be significant ($100 is a good starting 
point to not be insultive).  Keep in mind that the one who made the call 
is the one that needs to be bribed, not their co worker.

9.  When being a jackass after having been thrown out, it's usually a 
bad idea to talk about being friends with the owner, and when somebody 
walks up and says "what's going on" shoving them onto their ass, 
especially when it was the owner that you just shoved.


(hope this was somewhat entertaining)

My real rant of late has been....  women.  Now, there's some of you on 
this list, so please, hear me out on this rant, as it applies to 
everyone...  EQUALLY...

I have on more occasion witnessed women do things in clubs freely that 
would get a man ejected or possibly 86'd.  Women for years have played 
the "I an get anyone thrown out anytime game" and for some reason thing 
bouncers are too stupid to catch on.  Well, we know all about that 
game.  Thus, wen you complain, you'll find that typically, we take what 
you say under advisement and "keep an eye" on the suspect.  Why?  
Because honestly, there's been too much crying wolf.

Example:  Girl comes up, crying.  "There's (sob) a guy in there, he 
tried to (sob sob) get all over me.  He was grabbing my ass, trying to 
pull my top off, trying to stickhis tounge down my throat.  He wanted to 
rape me!!  throw him out!! (cry cry cry)."  We pull the guy out, she 
get's all upset at seeing him.  The guy looks completely confused.  In 
fact, the guy says to security "on my god!!!  What happened to her??  Oh 
the poor thing!  Is she ok???  Oh my god!!!"

We then tell him that she has accused him of creeping on her, attacking 
her, and grabing her in apropriately.  Guy then says "Oh my god that 
bitch!  I don't even know her!  On my god, how could she say such 
things!!!" about this time anothe rguy comes out, spots first guy "oh my 
god!  why are you here??  Your drink is getting all watery"  Hugs and 
touching between the two guys.  First guy "I don't even know that girl, 
I mean, I'm here with my boyfriend..  look at him!  Isn't he hot?  Look 
at that ass OH MY GOD (slap)!"  Smooching happens.

Now...  do I really think that this guy, with his gay friends, with his 
shirt off, shaved chest, making out with other guys in tight pants, 
bumping and grinding to  gay house music and getting all for for men, 
will suddenly spot a gal who is short, dumpy, about 50 pounds over 
weight that looks like she's 45 but her IS says 28, and decide he's 
gotta ride that hetrotrain to vagina town right here, right now.

No.  And neither do you.

That's but one example.

I often observe women who will  unasked for, decide they are going to 
drape themselves on people, start kissing on them, grab random ass,  and 
do what they want to who they want.  Acting in a way that any guy would 
get the shit kicked out of them, but they get away with it because they 
are a woman and figure any man they grab will be thrilled with the 
attention because we're all pigs.

This has to stop.  The same rules apply to everyone.  That's equality.

Urgent Letter re the $700 Billion Bank Bailout

Dear Fellow American Citizen:

The ongoing, severe economic turmoil in our nation - destined to get =20
worse if the right remedy is not enacted - was predicted in our video =20
The Money Masters as the inevitable result of our fractional reserve =20
banking system.

Our banking system, established by the Federal Reserve Act of 1913, =20
works essentially like a spring.  When the Central Bank, the Federal =20
Reserve, wishes to create new money, it simply does so.  There are no =20
reserves to our money.  The Fed then spends this money, usually to buy =20
Treasury Bonds from private owners of the bonds (more recently to =20
bailout or help huge banks buyout failing banks), which the sellers =20
had purchased from the Treasury Department.  These bonds (and Treasury =20
bills, TIPS and notes) were initially sold to the public to fund =20
government deficits. In our metaphor the money created by the Fed is =20
the spring.  The spring gets stretched in the following manner.

Banks, privately-owned, are permitted to loan out 90% of this new =20
Fed-created money once it is deposited by the sellers of the bonds.  =20
That would not be a problem, except for the fact that the borrowers =20
almost always redeposit the money (or the people they pay with their =20
loan proceeds do).  Once re-deposited, the banks can lend it out =20
again.  This re-loan, redeposit, re-loan, redeposit, etc. scheme, =20
authorized by the Federal Reserve Act of 1913, allows banks each time =20
to retain just 10% of the re-deposited loan proceeds as a reserve, =20
ultimately allowing banks to lend out 9 times the original amount =20
deposited, and to charge interest on it as many times as it was =20
loaned.  So instead of an interest rate of, for example, 6%, the banks =20
may be collectively receiving a total of 54% interest per year (6% x =20
9; usually it is somewhat less due to the lack of qualified =20
borrowers).  Now you know, if have not already seen The Money Masters, =20
why banks grow and prosper much more than other businesses, that is, =20
until they have stretched the spring to the maximum.

Once the economy is flooded with the bank-created money 9 times in =20
excess of the money originally created by the Fed, an expansion that =20
increases the money supply, which reduces the purchasing power of =20
already-existing money (including wages and savings), interest rates =20
begin to drop (as there is more money to lend) and prices rise =20
(inflation).  The dollar begins to fall relative to the money of other =20
countries not in this same stage of money expansion.  Money begins to =20
flow out of US Treasury bonds (due to lower interest rates and the =20
lessening purchasing power of the dollar due to inflation).  Thus ends =20
the expansionary or "boom" part of this artificial "business cycle."  =20
To combat rising inflation and the falling dollar, the Fed begins =20
raising interest rates.

Then the spring of the economy - the money supply - having been =20
stretched to the maximum, begins its contraction, usually initiated by =20
rising interest rates reaching a point that begins to inhibit =20
borrowing and also inflation.  The economic "bust" part of the cycle =20
begins. Loans dwindle as interest rates rise and credit terms tighten. =20
  Various segments of the economy, accustomed to easy credit, begin to =20
contract due to higher interest rates; loans become harder to get.  =20
Home prices fall, businesses begin to fail, bankruptcy's increase.  =20
This "bust" part of the cycle continues, and worsens, until inflation =20
is "tamed," prices stabilize, and the dollar rises relative to other =20
currencies.  Eventually, the higher interest rates begin to attract =20
foreign money, and the Treasury then is able to borrow what it needs =20
at lower and lower interest rates.  Interest rates fall.  The =20
artificial cycle then begins anew.

This boom-bust economic cycle is totally unnecessary and is the =20
fundamental cause of the inherent instability in our economy.  It is =20
due to too-rapid increases in the money supply due to deficit spending =20
and then the multiplier effect of fractional reserve banking =20
(described above) and to lenders greedy to take advantage of such a =20
system that rewards lending with more and more interest revenue; =20
followed by a too-rapid contraction of the money supply (such as we =20
are experiencing now), necessary to combat the inflationary effects of =20
the former phase, both the direct result of the Federal Reserve Act of =20
1913.  We urgently need to reform this system that rewards greed and =20
results in ever-increasing swings from boom-to-bust - destroying =20
ordinary businesses and farms in the process.  We need to repeal or =20
fundamentally reform the Federal Reserve Act of 1913, and to replace =20
it with a system that eliminates the ability of private banks to =20
"create" and multiply money as loans.

The major banks of this country - the ones the government is lending =20
your money to, and from which the Bailout Bill proposes to buy their =20
bad assets (wouldn't you too like the opportunity to sell off your bad =20
investments to the government!), are busily swallowing up the banks in =20
trouble in this latest bust - one deeper because of more rapid prior =20
monetary expansion and inflation.  As after all prior bust cycles, =20
they will emerge larger and more powerful, and fewer.  Wealth will be =20
even more concentrated under their control, which they will use in the =20
next bust to further this process, until eventually no one will own =20
anything but the ability to borrow - to go deeper into debt to banks =20
than their neighbors. Not savings, but credit scores will determine =20
the average American's ability to engage in economic activity (such as =20
buying a home or car).  No one will dare breathe a word against such =20
power, concentrated in very few hands, and our republic will end with =20
a whimper.

Our Congress struggles with ignorance of the complex, bank-created =20
system enacted in 1913.  It struggles with the money the bank PACs =20
flood into the political system to defeat their critics and elect =20
their shills. It struggles with mass media owned or controlled by the =20
banks, which seek to stir up panic in the populace, to stampede =20
Congress into bank-developed "solutions" that only make the =20
fundamental problems worse and increase their wealth.  Based on =20
history, the banks will not fail to see-saw the economy and the =20
markets to match their strategies for fooling the public, and putting =20
pressure on the Congress to do their will.  But we must resist.  We =20
must hold out for genuine reform - for repeal or fundamental reform of =20
the Federal Reserve Act of 1913.

Here is a hyperlink to one such reform proposal, the Monetary Reform =20
Act. It is not the only possible reform, but it is one developed, in =20
its essentials, over many years by numerous monetary reformers =20
including the late Nobel Laureate, Dr. Milton Friedman.  Any genuine =20
reform of our monetary system must include two basic elements: =20
fractional reserve lending (such as described above) must be =20
prohibited, and private banks must be forbidden from creating money, =20
whether as loans or otherwise.  The Monetary Reform Act does both.  It =20
also incorporates means of doing this that include paying off the huge =20
national debt, and stabilizing the economy.

We have not previously written the viewers of The Money Masters.  We =20
judged the time was not ripe.  But increasingly we are being asked - =20
urgently - what can we do, and when, to be effective. Now it is =20
clearly urgent that we flood Congress with our calls, emails and =20
letters, to oppose the proposed taxpayer-funded Bailout of the banks.  =20
Rather, we support genuine reform, that will not result in an even =20
greater concentration of economic power in fewer and fewer hands.  We =20
support the Monetary Reform Act, or any such Act that repeals or =20
reforms the Federal Reserve Act so as to prohibit fractional reserve =20
banking and money creation (as loans or otherwise) by private banks.  =20
We oppose the Bailout of the banks.  We want genuine, fundamental =20
reform, now!

Very truly yours,

Patrick  S.J. Carmack

Patrick S.J. Carmack, J.D.
Producer of The Money Masters
themoneymasters.com



The Two Step Plan to National Economic Reform and Recovery


1. Directs the Treasury Department to issue U.S. Notes (exactly like =20
Lincoln's Greenbacks) to pay off the National debt.

2. Increases the reserve ratio private banks are required to maintain =20
from 10% to 100%, thereby terminating their ability to create money, =20
while simultaneously absorbing the funds created to retire the =20
national debt.

These two relatively simple steps, which Congress has the power to =20
enact, would extinguish the national debt, without inflation or =20
deflation, and end the unjust practice of private banks creating money =20
as loans (i.e., fractional reserve banking). Paying off the national =20
debt would wipe out the $400+ billion annual interest payments and =20
thereby balance the budget. This Act would stabilize the economy and =20
end the boom-bust economic cycles caused by fractional reserve =20
banking.  For the full text of the Act click here to read the MONETARY =20
REFORM ACT.

Support the Monetary Reform Act - contact your Congressman today!

Money Masters | PO Box 67 | Manitou Springs | CO | 80829

ok everybody, here's the scoop on getting in for a jackson:

* send an email to kontrolrsvp@gmail.com

* include a first and last name

* one name per email. (no +1s, etc.)

* if it's not already on there, the email address used will be added to our
email list. it's low-traffic, secure, and you can unsubscribe at any time.

* to redeem, mention rsvp list at the box office, your first and last name
as included in the email, and have ID ready.

* deadline to rsvp is friday night at midnight.

* this entry rate is good all night (til our event ends @ 6am).


thanks and see you saturday!

----> greg

JOSH WINK

An American producer who simultaneously possessed European hit singles, a
major-label album contract, consistent contact with the dance mainstream,
plus the requisite underground credentials, Josh Wink appeared to lack for
nothing at the peak of his success in the mid-'90s. Part of the East
Coast/Philadelphia dance scene, Wink recorded three techno monsters out of
his bedroom studio (as Wink, Winx, and Size 9) that topped charts in Europe
during 1995 and saw him anointed as a dance poster boy, easily recognized b=
y
his ruddy good looks and flowing blond dreadlocks. Hardly the techno
kingpin, however, Wink's espousal of a vegan lifestyle and his defiantly
anti-drug ideals made him something of a unique personality in the
hedonistic world of dance music.

After being turned on by punk rock in the '70s, Josh Winkelman was inspired
by a diverse group of dance-styled artists during the 1980s -- ranging from
Depeche Mode to Kraftwerk to Run-D.M.C. -- and began working with a
Philadelphia-based mobile DJ service from the age of 13. After he met up
with a fellow DJ, King Britt, at one party, the duo began recording. One of
their first productions, 1990's "Tribal Confusion" by E-Culture, was
released on New York's Strictly Rhythm Records and became a success in
America's exploding club/rave scene, which Wink and Britt soundtracked by
DJing at events around the country. Wink had also recorded for Nervous,
another vaunted East Coast dance label, before forming Ovum Records in late
1994 with Britt.

Ovum and Wink had an international club hit right out of the box with 1995'=
s
"Liquid Summer"; the single led to Wink recording for a maze of European
labels. During 1995, he recorded "Don't Laugh" by Winx, "I'm Ready" by Size
9, and "Higher State of Consciousness" by Winks, all of which topped
European dance charts and even made several pop charts despite their debt t=
o
hard-edged acid trance. The singles were collected along with new material
for his 1996 debut album, Left Above the Clouds, and released as Winx. The
major labels came calling in 1997, and Wink decided to sign not only himsel=
f
but the entire Ovum Recordings label to a deal with Columbia. After
recording with King Britt, Nine Inch Nails' Trent Reznor, poet Ursula
Rucker, and Philly mod punks the Interpreters, Wink released his proper
album debut, Herehear, in 1998; the mix album Profound Sounds, Vol. 1
followed the next year. He spent much of his time contributing to Ovum acts
King Britt and Jamie Myerson, but by 2003 he had released both a second
volume in Profound Sounds as well as his second production album, 20 to 20.
Profound Sounds, Vol. 3 appeared in 2006.

SPEEDY J

After fifteen years of techno Speedy J has come full circle. He's making
techno again. But what a wide circle it was, and how fickle the trodden
path. Over the years he has collaborated with video-artists, filmmakers and
advertisers, made the pioneering DVD Umfeld and has continuously been
pushing the boundaries of electronic & experimental dance music. "I just
constantly want to do new things," he explains. Most recently this has been
exemplified in his new label Electric Deluxe, which will issue digital
releases only.

Jochem Paap (the Rotterdam artist owes the nickname Speedy J to his DJ
skills) is unanimously considered to be one of the first techno producers t=
o
come from the Benelux. Someone who, together with people like Laurent
Garnier, Aphex Twin and his good friend Richie Hawtin, helped raise the
genre just after it had escaped the Detroit delivery room. But while techno
develops into a multi-faced monster that still dominates many dance floors
worldwide, Jochem Paap, after the albums G Spot (1993) and Ginger (1995),
turns left and heads for more exciting places. On Public Energy No. 1 (1997=
)
and A Shocking Hobby (2000) the sound wizard exchanges flowing, harmonious
techno for a much more complex sound, filled with colliding samples,
crackling rhythms and tremendously thrilling turns. This is the time when
electronic dance music becomes profound and contemporaries like Autechre,
Funkst=F6rung and Aphex Twin have their machinery perform ever more
complicated tricks. During those days Jochem Paap converts his studio into =
a
modular system, which wins him the sought-after freedom. Suddenly everythin=
g
is possible with sound. And if an idea turns out to be more unruly than
expected he simply looks for software with which to crack the code of his
ideas after all. He discusses sound like graphic designers discuss form,
speaking of "contrast" and "depth" instead of a little ruffle here or a
bass-lick there. "I am sometimes really chiselling at sound," he reports
from his futuristic studio located in one of the famous cube quarters in
Rotterdam. "In essence my work is about stylising rather than composing."
Stylising is his strong point, he feels. "I might not be a brilliant
musician but I do know very well how to fashion my ideas into a particular
form. Out of a few components I try to make something distinctive."

Although Jochem Paap enjoys chiselling at sounds alone in his cube studio
for hours on end, he is anything but an einzelg=E4nger. Such is evident in =
his
Collabs-project, through which he has been collaborating with various techn=
o
musicians since 2004. The German Chris Liebing and Paap collaborate most
fruitfully. Together they play DJ sets in clubs for hours and released the
album Metalism in 2005, a ruthless techno-bomb more powerful than the
bunkerbusters of the American army. "Working with someone else provides you
with new insights," says Paap. "Collabs offers us both the possibility to
explore corners which we wouldn't so readily visit as solo artists. Collabs
prospers on the dance floor and after extensive wandering Paap's recent sol=
o
material brings him back to the clubs. "Right now I feel very strongly abou=
t
making and releasing techno. My heart is really in dance music after all."

DRUMCELL

Founder of Droid Recordings and co-founder of Droid Behavior, Drumcell has
been one of techno's greatest allies in Southern California in recent times=
.


A graduate of the Musician's Institute and a long-time performer at parties
in Southern California, Drumcell has been influenced by music from his
earliest years. After being exposed to raves in the early 90s, He grew
addicted to the sounds of acid house, techno, in its many forms, and
industrial. It was not long before he was copping turntables to satisfy his
vinyl fetish. By the early age of 14 he was playing in various local bands,
and through out the rest of his teenage years, cut his teeth-producing hip
hop records, dub and various forms of electronic music on Los Angeles based
underground labels. By combining his Production, DJing and networking skill=
s
and focusing in on his more mature musical tastes he soon established
himself as one of the major players in LA's growing techno scene.
Associating with the members of Acid Circus to form Droid Behavior as an
event production group and record label was the next logical step to raise
awareness for techno in the city and to help expose local Artists,
established djs, and performers from around the country. Over the last 5
years Drumcell has rocked parties from big to small on a weekly basis in LA
as well as gigs all over the U.S alongside such names as Kenny Larkin, John
Tejada, Tim Xavier, Dan Bell, Ben Sims, Adam Beyer, Jeff Mills, Speedy J,
Richie Hawtin, Mathew Dear, etc. and has also released quite a few heavy
trax on labels Omniscient, Remains, Heavy Industries, and his own DROID
Recordings imprint.

Drumcell has been known to keep on the edge of technology and continuously
pushing the limits to what the future has to offer. He is always in the
process of developing homebrew software as well as cutting edge hardware
solution to bring a fresh innovative taste to his production and
performances. When performing, Drumcell can be seen blurring the lines
between a live and a DJ set by utilizing tools such as FX processors,
samplers, drum machines, and other devices to weave a thick blend of acidic
techno and aggressive but funky minimalist groove to ensure a frenzy amongs=
t
his listeners. With the state of electronic music in North America leaning
towards stripped down funk rather then progressive fluff these days, Droid
has become the center for LA techno and Drumcell remains steadfast in his
mission of putting this city on the global map.


=3D=3D=3D> LINKS:

http://www.myspace.com/drumcell

Droid Behavior website:
http://www.droidbehavior.com/mission.html

Droid Behavior on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/droidbehavior

See all of you midnight marauders on the dancefloor!

Rock It Science founder Eric Sharp will be performing at Lovefest from 1:00
to 1:30 PM on SFHousemusic's Karma Float, 2:30 to 4 PM on Flavor Group's
Solid Gold Jacuzzi Float, and at 7 PM on Supperclub's float.  After that we
are throwing a bass bin rattling, floor shaking, sweat inducing after party
at Supperclub with 2 of the hottest acts in the USA.  Advance tickets are o=
n
sale through 10 AM tomorrow.  YEAH!!!!

*Scion, Supperclub, Rock It Science, and Everyscape present:*

*Drop The Lime aka Curses and Spank Rock's Devlin & Darko!!*

Tickets/Info: http://www.going.com/spankthelime

Scion, Supperclub, Rock It Science, and Everyscape.com come together to
bring you a smoking hot afterparty for the SF Lovefest at San Francisco's
world renowned Supperclub. Come lose your mind to the sounds of the freshes=
t
artists who are breaking barriers and pushing envelopes across the globe,
playing festivals like Coachella, Rock The Bells, and Shambala:* Drop the
Lime aka Curses*, NYC's Heavy Bass Champion, plus genre bending hip
hop/electro act *Spank Rock's Devlin & Darko* along with a great supporting
lineup. Do it!!

Talent:
*
Drop The Lime aka Curses (Institubes, Trouble & Bass - NYC)
*
Set the standard; then raise the bar. Or in New York City's Luca Venezia's
case =96 totally destroy that bar on a global scale. The 25-year-old known =
as
Drop The Lime (and Curses!) is the iconoclastic club fiend of the 21st
Century. Producer, remixer and DJ, he started out at 17 and has since
dropped approximately 150 underground classics, each year breaking
boundaries of the musical zeitgeist =96 relentlessly developing concepts an=
d
sounds that leaves his many imitators wiping away tears with a white flag.
Lauded by critics (XLR8R/Dazed & Confused), premier blogs (Discobelle, Tras=
h
Menagerie, Fluo Kids), peers (UK production God Switch named Luca in his to=
p
artists of 2007) and the world's cutting edge record labels (releases on Ma=
d
Decent, Counterfeet, Shockout, Ambush, Institubes and Fools Gold), he is th=
e
undisputed, celebrated NYC Bass Heavy Champion. Drop The Lime's acclaimed
solo albums =96 2005's "This Means Forever" and 2007's "We Never Sleep" on
Tigerbeat6 saw him murdering bass and bytes =96 an evolved style,
re-appropriating breakcore, bassline house, rave, jungle and dubstep,
unforgettably touched with Luca's own original vocals. Recent remixes for
Moby, Robyn, Blaqstarr, Health Disco, Midnight Juggernauts and Infants have
fuelled the blaze. It's time to get hysterical.

*Spank Rock's Devlin and Darko (Big Dada - Baltimore)*

Best known for being members of the amazing live act Spank Rock, Devlin &
Darko have dj-ed with the likes of Beck, KRS 1 and Gnarls Barkley, as well
as finding time to start 2 successful monthly parties: Baltimore Bass
Connection in Baltimore and Fully Fitted in NYC. They also put out highly
popular mix tapes with Spank Rock producer XXXchange.

Devlin & Darko have deep crates and they know how to use them, mixing
everything from classic hip hop to Italo disco to French electro into a
dance party that's populist without being strictly pop. They're adept
mixers, inventive selectors, and genial hosts. Expect them to keep things
bouncing until the very moment the lights go on and the sound guy pulls the
plug.

*James Amato (Potty Mouth Music, Smart Bar - Chicago)*

Label boss of the wildly successful fidget house label Potty Mouth Music
joins us from Chicago to drop his signature blend of nasty dirty tracks!

I don't know if any of you have had a chance to look at the economic =20
bailout bill that the House rejected by a slim margin but the Senate =20
passed their own version and is now in review for the House.  The bill =20
is 450 pages long and clearly just by scanning it shows me that the =20
bill gives sweeping new powers to the Treasury Secretary.  Other =20
things I've heard about it are it is mostly a bailout of derivatives, =20
not mortgages.  So this is going to collapse again in a few months =20
because derivatives are not worth anything, they are just paper.

How about the people, the ones that went to college for 4 years and =20
can't find a job, or people  that have been downsized, or families =20
being foreclosed on?  7 million people starved to death during the =20
Great Depression.

The people that want this bailout package to go through have a vested =20
interest in it, and are threatening there will be a crash if it =20
doesn't pass.  Well that's going to happen anyway, but don't you think =20
it's funny that the Dow dropped over 700 points the day the House did =20
not pass the bill.  This is economic terrorism being waged on the =20
people by the private bankers that control the monetary system.

I'm not trying to scare anyone or create fear.  The bankers are =20
already doing that for us.  I look at history and wonder what it might =20
look like today.  I hope the phone calls to the Representatives =20
continue.

Enjoy Lovefest this weekend, but also look at infrastructure of the =20
event itself and ask yourself how many of these services, including =20
the food served there, was not available because businesses shut down =20
due to the financial system correcting itself.  I tend to want to =20
believe that since the communication is more instantaneous and =20
widespread, things will turn out different than in 1929.  But we shall =20
see, won't we?

--

brats, the people that think that beef just grows on trees, all they =20
know how to do is 'card workie or 'card no workie' at the ATM, they =20
are going to turn into howling mobs of demons.  And the New World =20
Order is going to point them at the Patriots and say, "get 'em."

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Fri)


He does and he doesn't.  The very instantaneously efficient nature of
our economy also means that there's less of a vague period of rampant
inflation, because the cash becomes worthless instantly. :)

This means essentially, that money becomes obviously worthless in an
instant instead of where people kept trying to use it and had to spend
more and more of it to get things.

When this fiat economy goes, it'll pretty much be an instant barter
situation.  You have what you have and you either deal or coerce to
get what you need.  Or people starve very quickly and the reduction
in population makes things more sustainable fairly quickly, albeit
with some intensely widespread suffering to get there.

So yeah, he's got some points, but it won't be like he thinks, it'll
be worse...  And quite possibly it'll turn out that economics was the
weapon after nukes, and we'll have little more than sticks and stones
when this is all over.

-R.

"And quite possibly it'll turn out that economics was the
weapon after nukes"

I note that just a few weeks after Russia attacked Georgia, the Russian stock 
market lost half its value.? While we worry about the economy here, the U.S. 
Europe, Japan, and China faired better, losing much less value on a percentage 
basis.? Oil plummeted, dropping below $100 a barrel.? Getting the picture?

The question is who launched the attack?? Is the U.S. the target or the 
attacker?? Not everything is what it seems...

Here's some links if you are intereted in this theme...

Start here:

----- Original Message ----
From: Ray Wong <rayw@rayw.net>
To: electrofunk138@hotmail.com
Cc: michael the redstickman <red_stickman@yahoo.com>; sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Friday, October 3, 2008 2:56:25 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Fri)


He does and he doesn't.? The very instantaneously efficient nature of
our economy also means that there's less of a vague period of rampant
inflation, because the cash becomes worthless instantly. :)

This means essentially, that money becomes obviously worthless in an
instant instead of where people kept trying to use it and had to spend
more and more of it to get things.

When this fiat economy goes, it'll pretty much be an instant barter
situation.? You have what you have and you either deal or coerce to
get what you need.? Or people starve very quickly and the reduction
in population makes things more sustainable fairly quickly, albeit
with some intensely widespread suffering to get there.

So yeah, he's got some points, but it won't be like he thinks, it'll
be worse...? And quite possibly it'll turn out that economics was the
weapon after nukes, and we'll have little more than sticks and stones
when this is all over.

-R.

Subject: [sfraves] Prohibition UG Ticket Confusion?

There seems to be some confusion regarding the presales for P.U.G. Our =
flyers say, "Limited 100 pre-sales, $13 + drink ticket, $15 at the =
door".  The first batch of 100, $13 presales did sell out, but the way =
the flyers are written, one might assume the other 300+ would be held =
for sale at the door.  That's a big Oh Noooooo!  Woopsie! (The mere =
thought of selling 300+ tickets at the door gives me the willies.)  So =
yes, presales ARE still available through our website. The only =
difference is they're $15 and don't come with a drink ticket.  Sorry for =
the confusion.  =20

Where to go to grab 'em:  http://www.prohibitionparty.net

Oh and while your there, you can check out some of the new content, such =
as:
- A list of costume shops and stores that cater to vintage wear =
throughout the Sacramento & Bay Area for those wanting to come dressed =
in theme. After all it's close to Halloween, so maybe you can kill two =
birds with one stone?   http://www.prohibitionparty.net/costumes.html

- A forum for anyone who might like to help out in some way (or just say =
"hey").  I'm still a couple bartenders short actually - hint hint.  If =
you're in a financial spot and think you might be able to offer some of =
your time & energy in exchange for entry, then sign up and introduce =
yourself there.  http://forums.prohibitionparty.net/

weee!

*************************************************************************=
*****
Saturday, November 15th, 2008
Dragn'fly, Forest Green & friends present: Prohibition Underground
For full event info, costume ideas, & $15 presales go to:
http://www.prohibitionparty.net
Infoline: (415) 963-3553

from http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081004/ap_on_re_us/ike_lives_lost
Islanders who insisted on staying died in Ike

 By MONICA RHOR, Associated Press Writer *Sat Oct 4, 1:58 PM ET*

GALVESTON, Texas - The final hours brought the awful realization to victims
of Hurricane Ike that they had waited too long. This storm wasn't like the
others, the ones that left nothing worse than a harrowing tale to tell.

George Helmond, a hardy Galveston salt, watched the water rise and told a
buddy: I was born on this island and I'll die on this island.

Gail Ettenger, a free spirit who adopted the Bolivar Peninsula as her home
15 years ago, told a friend in a last phone call: I really messed up this
time.

Within hours, the old salt and the free spirit were gone as the powerful
Category 2 hurricane wracked the Texas Gulf Coast on Sept. 13, flattening
houses, obliterating entire towns and claiming at least 33 lives.

The dead =97 as young as 4, as old as 79 =97 included lifelong Galvestonian=
s
firmly rooted on the island and transplants drawn by the quiet of coastal
living.

Seven people drowned in a storm surge that moved in earlier and with more
ferocity than expected. Nine others died in the grimy, sweaty aftermath,
when lack of power and medicine exacted its toll. Eleven people were
poisoned by carbon monoxide or killed in fires from the generators they use=
d
in their own attempts to survive.

Hundreds of people remain missing three weeks after Ike's assault on Texas.
Local and city officials are no longer keeping their own count of missing
residents, and the estimate varies wildly from one agency to another.

According to the nonprofit Laura Recovery Center, about 300 people are
missing. Of those, about 200 from Galveston. However, the number "goes up
and down by the minute" as people call in to remove or add names, cautioned
executive director Bob Walcutt.

Some vanished during the evacuation of towns in the storm's path. Many were
last heard in desperate, last-ditch calls for help.

Immediately after the hurricane, Galveston officials conducted door-to-door
searches for survivors and possible victims. But the city is no longer
taking an active role in the search, city spokeswoman Alicia Cahill said.

Instead, search teams of sheriff's deputies, volunteer firefighters and
special K-9 search and recovery units have been using airboats and
all-terrain vehicles to sift through debris fields, tangled and fetid
marshlands, and the rubble left behind by Ike.

Bodies could have been tossed anywhere in the marshes, where thickets of
trees are littered with the contents of houses. Refrigerators, office
chairs, and television sets are scattered everywhere __ in the mud, in
bushes, on treetops.

"We are definitely looking and are going to do anything we can to find them=
,
but there may not be any answers to be given," said Galveston County
emergency management spokesman Colin Rizzo. "There are definitely going to
be people from Hurricane Ike that are never found."

_____

Gail Ettenger stumbled upon her house in Gilchrist by accident. But once sh=
e
saw the site on the bay side of Bolivar Peninsula, she knew she would never
leave.

Ettenger, a native of New Jersey, instilled the house with her own energy
and style. The 58-year-old's garden bloomed with vibrant birds-of-paradise.

And Reba, an 11-year-old Great Dane hobbled by arthritis, was her baby.
Ettenger loved to treat the dog to dinners of chicken and roast beef,
recalled JoAnne Burks, Ettenger's neighbor and close friend.

Ettenger, a chemist at ExxonMobil, didn't evacuate, reasoning that her hous=
e
had weathered Hurricane Rita in 2005 without a problem. She also did not
want to leave Reba, who could no longer climb into Ettenger's Jeep.

Burks and her husband pleaded with Ettenger to change her mind. But she
insisted.

Hours before Ike made landfall, Ettenger knew she had made the wrong choice=
.
She called Burks and described the water pushing up under her feet, the
propane tanks and other household items drifting by her windows, and
wondered which would float better: her Jeep or her house.

Her voice was shaky with fear, Burks said.

Burks spent the next 10 days searching for her friend, calling local, count=
y
and state officials without success. She tried the American Red Cross, FEMA=
,
even private investigators.

"I didn't want her to wind up like the victims of Katrina, who were never
found or identified," Burks said.

Ettenger's body was found Sept. 23, tossed on a debris field in a Chambers
County marsh about 10 miles from her house.

Amid the muck and remnants of homes, Burks found a pink leather collar. The
name Reba was spelled out in rhinestones.

_____

At 72, George Helmond had ridden out many storms and thought he could take
on Ike, too, neighbor Don Hanson said. "A lot of old Galvestonians are like
that."

Helmond had been one of the first residents of Sydnor Lane, which overlooks
a bayou on one side and a golf course on the other. A retired electrician,
Helmond was a die-hard fisherman, a dove hunter and straight-shooter
intensely proud of his Galveston roots.

Around 10 a.m., Helmond called Hanson, who had already left, to say the
water had already slipped over the road and toward his house. The street =
=97
the only way out of the neighborhood =97 was already impassable.

At 9:30 p.m., Helmond and Hanson talked for the last time. By then, the
water had pummeled through Helmond's garage, crushing the doors and
submerging his Cadillac. Hanson begged his friend to grab a life vest at hi=
s
house or to seek shelter there.

But at 2:30 a.m., for reasons no one knows, Helmond got in his pickup truck
and drove off at the height of Ike's fury.

Neighbors found Helmond's body the next day inside the truck, which had
slammed into the white golf course fence. The windshield was shattered.

Helmond's home suffered little damage. The water had reached above the
first-floor garage, but not inside the house.

"If he had stayed home and hadn't gone out, he'd be OK, but he panicked,"
said Hanson, 66. "Life goes on, but I will miss a good friend and I will
think about him."

_____

Even as Ike bore down on Texas, Jim Devine refused to leave his
cream-colored house within sight of the bay in San Leon. Devine had moved t=
o
the fishing town after retiring and loved the tranquil way of life there,
neighbors said.

The 76-year-old Devine drowned when Ike sent water barreling through his
house, picking him off the second-story porch and dropping him a block away=
.
Days later, Devine's empty home still bore the scars of the storm =97
shattered windows, twisted wood, and his boat, the Seabar, jammed under the
front steps.

His daughter left a warning and a memorial in orange spray paint: "Jim
Devine. No Trespassing."

_____

Port Bolivar held special meaning for 79-year-old Marian Violet Arrambide.
She met her husband there during World War II. Many years later, he built
the beach house where they could retire.

Arrambide, a retired nurse suffering the onset of dementia, lived with her
daughter, Magdalena Strickland, and nephew, Shane Williams, in that beach
house before Ike struck.

All three have been missing since the morning of Sept. 12, just as Ike bega=
n
to come ashore.

"My sister said 'I'm walking out the door in a hurry. Everything's taken
care of, I'll see you in a few hours.' That was it," said son Raul
Arrambide, describing a 6:15 a.m. phone call.

Since then, Arrambide has had little luck getting help or information.
Instead, Arrambide said, he's been passed from one agency to another.

"They send you back and forth until you're worn out," said Arrambide, his
voice showing the strain of the last weeks.

After five days with no word and no answers, Arrambide borrowed a boat to
search the area himself, but sheriff's deputies turned people away. He
finally found a local contractor who is helping search for missing
residents. That man found his relatives' vehicles, which had been washed of=
f
the road into a tree grove.

"I want to keep the hope that they are still alive, but by not hearing from
any of them, that hope is getting smaller and smaller," he said. "They
helped people all their lives. They did not deserve to go this way."

from
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112269/Why-propping=
-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html
Why propping up banks will not rescue a debauched financial system
Confession time. As 228 Representatives in Congress voted against Hank
Paulson's bail-out plan on Monday, I was cheering them on.


By Jeff Randall
Last Updated: 1:14PM BST 01 Oct 2008

Comments 127<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112269=
/Why-propping-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html#co=
mments>|
Comment
on this article<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112=
269/Why-propping-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html=
#postComment>

At last, there were public figures prepared to reject the political and
financial blackmail of a debased White House-Wall Street elite.

This is an unfashionable view; it runs counter to The Daily Telegraph's
editorial line. But the hard-sell of President Bush and the US Treasury
Secretary felt too much like the pressure patter of a door-to-door hawker.
Their message was crude: "Trust us. You are in a terrible place. Only we ca=
n
get you out of this mess. No need to check the details. Hurry now, or it
will be too late. Here's a pen. There's the dotted line. Just sign."

But with the President's ratings so low, few would let him leave the House
with anything more than small change. Congress asked, not unreasonably: "If
you guys know so much about banking, how come we are in such trouble?"

Having spent most of the year telling America, contrary to mounting
evidence, that the US economy was just dandy, Mr Bush's credibility is
threadbare. When making statements, he's beginning to look as if he doesn't
even believe himself. As for Mr Paulson, his long association with the
jackpot culture of Goldman Sachs is, in the eyes of many outsiders, a gilde=
d
millstone.

Predictably, the refuseniks have been pilloried as ill-informed nihilists.
They have been lambasted for failing to understand the consequences of thei=
r
actions. They are, according to the Big Bail-out Brigade, condemning the
rest of us to be buried alive in the rubble of a disintegrating banking
system.

Try a different take. Yes, the West's financial infrastructure is in severe
distress. Yes, more banks are going to crumble. Yes, there will be a
recession. But allocating $700bn (it would almost certainly turn out to be
more) to a clean-up programme for toxic assets, in effect socialising the
poison of private greed, has no merit other than to delay the inevitable. N=
o
amount of federal cash can rewind the X-rated horror video.

There is a conspiracy of bankers and politicians whose self-interest is
masquerading as sophisticated policy. They want us to believe that they hav=
e
the keys to salvation. I have not seen a scrap of evidence to confirm this.

There will, of course, be a renewed effort in Washington to push through a
package of national deliverance. Concessions will be made. The US taxpayer
will be offered improved terms. And, having made their point, having stood
up for "traditional American values", some of the naysayers in the House of
Representatives will cross over, enabling a deal to be done. Their
consciences will be salved, but the crisis will not be solved.

Meanwhile, in Britain, the ban on short-selling bank shares has done nothin=
g
to make them more attractive to investors. Having blamed hedge funds for
driving down the price of supposedly healthy businesses, officials must be
at a loss to explain why bank shares keep falling.

Halifax-Bank of Scotland dropped another 14pc yesterday to 122p. There is
now a yawning gap, about =A33bn, between the offer made by Lloyds TSB and
HBOS's stock market capitalisation. This is the share price's way of tellin=
g
us that it doesn't think the takeover is going to happen.

Both boards insist the deal will go ahead, but shareholders may have other
ideas. Which is a shame, because the creation of Lloyds-TSB-HBOS would help
perform the much-needed service of consolidating a bloated industry,
clearing out thousands of unwanted bankers, and ridding our high streets of
too many branches. It baffles me that we're closing Post Offices (2,500 out
of 14,000 to go) and yet we have a multiplicity of banks.

I recently visited Kingston-upon-Thames, where there is a blight of banks i=
n
the centre. On one street alone, there were five or six. I checked online
and discovered that in this one wealthy town there are three Barclays, two
HSBCs, plus branches of Royal Bank of Scotland, Halifax, Cheltenham &
Gloucester, Alliance & Leicester, Northern Rock, Bradford & Bingley, Lloyds
TSB, Co-operative Bank, Abbey, NatWest, Household Bank, and Beneficial
Finance =96 I may have missed a couple.

This, perhaps, will surprise you, but traditional banking =96 collecting
retail deposits and making loans to ordinary customers =96 is barely
profitable. Compared with the potential gains from a day at the
currency-swap races, or a night in the derivatives casino, current accounts
are cold potatoes. That is why bonus-hungry executives, at what we used to
think of as boring banks, were so keen to spin the red-hot wheel of fortune=
.


In these troubled times, protecting customers, especially depositors, is th=
e
right thing to do. The Government should extend the guarantee it has given
to Northern Rock to all bank deposits. Beyond that, however, Britain's
over-banked economy needs a Malthusian cull.

from
http://malaysia.news.yahoo.com/rtrs/20080928/tbs-brazil-us-crisis-7318940.h=
tml
Brazil's Lula calls US bailout plan unfair to poor Reuters - Monday,
September 29

BRASILIA, Sept 28 - Brazilian President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva blamed th=
e
United States for the global financial crisis and said its financial bailou=
t
plan was unfair to poor people.
ADVERTISEMENT

<http://sg.ard.yahoo.com/SIG=3D150e7u5ng/M=3D690130.13013903.13221092.54752=
89/D=3Dmy_news/S=3D2022385116:LREC/Y=3DMY/EXP=3D1222686368/L=3DSBZN1XxsfeqN=
pMiPSMRtxQAUTPDtKEjgmoMAApzA/B=3DwFlzHXxseNI-/J=3D1222679168140382/A=3D5470=
578/R=3D2/id=3Dnoscript/SIG=3D119lqgt2l/*http://malaysia.images.search.yaho=
o.com>

U.S. lawmakers on Sunday were set to sign off on a deal to create a $700
billion government fund to buy bad debt from ailing banks in a bid to stem =
a
credit crisis threatening the global economy.

"They want to help the banks and not help the poor," Lula said late on
Saturday in Sao Paulo during a campaign rally ahead of Oct. 5 municipal
elections.

"Why give $700 billion to the banks and no money to the poor guys who lost
their houses," Lula asked, according to local media. He referred to the
troubled U.S. housing market.

The former factory worker, who obtained record approval ratings this month,
said the United States had the primary responsibility to fix a crisis with
global repercussions that it had caused.

"I'm not at fault if they turned their economy into a casino," Lula said in
reference to accusations that lax U.S. financial regulations worsened the
crisis.

Brazil was in a better position to withstand the crisis than it was years
ago, the former union leader said.

"I don't want to say we're at ease but ... today we depend less on the
United States for our exports," Lula said.

Brazil's economy is growing by more than 5 percent annually but is expected
to slow to around 4 percent growth next year. A few Brazilian exporters
announced last week large derivatives losses related to currency
fluctuations caused by the global financial crisis.

'Un-American' Bailout, Paulson Should Have Quit, Gingrich Says
<http://us.mc589.mail.yahoo.com/mc/compose?to=3D&subject=3DABC%20News:%20Po=
litical%20Radar%20--%20%27Un-American%27%20Bailout,%20Paulson%20Should%20Ha=

ticalradar/2008/09/un-american-pla.html>

September 28, 2008 12:46 PM

ABC News' Tahman Bradley and Arnab Datta Report: Former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., on Sunday described Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson's
request for billions of dollars to buy debt from struggling Wall Street
financial firms as "un-American" and said the secretary should have stepped
down.

Gingrich even expressed concern with Paulson's connections to Wall Street.
The treasury secretary served as the chairman of a major global investment
banking and securities firm before joining the Bush administration.

"You have the former Chairman of Goldman Sachs asking for 700 billion
dollars, and in his initial request, asking for it in such an un-American
way that I think he should have resigned," said Gingrich. "I think Paulson
has terminally misunderstood the nature of the American system. Not just no
review, no judicial review, no congressional accountability. Give me 700
billion dollars, 700 BILLION dollars! 'I'll be glad to spend it for you.'
That's a centralization of power that is totally un-American."

from http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081004/ap_on_re_us/ike_lives_lost
Islanders who insisted on staying died in Ike

 By MONICA RHOR, Associated Press Writer *Sat Oct 4, 1:58 PM ET*

GALVESTON, Texas - The final hours brought the awful realization to victims
of Hurricane Ike that they had waited too long. This storm wasn't like the
others, the ones that left nothing worse than a harrowing tale to tell.

George Helmond, a hardy Galveston salt, watched the water rise and told a
buddy: I was born on this island and I'll die on this island.

Gail Ettenger, a free spirit who adopted the Bolivar Peninsula as her home
15 years ago, told a friend in a last phone call: I really messed up this
time.

Within hours, the old salt and the free spirit were gone as the powerful
Category 2 hurricane wracked the Texas Gulf Coast on Sept. 13, flattening
houses, obliterating entire towns and claiming at least 33 lives.

The dead =97 as young as 4, as old as 79 =97 included lifelong Galvestonian=
s
firmly rooted on the island and transplants drawn by the quiet of coastal
living.

Seven people drowned in a storm surge that moved in earlier and with more
ferocity than expected. Nine others died in the grimy, sweaty aftermath,
when lack of power and medicine exacted its toll. Eleven people were
poisoned by carbon monoxide or killed in fires from the generators they use=
d
in their own attempts to survive.

Hundreds of people remain missing three weeks after Ike's assault on Texas.
Local and city officials are no longer keeping their own count of missing
residents, and the estimate varies wildly from one agency to another.

According to the nonprofit Laura Recovery Center, about 300 people are
missing. Of those, about 200 from Galveston. However, the number "goes up
and down by the minute" as people call in to remove or add names, cautioned
executive director Bob Walcutt.

Some vanished during the evacuation of towns in the storm's path. Many were
last heard in desperate, last-ditch calls for help.

Immediately after the hurricane, Galveston officials conducted door-to-door
searches for survivors and possible victims. But the city is no longer
taking an active role in the search, city spokeswoman Alicia Cahill said.

Instead, search teams of sheriff's deputies, volunteer firefighters and
special K-9 search and recovery units have been using airboats and
all-terrain vehicles to sift through debris fields, tangled and fetid
marshlands, and the rubble left behind by Ike.

Bodies could have been tossed anywhere in the marshes, where thickets of
trees are littered with the contents of houses. Refrigerators, office
chairs, and television sets are scattered everywhere __ in the mud, in
bushes, on treetops.

"We are definitely looking and are going to do anything we can to find them=
,
but there may not be any answers to be given," said Galveston County
emergency management spokesman Colin Rizzo. "There are definitely going to
be people from Hurricane Ike that are never found."

_____

Gail Ettenger stumbled upon her house in Gilchrist by accident. But once sh=
e
saw the site on the bay side of Bolivar Peninsula, she knew she would never
leave.

Ettenger, a native of New Jersey, instilled the house with her own energy
and style. The 58-year-old's garden bloomed with vibrant birds-of-paradise.

And Reba, an 11-year-old Great Dane hobbled by arthritis, was her baby.
Ettenger loved to treat the dog to dinners of chicken and roast beef,
recalled JoAnne Burks, Ettenger's neighbor and close friend.

Ettenger, a chemist at ExxonMobil, didn't evacuate, reasoning that her hous=
e
had weathered Hurricane Rita in 2005 without a problem. She also did not
want to leave Reba, who could no longer climb into Ettenger's Jeep.

Burks and her husband pleaded with Ettenger to change her mind. But she
insisted.

Hours before Ike made landfall, Ettenger knew she had made the wrong choice=
.
She called Burks and described the water pushing up under her feet, the
propane tanks and other household items drifting by her windows, and
wondered which would float better: her Jeep or her house.

Her voice was shaky with fear, Burks said.

Burks spent the next 10 days searching for her friend, calling local, count=
y
and state officials without success. She tried the American Red Cross, FEMA=
,
even private investigators.

"I didn't want her to wind up like the victims of Katrina, who were never
found or identified," Burks said.

Ettenger's body was found Sept. 23, tossed on a debris field in a Chambers
County marsh about 10 miles from her house.

Amid the muck and remnants of homes, Burks found a pink leather collar. The
name Reba was spelled out in rhinestones.

_____

At 72, George Helmond had ridden out many storms and thought he could take
on Ike, too, neighbor Don Hanson said. "A lot of old Galvestonians are like
that."

Helmond had been one of the first residents of Sydnor Lane, which overlooks
a bayou on one side and a golf course on the other. A retired electrician,
Helmond was a die-hard fisherman, a dove hunter and straight-shooter
intensely proud of his Galveston roots.

Around 10 a.m., Helmond called Hanson, who had already left, to say the
water had already slipped over the road and toward his house. The street =
=97
the only way out of the neighborhood =97 was already impassable.

At 9:30 p.m., Helmond and Hanson talked for the last time. By then, the
water had pummeled through Helmond's garage, crushing the doors and
submerging his Cadillac. Hanson begged his friend to grab a life vest at hi=
s
house or to seek shelter there.

But at 2:30 a.m., for reasons no one knows, Helmond got in his pickup truck
and drove off at the height of Ike's fury.

Neighbors found Helmond's body the next day inside the truck, which had
slammed into the white golf course fence. The windshield was shattered.

Helmond's home suffered little damage. The water had reached above the
first-floor garage, but not inside the house.

"If he had stayed home and hadn't gone out, he'd be OK, but he panicked,"
said Hanson, 66. "Life goes on, but I will miss a good friend and I will
think about him."

_____

Even as Ike bore down on Texas, Jim Devine refused to leave his
cream-colored house within sight of the bay in San Leon. Devine had moved t=
o
the fishing town after retiring and loved the tranquil way of life there,
neighbors said.

The 76-year-old Devine drowned when Ike sent water barreling through his
house, picking him off the second-story porch and dropping him a block away=
.
Days later, Devine's empty home still bore the scars of the storm =97
shattered windows, twisted wood, and his boat, the Seabar, jammed under the
front steps.

His daughter left a warning and a memorial in orange spray paint: "Jim
Devine. No Trespassing."

_____

Port Bolivar held special meaning for 79-year-old Marian Violet Arrambide.
She met her husband there during World War II. Many years later, he built
the beach house where they could retire.

Arrambide, a retired nurse suffering the onset of dementia, lived with her
daughter, Magdalena Strickland, and nephew, Shane Williams, in that beach
house before Ike struck.

All three have been missing since the morning of Sept. 12, just as Ike bega=
n
to come ashore.

"My sister said 'I'm walking out the door in a hurry. Everything's taken
care of, I'll see you in a few hours.' That was it," said son Raul
Arrambide, describing a 6:15 a.m. phone call.

Since then, Arrambide has had little luck getting help or information.
Instead, Arrambide said, he's been passed from one agency to another.

"They send you back and forth until you're worn out," said Arrambide, his
voice showing the strain of the last weeks.

After five days with no word and no answers, Arrambide borrowed a boat to
search the area himself, but sheriff's deputies turned people away. He
finally found a local contractor who is helping search for missing
residents. That man found his relatives' vehicles, which had been washed of=
f
the road into a tree grove.

"I want to keep the hope that they are still alive, but by not hearing from
any of them, that hope is getting smaller and smaller," he said. "They
helped people all their lives. They did not deserve to go this way."

from
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112269/Why-propping=
-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html
Why propping up banks will not rescue a debauched financial system
Confession time. As 228 Representatives in Congress voted against Hank
Paulson's bail-out plan on Monday, I was cheering them on.

By Jeff Randall
Last Updated: 1:14PM BST 01 Oct 2008

Comments 127<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112269=
/Why-propping-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html#co=
mments>|
Comment
on this article<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112=
269/Why-propping-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html=
#postComment>

At last, there were public figures prepared to reject the political and
financial blackmail of a debased White House-Wall Street elite.

This is an unfashionable view; it runs counter to The Daily Telegraph's
editorial line. But the hard-sell of President Bush and the US Treasury
Secretary felt too much like the pressure patter of a door-to-door hawker.
Their message was crude: "Trust us. You are in a terrible place. Only we ca=
n
get you out of this mess. No need to check the details. Hurry now, or it
will be too late. Here's a pen. There's the dotted line. Just sign."

But with the President's ratings so low, few would let him leave the House
with anything more than small change. Congress asked, not unreasonably: "If
you guys know so much about banking, how come we are in such trouble?"

Having spent most of the year telling America, contrary to mounting
evidence, that the US economy was just dandy, Mr Bush's credibility is
threadbare. When making statements, he's beginning to look as if he doesn't
even believe himself. As for Mr Paulson, his long association with the
jackpot culture of Goldman Sachs is, in the eyes of many outsiders, a gilde=
d
millstone.

Predictably, the refuseniks have been pilloried as ill-informed nihilists.
They have been lambasted for failing to understand the consequences of thei=
r
actions. They are, according to the Big Bail-out Brigade, condemning the
rest of us to be buried alive in the rubble of a disintegrating banking
system.

Try a different take. Yes, the West's financial infrastructure is in severe
distress. Yes, more banks are going to crumble. Yes, there will be a
recession. But allocating $700bn (it would almost certainly turn out to be
more) to a clean-up programme for toxic assets, in effect socialising the
poison of private greed, has no merit other than to delay the inevitable. N=
o
amount of federal cash can rewind the X-rated horror video.

There is a conspiracy of bankers and politicians whose self-interest is
masquerading as sophisticated policy. They want us to believe that they hav=
e
the keys to salvation. I have not seen a scrap of evidence to confirm this.

There will, of course, be a renewed effort in Washington to push through a
package of national deliverance. Concessions will be made. The US taxpayer
will be offered improved terms. And, having made their point, having stood
up for "traditional American values", some of the naysayers in the House of
Representatives will cross over, enabling a deal to be done. Their
consciences will be salved, but the crisis will not be solved.

Meanwhile, in Britain, the ban on short-selling bank shares has done nothin=
g
to make them more attractive to investors. Having blamed hedge funds for
driving down the price of supposedly healthy businesses, officials must be
at a loss to explain why bank shares keep falling.

Halifax-Bank of Scotland dropped another 14pc yesterday to 122p. There is
now a yawning gap, about =A33bn, between the offer made by Lloyds TSB and
HBOS's stock market capitalisation. This is the share price's way of tellin=
g
us that it doesn't think the takeover is going to happen.

Both boards insist the deal will go ahead, but shareholders may have other
ideas. Which is a shame, because the creation of Lloyds-TSB-HBOS would help
perform the much-needed service of consolidating a bloated industry,
clearing out thousands of unwanted bankers, and ridding our high streets of
too many branches. It baffles me that we're closing Post Offices (2,500 out
of 14,000 to go) and yet we have a multiplicity of banks.

I recently visited Kingston-upon-Thames, where there is a blight of banks i=
n
the centre. On one street alone, there were five or six. I checked online
and discovered that in this one wealthy town there are three Barclays, two
HSBCs, plus branches of Royal Bank of Scotland, Halifax, Cheltenham &
Gloucester, Alliance & Leicester, Northern Rock, Bradford & Bingley, Lloyds
TSB, Co-operative Bank, Abbey, NatWest, Household Bank, and Beneficial
Finance =96 I may have missed a couple.

This, perhaps, will surprise you, but traditional banking =96 collecting
retail deposits and making loans to ordinary customers =96 is barely
profitable. Compared with the potential gains from a day at the
currency-swap races, or a night in the derivatives casino, current accounts
are cold potatoes. That is why bonus-hungry executives, at what we used to
think of as boring banks, were so keen to spin the red-hot wheel of fortune=
.


In these troubled times, protecting customers, especially depositors, is th=
e
right thing to do. The Government should extend the guarantee it has given
to Northern Rock to all bank deposits. Beyond that, however, Britain's
over-banked economy needs a Malthusian cull.

from http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081004/ap_on_re_us/ike_lives_lost
Islanders who insisted on staying died in Ike

 By MONICA RHOR, Associated Press Writer *Sat Oct 4, 1:58 PM ET*

GALVESTON, Texas - The final hours brought the awful realization to victims
of Hurricane Ike that they had waited too long. This storm wasn't like the
others, the ones that left nothing worse than a harrowing tale to tell.

George Helmond, a hardy Galveston salt, watched the water rise and told a
buddy: I was born on this island and I'll die on this island.

Gail Ettenger, a free spirit who adopted the Bolivar Peninsula as her home
15 years ago, told a friend in a last phone call: I really messed up this
time.

Within hours, the old salt and the free spirit were gone as the powerful
Category 2 hurricane wracked the Texas Gulf Coast on Sept. 13, flattening
houses, obliterating entire towns and claiming at least 33 lives.

The dead =97 as young as 4, as old as 79 =97 included lifelong Galvestonian=
s
firmly rooted on the island and transplants drawn by the quiet of coastal
living.

Seven people drowned in a storm surge that moved in earlier and with more
ferocity than expected. Nine others died in the grimy, sweaty aftermath,
when lack of power and medicine exacted its toll. Eleven people were
poisoned by carbon monoxide or killed in fires from the generators they use=
d
in their own attempts to survive.

Hundreds of people remain missing three weeks after Ike's assault on Texas.
Local and city officials are no longer keeping their own count of missing
residents, and the estimate varies wildly from one agency to another.

According to the nonprofit Laura Recovery Center, about 300 people are
missing. Of those, about 200 from Galveston. However, the number "goes up
and down by the minute" as people call in to remove or add names, cautioned
executive director Bob Walcutt.

Some vanished during the evacuation of towns in the storm's path. Many were
last heard in desperate, last-ditch calls for help.

Immediately after the hurricane, Galveston officials conducted door-to-door
searches for survivors and possible victims. But the city is no longer
taking an active role in the search, city spokeswoman Alicia Cahill said.

Instead, search teams of sheriff's deputies, volunteer firefighters and
special K-9 search and recovery units have been using airboats and
all-terrain vehicles to sift through debris fields, tangled and fetid
marshlands, and the rubble left behind by Ike.

Bodies could have been tossed anywhere in the marshes, where thickets of
trees are littered with the contents of houses. Refrigerators, office
chairs, and television sets are scattered everywhere __ in the mud, in
bushes, on treetops.

"We are definitely looking and are going to do anything we can to find them=
,
but there may not be any answers to be given," said Galveston County
emergency management spokesman Colin Rizzo. "There are definitely going to
be people from Hurricane Ike that are never found."

_____

Gail Ettenger stumbled upon her house in Gilchrist by accident. But once sh=
e
saw the site on the bay side of Bolivar Peninsula, she knew she would never
leave.

Ettenger, a native of New Jersey, instilled the house with her own energy
and style. The 58-year-old's garden bloomed with vibrant birds-of-paradise.

And Reba, an 11-year-old Great Dane hobbled by arthritis, was her baby.
Ettenger loved to treat the dog to dinners of chicken and roast beef,
recalled JoAnne Burks, Ettenger's neighbor and close friend.

Ettenger, a chemist at ExxonMobil, didn't evacuate, reasoning that her hous=
e
had weathered Hurricane Rita in 2005 without a problem. She also did not
want to leave Reba, who could no longer climb into Ettenger's Jeep.

Burks and her husband pleaded with Ettenger to change her mind. But she
insisted.

Hours before Ike made landfall, Ettenger knew she had made the wrong choice=
.
She called Burks and described the water pushing up under her feet, the
propane tanks and other household items drifting by her windows, and
wondered which would float better: her Jeep or her house.

Her voice was shaky with fear, Burks said.

Burks spent the next 10 days searching for her friend, calling local, count=
y
and state officials without success. She tried the American Red Cross, FEMA=
,
even private investigators.

"I didn't want her to wind up like the victims of Katrina, who were never
found or identified," Burks said.

Ettenger's body was found Sept. 23, tossed on a debris field in a Chambers
County marsh about 10 miles from her house.

Amid the muck and remnants of homes, Burks found a pink leather collar. The
name Reba was spelled out in rhinestones.

_____

At 72, George Helmond had ridden out many storms and thought he could take
on Ike, too, neighbor Don Hanson said. "A lot of old Galvestonians are like
that."

Helmond had been one of the first residents of Sydnor Lane, which overlooks
a bayou on one side and a golf course on the other. A retired electrician,
Helmond was a die-hard fisherman, a dove hunter and straight-shooter
intensely proud of his Galveston roots.

Around 10 a.m., Helmond called Hanson, who had already left, to say the
water had already slipped over the road and toward his house. The street =
=97
the only way out of the neighborhood =97 was already impassable.

At 9:30 p.m., Helmond and Hanson talked for the last time. By then, the
water had pummeled through Helmond's garage, crushing the doors and
submerging his Cadillac. Hanson begged his friend to grab a life vest at hi=
s
house or to seek shelter there.

But at 2:30 a.m., for reasons no one knows, Helmond got in his pickup truck
and drove off at the height of Ike's fury.

Neighbors found Helmond's body the next day inside the truck, which had
slammed into the white golf course fence. The windshield was shattered.

Helmond's home suffered little damage. The water had reached above the
first-floor garage, but not inside the house.

"If he had stayed home and hadn't gone out, he'd be OK, but he panicked,"
said Hanson, 66. "Life goes on, but I will miss a good friend and I will
think about him."

_____

Even as Ike bore down on Texas, Jim Devine refused to leave his
cream-colored house within sight of the bay in San Leon. Devine had moved t=
o
the fishing town after retiring and loved the tranquil way of life there,
neighbors said.

The 76-year-old Devine drowned when Ike sent water barreling through his
house, picking him off the second-story porch and dropping him a block away=
.
Days later, Devine's empty home still bore the scars of the storm =97
shattered windows, twisted wood, and his boat, the Seabar, jammed under the
front steps.

His daughter left a warning and a memorial in orange spray paint: "Jim
Devine. No Trespassing."

_____

Port Bolivar held special meaning for 79-year-old Marian Violet Arrambide.
She met her husband there during World War II. Many years later, he built
the beach house where they could retire.

Arrambide, a retired nurse suffering the onset of dementia, lived with her
daughter, Magdalena Strickland, and nephew, Shane Williams, in that beach
house before Ike struck.

All three have been missing since the morning of Sept. 12, just as Ike bega=
n
to come ashore.

"My sister said 'I'm walking out the door in a hurry. Everything's taken
care of, I'll see you in a few hours.' That was it," said son Raul
Arrambide, describing a 6:15 a.m. phone call.

Since then, Arrambide has had little luck getting help or information.
Instead, Arrambide said, he's been passed from one agency to another.

"They send you back and forth until you're worn out," said Arrambide, his
voice showing the strain of the last weeks.

After five days with no word and no answers, Arrambide borrowed a boat to
search the area himself, but sheriff's deputies turned people away. He
finally found a local contractor who is helping search for missing
residents. That man found his relatives' vehicles, which had been washed of=
f
the road into a tree grove.

"I want to keep the hope that they are still alive, but by not hearing from
any of them, that hope is getting smaller and smaller," he said. "They
helped people all their lives. They did not deserve to go this way."
