from
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112269/Why-propping=
-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html
Why propping up banks will not rescue a debauched financial system
Confession time. As 228 Representatives in Congress voted against Hank
Paulson's bail-out plan on Monday, I was cheering them on.

By Jeff Randall
Last Updated: 1:14PM BST 01 Oct 2008

Comments 127<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112269=
/Why-propping-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html#co=
mments>|
Comment
on this article<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/jeffrandall/3112=
269/Why-propping-up-banks-will-not-rescue-a-debauched-financial-system.html=
#postComment>

At last, there were public figures prepared to reject the political and
financial blackmail of a debased White House-Wall Street elite.

This is an unfashionable view; it runs counter to The Daily Telegraph's
editorial line. But the hard-sell of President Bush and the US Treasury
Secretary felt too much like the pressure patter of a door-to-door hawker.
Their message was crude: "Trust us. You are in a terrible place. Only we ca=
n
get you out of this mess. No need to check the details. Hurry now, or it
will be too late. Here's a pen. There's the dotted line. Just sign."

But with the President's ratings so low, few would let him leave the House
with anything more than small change. Congress asked, not unreasonably: "If
you guys know so much about banking, how come we are in such trouble?"

Having spent most of the year telling America, contrary to mounting
evidence, that the US economy was just dandy, Mr Bush's credibility is
threadbare. When making statements, he's beginning to look as if he doesn't
even believe himself. As for Mr Paulson, his long association with the
jackpot culture of Goldman Sachs is, in the eyes of many outsiders, a gilde=
d
millstone.

Predictably, the refuseniks have been pilloried as ill-informed nihilists.
They have been lambasted for failing to understand the consequences of thei=
r
actions. They are, according to the Big Bail-out Brigade, condemning the
rest of us to be buried alive in the rubble of a disintegrating banking
system.

Try a different take. Yes, the West's financial infrastructure is in severe
distress. Yes, more banks are going to crumble. Yes, there will be a
recession. But allocating $700bn (it would almost certainly turn out to be
more) to a clean-up programme for toxic assets, in effect socialising the
poison of private greed, has no merit other than to delay the inevitable. N=
o
amount of federal cash can rewind the X-rated horror video.

There is a conspiracy of bankers and politicians whose self-interest is
masquerading as sophisticated policy. They want us to believe that they hav=
e
the keys to salvation. I have not seen a scrap of evidence to confirm this.

There will, of course, be a renewed effort in Washington to push through a
package of national deliverance. Concessions will be made. The US taxpayer
will be offered improved terms. And, having made their point, having stood
up for "traditional American values", some of the naysayers in the House of
Representatives will cross over, enabling a deal to be done. Their
consciences will be salved, but the crisis will not be solved.

Meanwhile, in Britain, the ban on short-selling bank shares has done nothin=
g
to make them more attractive to investors. Having blamed hedge funds for
driving down the price of supposedly healthy businesses, officials must be
at a loss to explain why bank shares keep falling.

Halifax-Bank of Scotland dropped another 14pc yesterday to 122p. There is
now a yawning gap, about =A33bn, between the offer made by Lloyds TSB and
HBOS's stock market capitalisation. This is the share price's way of tellin=
g
us that it doesn't think the takeover is going to happen.

Both boards insist the deal will go ahead, but shareholders may have other
ideas. Which is a shame, because the creation of Lloyds-TSB-HBOS would help
perform the much-needed service of consolidating a bloated industry,
clearing out thousands of unwanted bankers, and ridding our high streets of
too many branches. It baffles me that we're closing Post Offices (2,500 out
of 14,000 to go) and yet we have a multiplicity of banks.

I recently visited Kingston-upon-Thames, where there is a blight of banks i=
n
the centre. On one street alone, there were five or six. I checked online
and discovered that in this one wealthy town there are three Barclays, two
HSBCs, plus branches of Royal Bank of Scotland, Halifax, Cheltenham &
Gloucester, Alliance & Leicester, Northern Rock, Bradford & Bingley, Lloyds
TSB, Co-operative Bank, Abbey, NatWest, Household Bank, and Beneficial
Finance =96 I may have missed a couple.

This, perhaps, will surprise you, but traditional banking =96 collecting
retail deposits and making loans to ordinary customers =96 is barely
profitable. Compared with the potential gains from a day at the
currency-swap races, or a night in the derivatives casino, current accounts
are cold potatoes. That is why bonus-hungry executives, at what we used to
think of as boring banks, were so keen to spin the red-hot wheel of fortune=
.


In these troubled times, protecting customers, especially depositors, is th=
e
right thing to do. The Government should extend the guarantee it has given
to Northern Rock to all bank deposits. Beyond that, however, Britain's
over-banked economy needs a Malthusian cull.

This week the US Treasury released $1.48 trillion dollars, (3x times what
we've spent in the last 5 and a half years in Iraq), of taxpayer money to
Wall Street, (there was a shadow bail-out of $630 billion dollars that got
practically no press attention
http://news.google.com/news?hl=en&tab=wn&ned=&ie=UTF-8&ncl=1252614839 ), on
top of the $850 billion dollars that everyone knows about.

All three major stock markets closed on Friday below the level they were at
the day George Bush became President in January of 2001.

http://silencedmajority.blogs.com/silenced_majority_portal/2008/10/clinton-vs-bush.html

What does this mean for you, the average taxpayer?

Annual per capita income in the United States is currently $46 thousand
dollars and there are 138 million taxpayers, so $1.48 trillion divided by
138 million people averages out to just under $11,000 dollars per person, or
just under 25% of your annual income.

$11K a year averages out to the first $40 dollars you make at work each day
going to pay for this. For those making $46K it reduces your earnings from
$185 a day to $145 a day. If you're a minimum wage worker at $6.55 an hour
that will leave you with $12 at the end of the day, which will also be
taxed.

If you add the $1.5 trillion dollars that we also owe the Chinese you can
double those figures to 50%.

This does not include the $3 trillion dollar Federal Budget or interest
payments on US debt, or the monies that need to be spent on
rent/mortgages/gas/food by the average person. Add all that up too, and what
we're going to spend in Iraq, might as well, and one rapidly begins to
approach zero percent. Zero, as in nothing.

100 years ago the citizens of Russia under the Czars endured taxation rates
of 90% before they got fed up and had enough, it will be interesting to see
in the coming few years if American citizens will be as forgiving as
compliant as they were.

One positive thing we have learned from Bush and Palin being the polarizing
political figures that they are is that we now know, that no matter what
happens, and how much they abuse their own people, and take away from them
every single last thing that they have, leaders like that will always have
the full and blind support of 1/3rd of the population, no matter how much
direct evidence of how their own lives and livelihoods are being destroyed
outright in front of them presents itself to them.

Nope, these poor, crazy, deluded, willfully ignorant people will not only
swallow as much garbage as can be mercilessly shoveled down their throats by
their leaders, they will defend these power mad people to the ends of the
earth, vociferously attacking those that are trying to help them see this,
and then come back and ask for seconds.

I see evidence of that everyday on lists like this and all over the web
these days and it would be funny, instead of being the sad, shameful pity
that it is. Not to mention outright dangerous to the other 70% of the
population. Czarist/Stalinist Russia, Nazi Germany and Mao's China all came
to a very bad end and millions upon millions of people were senselessly
murdered in the process of fulfilling their leader's insane ambitions.

Is that something any Good American wants to have happen here?

On Fri, Oct 3, 2008 at 5:31 PM, <electrofunk138@hotmail.com> wrote:

>
> That 2nd one is a bitch - he really makes some clearly on point comparisons
> between the USSR and the USA. Scary shit.

.

I spent a great deal of my childhood and adolescence visiting relatives that
were trapped behind the Soviet Iron Curtain in East Germany and other
Communist countries under Soviet domination and at the time everybody knew
that the Soviet was going to collapse, with the US to follow roughly the
same path 20 years later.

Turns out they were right on both accounts and Orlov pretty much nails it in
his piece. he's just got a book out on the subject and he goes much more in
depth than the PowerPoint presentation here on his blog, this article is a
good place to start: http://docs.google.com/View?docid=dtxqwqr_20dc52sm

Here's his blog link:
http://cluborlov.blogspot.com/2006/05/dmitry-orlov.html

One indication I've been trying to point out to people in terms of
similarities between East Germany and the US is that in the last ten years
the citizens of the US have become just as fearful of the police as their
East German counterparts used to be.

That's more of a social indicator of bad shit, than an economic one, I know,
but I find it chilling as well.
.

> JOSH WINK
>
> An American producer who simultaneously possessed European hit singles, a
> major-label album contract, consistent contact with the dance mainstream,
> plus the requisite underground credentials, Josh Wink appeared to lack for
> nothing at the peak of his success in the mid-'90s. Part of the East
> Coast/Philadelphia dance scene, Wink recorded three techno monsters out of
> his bedroom studio (as Wink, Winx, and Size 9) that topped charts in Europe
> during 1995 and saw him anointed as a dance poster boy, easily recognized by
> his ruddy good looks and flowing blond dreadlocks. Hardly the techno
> kingpin, however, Wink's espousal of a vegan lifestyle and his defiantly
> anti-drug ideals made him something of a unique personality in the
> hedonistic world of dance music.
>
> After being turned on by punk rock in the '70s, Josh Winkelman was inspired
> by a diverse group of dance-styled artists during the 1980s -- ranging from
> Depeche Mode to Kraftwerk to Run-D.M.C. -- and began working with a
> Philadelphia-based mobile DJ service from the age of 13. After he met up
> with a fellow DJ, King Britt, at one party, the duo began recording. One of
> their first productions, 1990's "Tribal Confusion" by E-Culture, was
> released on New York's Strictly Rhythm Records and became a success in
> America's exploding club/rave scene, which Wink and Britt soundtracked by
> DJing at events around the country. Wink had also recorded for Nervous,
> another vaunted East Coast dance label, before forming Ovum Records in late
> 1994 with Britt.
>
> Ovum and Wink had an international club hit right out of the box with 1995's
> "Liquid Summer"; the single led to Wink recording for a maze of European
> labels. During 1995, he recorded "Don't Laugh" by Winx, "I'm Ready" by Size
> 9, and "Higher State of Consciousness" by Winks, all of which topped
> European dance charts and even made several pop charts despite their debt to
> hard-edged acid trance. The singles were collected along with new material
> for his 1996 debut album, Left Above the Clouds, and released as Winx. The
> major labels came calling in 1997, and Wink decided to sign not only himself
> but the entire Ovum Recordings label to a deal with Columbia. After
> recording with King Britt, Nine Inch Nails' Trent Reznor, poet Ursula
> Rucker, and Philly mod punks the Interpreters, Wink released his proper
> album debut, Herehear, in 1998; the mix album Profound Sounds, Vol. 1
> followed the next year. He spent much of his time contributing to Ovum acts
> King Britt and Jamie Myerson, but by 2003 he had released both a second
> volume in Profound Sounds as well as his second production album, 20 to 20.
> Profound Sounds, Vol. 3 appeared in 2006.
>
>

>
>
> SPEEDY J
>
> After fifteen years of techno Speedy J has come full circle. He's making
> techno again. But what a wide circle it was, and how fickle the trodden
> path. Over the years he has collaborated with video-artists, filmmakers and
> advertisers, made the pioneering DVD Umfeld and has continuously been
> pushing the boundaries of electronic & experimental dance music. "I just
> constantly want to do new things," he explains. Most recently this has been
> exemplified in his new label Electric Deluxe, which will issue digital
> releases only.
>
> Jochem Paap (the Rotterdam artist owes the nickname Speedy J to his DJ
> skills) is unanimously considered to be one of the first techno producers to
> come from the Benelux. Someone who, together with people like Laurent
> Garnier, Aphex Twin and his good friend Richie Hawtin, helped raise the
> genre just after it had escaped the Detroit delivery room. But while techno
> develops into a multi-faced monster that still dominates many dance floors
> worldwide, Jochem Paap, after the albums G Spot (1993) and Ginger (1995),
> turns left and heads for more exciting places. On Public Energy No. 1 (1997)
> and A Shocking Hobby (2000) the sound wizard exchanges flowing, harmonious
> techno for a much more complex sound, filled with colliding samples,
> crackling rhythms and tremendously thrilling turns. This is the time when
> electronic dance music becomes profound and contemporaries like Autechre,
> Funkstrung and Aphex Twin have their machinery perform ever more
> complicated tricks. During those days Jochem Paap converts his studio into a
> modular system, which wins him the sought-after freedom. Suddenly everything
> is possible with sound. And if an idea turns out to be more unruly than
> expected he simply looks for software with which to crack the code of his
> ideas after all. He discusses sound like graphic designers discuss form,
> speaking of "contrast" and "depth" instead of a little ruffle here or a
> bass-lick there. "I am sometimes really chiselling at sound," he reports
> from his futuristic studio located in one of the famous cube quarters in
> Rotterdam. "In essence my work is about stylising rather than composing."
> Stylising is his strong point, he feels. "I might not be a brilliant
> musician but I do know very well how to fashion my ideas into a particular
> form. Out of a few components I try to make something distinctive."
>
> Although Jochem Paap enjoys chiselling at sounds alone in his cube studio
> for hours on end, he is anything but an einzelgnger. Such is evident in his
> Collabs-project, through which he has been collaborating with various techno
> musicians since 2004. The German Chris Liebing and Paap collaborate most
> fruitfully. Together they play DJ sets in clubs for hours and released the
> album Metalism in 2005, a ruthless techno-bomb more powerful than the
> bunkerbusters of the American army. "Working with someone else provides you
> with new insights," says Paap. "Collabs offers us both the possibility to
> explore corners which we wouldn't so readily visit as solo artists. Collabs
> prospers on the dance floor and after extensive wandering Paap's recent solo
> material brings him back to the clubs. "Right now I feel very strongly about
> making and releasing techno. My heart is really in dance music after all."
>
>

>
>
> DRUMCELL
>
> Founder of Droid Recordings and co-founder of Droid Behavior, Drumcell has
> been one of techno's greatest allies in Southern California in recent times.
>
>
> A graduate of the Musician's Institute and a long-time performer at parties
> in Southern California, Drumcell has been influenced by music from his
> earliest years. After being exposed to raves in the early 90s, He grew
> addicted to the sounds of acid house, techno, in its many forms, and
> industrial. It was not long before he was copping turntables to satisfy his
> vinyl fetish. By the early age of 14 he was playing in various local bands,
> and through out the rest of his teenage years, cut his teeth-producing hip
> hop records, dub and various forms of electronic music on Los Angeles based
> underground labels. By combining his Production, DJing and networking skills
> and focusing in on his more mature musical tastes he soon established
> himself as one of the major players in LA's growing techno scene.
> Associating with the members of Acid Circus to form Droid Behavior as an
> event production group and record label was the next logical step to raise
> awareness for techno in the city and to help expose local Artists,
> established djs, and performers from around the country. Over the last 5
> years Drumcell has rocked parties from big to small on a weekly basis in LA
> as well as gigs all over the U.S alongside such names as Kenny Larkin, John
> Tejada, Tim Xavier, Dan Bell, Ben Sims, Adam Beyer, Jeff Mills, Speedy J,
> Richie Hawtin, Mathew Dear, etc. and has also released quite a few heavy
> trax on labels Omniscient, Remains, Heavy Industries, and his own DROID
> Recordings imprint.
>
> Drumcell has been known to keep on the edge of technology and continuously
> pushing the limits to what the future has to offer. He is always in the
> process of developing homebrew software as well as cutting edge hardware
> solution to bring a fresh innovative taste to his production and
> performances. When performing, Drumcell can be seen blurring the lines
> between a live and a DJ set by utilizing tools such as FX processors,
> samplers, drum machines, and other devices to weave a thick blend of acidic
> techno and aggressive but funky minimalist groove to ensure a frenzy amongst
> his listeners. With the state of electronic music in North America leaning
> towards stripped down funk rather then progressive fluff these days, Droid
> has become the center for LA techno and Drumcell remains steadfast in his
> mission of putting this city on the global map.
>
>

> from http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Island
> Crystal Island From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
> Jump to: navigation
> <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Island#column-one>,
> search
> <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Island#searchInput>
> [image: Project of the Crystal
>
Island]<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image:CrystalIslandFoster.jpg>
> <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image:CrystalIslandFoster.jpg>
> Project of the Crystal Island
> 
> *Crystal Island* is a proposed building project in
> Moscow<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moscow>,
> Russia <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russia> that is
> currently planned to
> have around 2,500,000 square metres (27,000,000 square feet)
> of floor space
> and a height of 450 metres (1,300 ft) designed by Norman
>
Foster<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norman_Foster,_Baron_Foster_of_Thames_Bank>
> .[1]
>
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Island#cite_note-Luzhkov-0>
> At
> these dimensions upon completion it would be one of the
> largest
>
structures<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_largest_buildings_in_the_world>(in
> floor space) on earth. The architectural firm behind the
> design is
> Foster
> and Partners
> <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foster_and_Partners>.
> 
> The tent-like superstructure rises to 450 m, and forms a
> breathable "second
> skin" and thermal buffer for the main building, shielding the
> interior
> spaces from Moscow's weather. This second skin will be sealed
> in winter to
> minimise heat losses, and open in summer so that the interior
> can be cooled
> naturally. The building is integrated into a new park, which
> will provide a
> range of activities throughout the year, with cross country
> skiing<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_country_skiing>and
> ice
> skating <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ice_skating> in the
>
winter[2]<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Island#cite_note-foster-1>
> .
> 
> It is stated to have a multitude of cultural, exhibition,
> performance,
> hotel, apartment, retail and office space, as well as an
> international
> school for 500
>
students.[2]<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Island#cite_note-foster-1>
> 
> The building will be powered by built-in solar
> panels<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_panel>and wind
> turbines
>
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wind_turbine>.[3]<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Island#cite_note-2>Efficient
> energy management includes on-site renewable and low-carbon
> energy
>
generation[2]<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Island#cite_note-foster-1>
> .
> 
>
[edit<http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Crystal_Island&action=edit&section=1>
> ] See also
> 
>    - Hyperboloid
> structure<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperboloid_structure>
>    - List of Hyperboloid
>
structures<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hyperboloid_structures>
> 
>

Thanks very much! Sorry if my post came off as a troll - absolutely the
farthest thing from my intention.

I note that shatter did not care for the video either (his remark about
maybe 12 people attending if the like were presented here), so I had not
considered that my post would be taken for trolling, since it did not seem
to be a disagreement with anyone here.

I will definitely try to be more aware of my tone in the future so that my
posts aren't misunderstood.

I posted because I had watched the video and was disturbed by the Nazi-like
elements I saw, particularly so in the "related videos" section - there
seems to be a conscious insertion of Nazi imagery. The skull logo and flags
strongly resemble some SS decorations, the "Y"-shaped logo as a backdrop in
one of the videos is very like the logo of the white-supremacist National
Vanguard - google that, and if you aren't afraid of losing your breakfast,
google "Romanian National Vanguard" - sickening stuff, but it is good to
check out to be reminded just how sick and crazy the world can be.

And there is a connection between _some_  gabba artists and white supremacy,
so it caused some concern for me. We don't want such negative things
inserting themselves into our culture.

Stuff like the Romanian site really makes me appreciate even more the
inclusive, loving, respectful, unifying culture of rave.

Thank you again, and again my apologies if my post came off as a troll. I
will be more thoughtful in the future.

--Panther

drawing connections is narrow minded, as there have been neo-nazi 
influenced on Punk, metal, and country music to name but a few.

I pointed out about 12 people showing up in the bay area because the 
only thing anyone seems to give two shits about is shitty house music 
and of late, canned $59 keyboard drum beats (what some are calling 
minimum techno, and what i would ask is "more techno less minimal you 
lazy fuck").  Trace has become a dirty word because of the zombies that 
practice DJ worship at the alter of Fail.  So, what's left?  Breaks?  I 
can dig that, but then again you get the mass drone of house heads 
bitching about "we want house....  we want house.....  we want house...  
my E is wearing off....."

Not that I'm jaded or anything.

enjoy what they will.  Godwins law was already invoked in your initial 
retort thus it was going to go unanswered, however, since you decided to

Mayor In Russia Says He Can See Sarah Palin Showering =46rom His House


(Provideniya, Russia) Governor Sarah Palin, the Republican Vice =20
Presidential nominee, has said that she can see Russia from her =20
house. Across the Bering Strait in Provideniya Bay sits the town of =20
Provideniya, Russia and its mayor Dimitri Andropov. He says that he =20
can see Palin showering from HIS house. =93And it is very nice.=94

Mayor Andropov added that his small town, like America, is transfixed =20=

with the buxom Governor. =93We have a shower watchman on duty 24/7. And =20=

when the delightful Palin turns on the water and lets down her hair, =20
the alarm sounds, telling everyone to rush to my house for a show. =20
The kids love it.=94

Leonid Andropov, the Mayor=92s brother, said that the ability to see =20
Palin shower has given him and the other men a newfound respect for =20
her. =93She=92s a very thorough cleaner, which is tough when one is =20
dealing with moose guts, wolf blood and oil=85And she doesn=92t have a =20=

mustache, which is just a big plus for us.=94

In a spontaneous Q&A at a Phoenix donut shop, Sarah Palin said that =20
she=92s okay with the Russians watching her shower. =93I=92m flattered. =
And =20
hopefully my cleanliness can inspire them to go after freedom, =20
liberty and democracy...so that they can create jobs, get more =20
freedom and liberty to help the economic job search, then hunt down =20
the terror loving terrorists and change their nation of human people =20
for the better.=94

=93All I heard from that speech was change, and change to us is bad,=94 =20=

said Mayor Andropov. =93Change means John McCain will win the election =20=

and take our water princess to shower in Washington D.C=85We don=92t =
want =20
that to happen=85Everything else Governor Palin said was over our small =20=

town heads. But that=92s okay, because we like to watch Sarah the same =20=

way she likes to watch Saturday Night Live, with the sound turned down.=94=


In other news, Bill Clinton announced his candidacy for Mayor of =20
Provideniya.

 Subject: Re: [sfraves] Lovefest reports...
 From: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
 Date: Tue, October 07, 2008 8:05 am

=20
 OK here's mine...
=20
=20
 Headline: Love Fest Killed Muni
=20
 We couldn't get a sitter so we really only attended the parade part and
briefly went into the festival area itself.  Took Muni from West Portal
to the parade and saw at least 6 full trains packed with ravers before
we jammed ourselves into one.  When we got off at Civic Center it was
pandemonium; there were ravers and weirdos everywhere.  Muni people were
obviously overwhelmed and irritated.
=20
 We got to Market just as the parade approached.  Wow!  Many more floats
this year with bigger sound systems and higher production values on them
as well.  Heard many good tunes as the parade progressed and some, umm,
not so good.  Went over to the SF House float area for a while looking
for Chuck G but no joy,
=20
 Danced for a bit there and the boys picked up on girls.  Tyrone (age 17
mos.) was especially successful.  I thought this one girl in a lime
green dress he was flirting with was going to follow us home.  He used
this pointing move I taught him.  Hilarious.
=20
 The boys got tired after a bit and we had to depart.  Went back into
Muni and the situation was even worse.  Still more ravers coming
downtown from the West Side.  And even the outbound trains were
partially packed with ravers.  Amazing.
=20
 To my surprise there are literally thousands of young rave heads living
out here on the West Side, probably largely SF State kids.  And they
were out in force.  Wow. =20
=20
 Peter

Subject: [sfraves] Recommended Software Application from Google

This application:
http://news.cnet.com/8301-17939_109-10059735-2.html
might be of interest to some of us who get all liquored up and decide to 
post to sfraves.

"Just a quick post to mention a silly (or is it?) experiment that Google has released to the public: Mail Goggles.
This feature is designed to prevent you from sending stupid e-mails in
the small hours, when you're most likely to be inebriated and at risk
of making a complete idiot of yourself.

Don't drink and e-mail.

When enabled, Mail Goggles kicks in at the time you specify (default
is between 10 p.m. and 4 a.m. on Friday and Saturday), and throws five
math problems up on the screen when you press "send." You have a
limited period of time to solve them. If you can answer the questions,
presumably you're of mind sound enough to tell off your boss, or pour
your heart out to your ex-lover.
If you can solve simple math problems even when under the
table, there's an option to ramp up the difficulty of the questions,
but sadly they remain in the arithmetic realm and don't drift into
interesting algebra or calculus.
To activate Mail Goggles, go into Gmail's settings, and turn on Mail
Goggles in the "Labs" tab. Then adjust how and when it works in the
"General" tab."


-- 
San Francisco Bay Guardian's Readers Choice Award Winner: Best Radio DJ:
http://www.sfbg.com/promo/pollpositions.php
AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)

"Opinions are my own only, and do not necessarily represent those of
KZSU Radio or Stanford University." (or words to that effect.)

> circling the whole deal three times=2C fatigue & a fat headache got the
> best of me so we peaced out.=20
>=20
> Favorite set for me was DRC @ Clubberz Cure=2C however there were many
> close-seconds.  Hey Peter=2C we need to catch up soon!
>=20
> peace
>=20
> now I'm that guy     =20
>=20

>  Subject: Re: [sfraves] Lovefest reports...

> =20
>  OK here's mine...
> =20
> =20
>  Headline: Love Fest Killed Muni
> =20
>  We couldn't get a sitter so we really only attended the parade part and
> briefly went into the festival area itself.  Took Muni from West Portal
> to the parade and saw at least 6 full trains packed with ravers before
> we jammed ourselves into one.  When we got off at Civic Center it was
> pandemonium=3B there were ravers and weirdos everywhere.  Muni people wer=
e
> obviously overwhelmed and irritated.
> =20
>  We got to Market just as the parade approached.  Wow!  Many more floats
> this year with bigger sound systems and higher production values on them
> as well.  Heard many good tunes as the parade progressed and some=2C umm=
=2C
> not so good.  Went over to the SF House float area for a while looking
> for Chuck G but no joy=2C
> =20
>  Danced for a bit there and the boys picked up on girls.  Tyrone (age 17
> mos.) was especially successful.  I thought this one girl in a lime
> green dress he was flirting with was going to follow us home.  He used
> this pointing move I taught him.  Hilarious.
> =20
>  The boys got tired after a bit and we had to depart.  Went back into
> Muni and the situation was even worse.  Still more ravers coming
> downtown from the West Side.  And even the outbound trains were
> partially packed with ravers.  Amazing.
> =20
>  To my surprise there are literally thousands of young rave heads living
> out here on the West Side=2C probably largely SF State kids.  And they
> were out in force.  Wow. =20
> =20
>  Peter
> =20

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Lovefest reports...

On Tue, Oct 07, 2008 at 07:47:14AM -0700, dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
> Let's share some.

Well, never been very good at recounting experiences, but what the
hell:

Did a little Thursday night prestart at Phonic/EndUp but missed the party
at Otis.  nice party, pretty moderate sized crowd given love fest was
about to happen, though.

Missed the killswitch klusterfuck on friday, but rolled into an early start
with the dirtybird party at mezzanine.  JPhlip killed as she always seems to,
the rest of the crew did their usual too.  Can't remember last trip to mezz,
never noticed the fuzzy hanging ropes used for the vip area before, those
feel really nice, uhh, sometimes. :)

>From there checked out the abraxis party at jelly's, which wasn't doing so
well.  On leaving met some stalker/generally weird dude who kept talking to
us and trying to social hack us, not sure if he's a PI, hacker, reporter or
maybe a scientologist guy sent to fuck one of us over but definitely the
low point of the weekend.

Back to basecamp to chill for a bit, help get the kontrol livecast levels
set clean, some different assistance and off to the fest, had a surprisingly
good time, but still feel like SF LF just isn't really there yet.

I mean, come on, look how many ravers and other heads were there, and in
terms of music, you've got 1-2 techno, 1-2 dnb, 1-2 trance and most
of the only 17 total were these big commercial/mainstream crews?  Anyway,
some good sounds at the couple of em, just not enough of them.  Looks like
I need to plan on creating a float next year.

Overall it was a good time, fairly friendly nice crowd, saw drugs aplenty of
the socially friendly variety, really the only annoying folks were the
couple of Obama supporters who were intentionally causing the most delay
in the crowded foot traffic lanes (like really, how many people there are
planning to vote for someone else?), other than that good times.  Took
a break at one point to run down to SoMA for a shower and check on the
Kontrol webcast, which sounded great almost all event(went down during
Sammy D's set near the end).

Bailed for dinner, finally gave in and took an hour nap, off to kontrol,
got there in time for Speedy J, scored a little more stayawake assistance and
held it together until 7:30 or so, decided this time the fade out was
too strong for assistance so went home, slept for 4 hours this time before
heading back out, wandered, nothing of note sunday afternoon, got back
home sometime around 2am and went to sleep.

And yeah, surprisingly few listers during the weekend, guess everyone went
to different parties.  Quite the duration, good LoveFest, just hope it
keeps growing into something like the real parade in Germany. ;)

-R.

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Lovefest reports...

Forest and I went to the Skills party and hung out
with Terry.  It was lots of fun!  What an amazing
production!  They had 32 dual 15" subs per side in the
main room, the stack of speakers was literally like 30
feet tall, with 7 massive lasers, and awesome visual
screens.  The side rooms also had booming and clear
sound systems and awesome visuals!  Terry's visuals
were dope, as usual, and the whole room was green when
Green Velvet was playing, wicked!  Go JK on sound!

Unfortunately, there probably won't be a Berlin Love Parade next year, as
far as I know. This year the Parade was in Dortmund. Generally speaking,
Berliners seem to be totally over Love Parade; it's old news. There have
been legal issues surrounding holding Love Parade in Berlin for a couple
years now.
-Chelsea

Subject: [sfraves] My Lovely Love Filled Lovin' YUmmy Weekend Review PT1

OK... so 'cause like my weekend was incredibally mondo hella friggin'
long, I"m gonna try to make this review as short as possible...

So my weekend actually started on Wed afternoon... i went out to the City
& went to school to meet w/ my couselors... then I went to Qool Happy Hour
for the premiere of the SF LoveFest Mini Documentary... so that was kinda
fun 'cause saw alota people who been MIA for a while :)  Qool was actually
pretty fun :)  I mean... there was like this Proggy almost Candy house
playing when the happy just started then like moved to this Proggy kinda
trance which was kinda funny 'cause i heard tracks I ain't heard in years.
 The crowd was pretty mixed with the yups & the ravers & the clubbers, but
it was a totally good vibe!  Then when the SFLF Mini doc showed, it just
made everyone happy :)

But my primary goal was to get to San Jose to Terry's pad 'cause I need to
crash there.  Like my homie from Rhode Island planned on coming out for
LoveFest & he really wanted me to pick him up.  LoL... so like instead of
telling people the whole long mondo story why i needed to get out to the
South Bay ASAP... I just told them "I need to pick up a LoveFest DJ @ SJ
Airport" which was actually 2 truths into 1 'cause he is a DJ & he was
going to LoveFest... but I needed to shortcut it...

So after a long walk, a long wait at Cal Train with a bunch of Canadians &
Portuguese women who liked singing, a really long Cal Train Commute with
this punk rock wannabe haight street couple, a Chinese man on his cell
phone, & this mondo like hella freaky lookin' like old man who kept
peaking at me inbetween the seats in front of me while his wife was
talkin' to him, I finally made it the South Bay.  Then at the station,
like Terry wasn't there yet & I ws kinda freakin' out 'cause the only pay
phone there to call him was like busted.  Luckily half an hour later,
after walking around the station & the surrounding area all confuzed and
totally mondo lost, this Latino dude by this apartment complex called
Terry for me & Luckily he & Paula just arrived & wre like on the other
side of the station.  Then as soon as i was relieved and walking through
the tunnel, two homeless dude, one with a banjo singing for me to wait for
im started chasing me.  Hello 2day... so I just hella ran until I say
their car & jumped the fuck in!

So FINALLY, after hours of endless travel and small adventure, I made it
to my goal.  Then after like a couple hours of talking w/ Terry & Paula &
watching TV, I slept.  Woke up around like 9:45ish, had a yummy Estioko
breakfast with this yummy blended coffee, watched more TV, got ready,
talked with Paula more & her Brother & his girlfriend, play endlessly with
Chewwy & Han Solo (even tried walking them, but that didn't work), then
got dropped off at the airport to meet up with Steppo!

OK.. I just wanna say right quick, Terry, Thank U sooooooooo much for
everything!!  I reeeeeeeeally  really really totally hella mondo like
appreciate everything man!  I mean... that had to of been like kinda the
shortest visit i've ever had with  you.  But like seroulsy, thank U much
Pare!  You & Paula & Brother & GF helped me soooooooooo much! YAAAAY!!

So me & Steppo are at the airport and he told me that this chica from
Davis, this newbie in the dubstep scene & in dubstep.fm, Haliegh, was on
her way to pick him up too.  So we didn't have to do the whole public
transport commute to the City.  LoL... she showed up like an hour & a half
later then lied to us that it took her only 2 hours to drive down from
Davis *rolls eyes* HELLO 2DAY, yeah right!

So we ate at In N Out 'cause it's where all the Cali Tourist Newbies gotta
eat, got to his Homie's pad in SOMA, went bar hopping in The Mission, then
ended up in Trauma at El Rincon!  Oooh Wow, Trauma was so fun.  LoL...
Young crowd & saw alota people, familiar faces, mondo good vibes!  It was
Dope!!  The music went from Jungle, to breaks/ electro house, dubstep,
then back to jungle!  Danced alot & chilled alot with Steppo too!!

So that's the end of part on & I'll probably do PT2 when i get back from
V-Town tomorrow 'cause I gotta sleep early... lol... hello 2day.. .it's
already like 10 to 4... but yeah, so far the weekend was just so
promising!  YAAAY!!!




-- 
Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> ObY {8O)

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Blowin' the roof off this sucka: 15 yr. anniv. of An Epiphany

All I've got to say about the subject line are 2 words; Dragn'fly and 
AndyW.  Yup, that roof doesn't have a chance!!

I'm SO excited to have these two coming down to celebrate the 15 yr. 
anniversary of An Epiphany Of Sound!!  It was only last Thur., as I was 
getting ready for the show, that I realized that this week was the 
anniversary day.  So I quickly thought who would be best to have join in 
and make the celebration proper.  And these 2 immediately came to mind.
Both because of the music they bring as well as the connections they 
have to the show.  This is going to be big!!  And oh so perfect!

So, be sure to tune in to An Epiphany Of Sound this Thursday, from 
9a-noon pacific time, for our celebration of 15 yrs. on the air with 
AndyW and Dragn'fly.  We're over the air in the bay area at 90.1FM and 
we stream to the world at http://kzsulive.stanford.edu

DO NOT MISS THIS ONE!

Peace all,
J.C.

from
http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/obamas_spending_edge.html

[image: Chris Cillizza's Politics Blog -- The
Fix]<http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/>
washingtonpost.com's Politics Blog *About This
Blog<http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2005/10/get_your_fix.html>
*   |   *Meet Chris
Cillizza<http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2005/09/about_chris_cillizza.html>
*   |   [image: RSS Feeds] <http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/index.xml>
*RSS Feed* <http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/index.xml>   (What's

  Obama Outspending McCain Nearly 3 to 1 on Television
Democratic presidential candidate Sen. Barack Obama, D-Ill., waves as he
arrives for a technical walk through before a scheduled townhall-style
presidential debate at Belmont University in Nashville, Tenn., Tuesday, Oct.
7, 2008. (AP Photo/Charles Dharapak)

*Barack Obama* is outspending *John McCain* at nearly a three-to-one clip on
television time in the final weeks of the presidential election, according
to ad buy information obtained by The Fix, a financial edge that is almost
certainly contributing to the momentum for the Illinois senator in key
battleground states.

>From Sept. 30 to Oct. 6, Obama spent more than $20 million on television ads
in 17 states including more than $3 million in Pennsylvania and more than $2
million each in Florida, Michigan and Ohio. McCain in that same time frame
spent just $7.2 million in 15 states. Even when the Republican National
Committee's independent expenditure spending in Indiana, Michigan, Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Virginia and Wisconsin is factored in (a total of $5.3
million), Obama still outspent the combined GOP forces by roughly $8 million
in the last week alone. (See full distribution after the
jump<http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/obamas_spending_edge.html#chart>.)


The spending edge enjoyed by Obama has been used almost exclusively to
hammer McCain as both a clone of the current president and someone who is
out of touch on key domestic issues -- most notably the economy. The
assertion of Obama's spending edge has coincided with the collapse of the
financial industry and a refocusing by voters on the economy to turn the
election from a toss up to one in which the Democratic candidate has moved
into a discernible lead.

While the struggles of McCain and his party over the Wall Street bailout
bill that passed Congress last week after much *sturm und drang* have been
well documented, the practical political impact of Obama's decision to
forego public financing for the general election and McCain's choice to
accept the $84 million in public funds has not been as fully explored.

Obama's fundraising machine has continued to churn in recent months -- bringing
in $67.5 million in August
alone<http://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/15/us/politics/15donors.html?_r=1&oref=slogin>and
ending that month with more than $77 million on hand. (Reports for
September are not due at the Federal Election Commission until Oct. 20.)

Obama's ad spending strategy has been based on the idea of stretching McCain
to the limit in a series of non-traditional battlegrounds (Indiana, North
Carolina, Colorado, Virginia), knowing that such an approach would force the
cash-poorer Republican's hand at some point.

That decision paid off last week when McCain pulled down his television ads
in Michigan<http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/mccain_moves_out_of_michigan_w.html>,
a move due in large part to the prohibitive cost of continuing to run
commercials in the Wolverine State. A look at advertising in the last week
in Michigan showed Obama dropping nearly $2.2 million as compared to
$642,000 for McCain and just over $1 million by the RNC -- a difference of
nearly $600,000 in favor of the Illinois senator.

A detailed look at campaign spending on ads over the last week shows clearly
how Obama is using his financial edge over McCain. In 13 of the 15 states
where both candidates were on television, Obama outspent McCain -- in some
states, drastically.

In Florida, where recent
polling<http://www.pollster.com/polls/fl/08-fl-pres-ge-mvo.php>suggests
an Obama surge, the Illinois senator disbursed more than $2.8
million for television ads in the last week while McCain spent $623,000 -- a
massive $2.17 million spending gap.

In North Carolina, Obama dropped approximately $1.5 million on television
commercials last week while McCain spent only $137,000. Such a wide spending
disparity explains why a series of polls has shown Obama trending upward in
the Tarheel State of late.

Even in Pennsylvania, the state where McCain is now focusing much of his
time and energy in the final month of the campaign, Obama's spending
advantage is massive. Obama disbursed a little more than $3 million in the
Keystone State last month as compared to $1.2 million in ad spending by
McCain and another $807,000 by the RNC. It adds up to a million-dollar edge
for Obama on television -- meaning that he outspending Republican by roughly
33 percent in Pennsylvania.

In Virginia, a state that has gone Republican in every presidential election
since 1964, Obama's pronounced spending advantage is also being felt. Obama
spent $1.6 million on ads in the Commonwealth last week while the combined
forces of McCain and the RNC spent $909,000 -- giving Obama a $700,000
spending lead.

Only in Minnesota and Iowa did McCain have a spending edge on television
over Obama in the last week.

In Minnesota, the McCain spent $377,000 on television, far more than the
$196,000 Obama spent during the same period. Republicans saw a significant
uptick in their numbers in Minnesota following the national party convention
in August although most recent
surveys<http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2008/president/mn/minnesota_mccain_vs_obama-550.html>show
Obama reclaiming a statistically significant lead. History is also
against McCain in the state as no Republican presidential nominee has
carried Minnesota since 1972.

In Iowa, McCain spent $297,000 on television as compared to $224,000 for
Obama. That's rough parity in a state where polling shows Obama with a
comfortable lead. McCain has spent considerable time, attention and money in
Iowa, however, a strategy that has baffled many within the Obama campaign.
Iowa went for then Vice President *Al Gore* in 2000 by 4,000 votes in 2000
but *George W. Bush* carried it by 10,000 votes four years later.

Spending by the RNC's independent expenditure arm has kept McCain within
shouting distance of Obama in several crucial states including Ohio and
Wisconsin.

In Ohio, Obama spent $2.86 million on television last week while the
combination of McCain ($1.1 million) and the RNC ($1.66 million) gave
Democrats just a $100,000 edge. The same was true in Wisconsin where Obama
disbursed $1.24 million, compared to $1.03 million for McCain and the RNC.

Is Obama's spending edge conclusive when it comes to determining the outcome
on Nov. 4? No. External events can -- and always seem to -- intrude on even
the best laid of political plans and strategies. But, Obama's fundraising
prowess has provided him a major leg up in the final month of the campaign
that, when combined with the detrimental effects the focus on the economy
has had on McCain, make it an uphill climb to victory for the Arizona
senator.

   *+$218K, Obama*

  Obama Outspending McCain Nearly 3 to 1 on Television
Democratic presidential candidate Sen. Barack Obama, D-Ill., waves as he
arrives for a technical walk through before a scheduled townhall-style
presidential debate at Belmont University in Nashville, Tenn., Tuesday, Oct.
7, 2008. (AP Photo/Charles Dharapak)

in 17 states including more than $3 million in Pennsylvania and more than $2

Committee's independent expenditure spending in Indiana, Michigan, Ohio,

surveys<http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2008/president/mn/minnesota_mccain_vs_obama-550.html>show
Obama reclaiming a statistically significant lead. History is also
against McCain in the state as no Republican presidential nominee has
carried Minnesota since 1972.

In Iowa, McCain spent $297,000 on television as compared to $224,000 for
Obama. That's rough parity in a state where polling shows Obama with a
comfortable lead. McCain has spent considerable time, attention and money in
Iowa, however, a strategy that has baffled many within the Obama campaign.
Iowa went for then Vice President *Al Gore* in 2000 by 4,000 votes in 2000
but *George W. Bush* carried it by 10,000 votes four years later.

Spending by the RNC's independent expenditure arm has kept McCain within
shouting distance of Obama in several crucial states including Ohio and
Wisconsin.

In Ohio, Obama spent $2.86 million on television last week while the
combination of McCain ($1.1 million) and the RNC ($1.66 million) gave
Democrats just a $100,000 edge. The same was true in Wisconsin where Obama
disbursed $1.24 million, compared to $1.03 million for McCain and the RNC.

Is Obama's spending edge conclusive when it comes to determining the outcome
on Nov. 4? No. External events can -- and always seem to -- intrude on even
the best laid of political plans and strategies. But, Obama's fundraising
prowess has provided him a major leg up in the final month of the campaign
that, when combined with the detrimental effects the focus on the economy
has had on McCain, make it an uphill climb to victory for the Arizona
senator.

> from
> http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/obamas_spending_edge.html
>
> [image: Chris Cillizza's Politics Blog -- The
> Fix]<http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/>
> washingtonpost.com's Politics Blog *About This
> Blog<http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2005/10/get_your_fix.html>
> *   |   *Meet Chris
> Cillizza<
> http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2005/09/about_chris_cillizza.html>
> *   |   [image: RSS Feeds] <
> http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/index.xml>
> *RSS Feed* <http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/index.xml>   (What's
> RSS?<http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/rss/index.html#what>)
>
> Obama Outspending McCain Nearly 3 to 1 on Television
> Democratic presidential candidate Sen. Barack Obama, D-Ill., waves as he
> arrives for a technical walk through before a scheduled townhall-style
> presidential debate at Belmont University in Nashville, Tenn., Tuesday,
> Oct.
> 7, 2008. (AP Photo/Charles Dharapak)
>
> *Barack Obama* is outspending *John McCain* at nearly a three-to-one clip
> on
> television time in the final weeks of the presidential election, according
> to ad buy information obtained by The Fix, a financial edge that is almost
> certainly contributing to the momentum for the Illinois senator in key
> battleground states.
>
> From Sept. 30 to Oct. 6, Obama spent more than $20 million on television
> ads
> in 17 states including more than $3 million in Pennsylvania and more than
> $2
> million each in Florida, Michigan and Ohio. McCain in that same time frame
> spent just $7.2 million in 15 states. Even when the Republican National
> Committee's independent expenditure spending in Indiana, Michigan, Ohio,
> Pennsylvania, Virginia and Wisconsin is factored in (a total of $5.3
> million), Obama still outspent the combined GOP forces by roughly $8
> million
> in the last week alone. (See full distribution after the
> jump<
> http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/obamas_spending_edge.html#chart
> >.)
>
>
> The spending edge enjoyed by Obama has been used almost exclusively to
> hammer McCain as both a clone of the current president and someone who is
> out of touch on key domestic issues -- most notably the economy. The
> assertion of Obama's spending edge has coincided with the collapse of the
> financial industry and a refocusing by voters on the economy to turn the
> election from a toss up to one in which the Democratic candidate has moved
> into a discernible lead.
>
> While the struggles of McCain and his party over the Wall Street bailout
> bill that passed Congress last week after much *sturm und drang* have been
> well documented, the practical political impact of Obama's decision to
> forego public financing for the general election and McCain's choice to
> accept the $84 million in public funds has not been as fully explored.
>
> Obama's fundraising machine has continued to churn in recent months --
> bringing
> in $67.5 million in August
> alone<
> http://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/15/us/politics/15donors.html?_r=1&oref=slogin
> >and
> ending that month with more than $77 million on hand. (Reports for
> September are not due at the Federal Election Commission until Oct. 20.)
>
> Obama's ad spending strategy has been based on the idea of stretching
> McCain
> to the limit in a series of non-traditional battlegrounds (Indiana, North
> Carolina, Colorado, Virginia), knowing that such an approach would force
> the
> cash-poorer Republican's hand at some point.
>
> That decision paid off last week when McCain pulled down his television ads
> in Michigan<
> http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/mccain_moves_out_of_michigan_w.html
> >,
> a move due in large part to the prohibitive cost of continuing to run
> commercials in the Wolverine State. A look at advertising in the last week
> in Michigan showed Obama dropping nearly $2.2 million as compared to
> $642,000 for McCain and just over $1 million by the RNC -- a difference of
> nearly $600,000 in favor of the Illinois senator.
>
> A detailed look at campaign spending on ads over the last week shows
> clearly
> how Obama is using his financial edge over McCain. In 13 of the 15 states
> where both candidates were on television, Obama outspent McCain -- in some
> states, drastically.
>
> In Florida, where recent
> polling<http://www.pollster.com/polls/fl/08-fl-pres-ge-mvo.php>suggests
> an Obama surge, the Illinois senator disbursed more than $2.8
> million for television ads in the last week while McCain spent $623,000 --
> a
> massive $2.17 million spending gap.
>
> In North Carolina, Obama dropped approximately $1.5 million on television
> commercials last week while McCain spent only $137,000. Such a wide
> spending
> disparity explains why a series of polls has shown Obama trending upward in
> the Tarheel State of late.
>
> Even in Pennsylvania, the state where McCain is now focusing much of his
> time and energy in the final month of the campaign, Obama's spending
> advantage is massive. Obama disbursed a little more than $3 million in the
> Keystone State last month as compared to $1.2 million in ad spending by
> McCain and another $807,000 by the RNC. It adds up to a million-dollar edge
> for Obama on television -- meaning that he outspending Republican by
> roughly
> 33 percent in Pennsylvania.
>
> In Virginia, a state that has gone Republican in every presidential
> election
> since 1964, Obama's pronounced spending advantage is also being felt. Obama
> spent $1.6 million on ads in the Commonwealth last week while the combined
> forces of McCain and the RNC spent $909,000 -- giving Obama a $700,000
> spending lead.
>
> Only in Minnesota and Iowa did McCain have a spending edge on television
> over Obama in the last week.
>
> In Minnesota, the McCain spent $377,000 on television, far more than the
> $196,000 Obama spent during the same period. Republicans saw a significant
> uptick in their numbers in Minnesota following the national party
> convention
> in August although most recent
> surveys<
> http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2008/president/mn/minnesota_mccain_vs_obama-550.html
> >show
> Obama reclaiming a statistically significant lead. History is also
> against McCain in the state as no Republican presidential nominee has
> carried Minnesota since 1972.
>
> In Iowa, McCain spent $297,000 on television as compared to $224,000 for
> Obama. That's rough parity in a state where polling shows Obama with a
> comfortable lead. McCain has spent considerable time, attention and money
> in
> Iowa, however, a strategy that has baffled many within the Obama campaign.
> Iowa went for then Vice President *Al Gore* in 2000 by 4,000 votes in 2000
> but *George W. Bush* carried it by 10,000 votes four years later.
>
> Spending by the RNC's independent expenditure arm has kept McCain within
> shouting distance of Obama in several crucial states including Ohio and
> Wisconsin.
>
> In Ohio, Obama spent $2.86 million on television last week while the
> combination of McCain ($1.1 million) and the RNC ($1.66 million) gave
> Democrats just a $100,000 edge. The same was true in Wisconsin where Obama
> disbursed $1.24 million, compared to $1.03 million for McCain and the RNC.
>
> Is Obama's spending edge conclusive when it comes to determining the
> outcome
> on Nov. 4? No. External events can -- and always seem to -- intrude on even
> the best laid of political plans and strategies. But, Obama's fundraising
> prowess has provided him a major leg up in the final month of the campaign
> that, when combined with the detrimental effects the focus on the economy
> has had on McCain, make it an uphill climb to victory for the Arizona
> senator.

>   Obama Outspending McCain Nearly 3 to 1 on Television
> Democratic presidential candidate Sen. Barack Obama=2C D-Ill.=2C waves as=
 he
> arrives for a technical walk through before a scheduled townhall-style
> presidential debate at Belmont University in Nashville=2C Tenn.=2C Tuesda=
y=2C Oct.
> 7=2C 2008. (AP Photo/Charles Dharapak)
>=20
> *Barack Obama* is outspending *John McCain* at nearly a three-to-one clip=
 on
> television time in the final weeks of the presidential election=2C accord=
ing
> to ad buy information obtained by The Fix=2C a financial edge that is alm=
ost
> certainly contributing to the momentum for the Illinois senator in key
> battleground states.
>=20
> From Sept. 30 to Oct. 6=2C Obama spent more than $20 million on televisio=
n ads
> in 17 states including more than $3 million in Pennsylvania and more than=
 $2
> million each in Florida=2C Michigan and Ohio. McCain in that same time fr=
ame
> spent just $7.2 million in 15 states. Even when the Republican National
> Committee's independent expenditure spending in Indiana=2C Michigan=2C Oh=
io=2C
> Pennsylvania=2C Virginia and Wisconsin is factored in (a total of $5.3
> million)=2C Obama still outspent the combined GOP forces by roughly $8 mi=
llion
> in the last week alone. (See full distribution after the
> jump<http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/obamas_spending_edge=
.html#chart>.)
>=20
>=20
> The spending edge enjoyed by Obama has been used almost exclusively to
> hammer McCain as both a clone of the current president and someone who is
> out of touch on key domestic issues -- most notably the economy. The
> assertion of Obama's spending edge has coincided with the collapse of the
> financial industry and a refocusing by voters on the economy to turn the
> election from a toss up to one in which the Democratic candidate has move=
d
> into a discernible lead.
>=20
> While the struggles of McCain and his party over the Wall Street bailout
> bill that passed Congress last week after much *sturm und drang* have bee=
n
> well documented=2C the practical political impact of Obama's decision to
> forego public financing for the general election and McCain's choice to
> accept the $84 million in public funds has not been as fully explored.
>=20
> Obama's fundraising machine has continued to churn in recent months -- br=
inging
> in $67.5 million in August
> alone<http://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/15/us/politics/15donors.html?_r=3D1&=
oref=3Dslogin>and
> ending that month with more than $77 million on hand. (Reports for
> September are not due at the Federal Election Commission until Oct. 20.)
>=20
> Obama's ad spending strategy has been based on the idea of stretching McC=
ain
> to the limit in a series of non-traditional battlegrounds (Indiana=2C Nor=
th
> Carolina=2C Colorado=2C Virginia)=2C knowing that such an approach would =
force the
> cash-poorer Republican's hand at some point.
>=20
> That decision paid off last week when McCain pulled down his television a=
ds
> in Michigan<http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/mccain_moves_=
out_of_michigan_w.html>=2C
> a move due in large part to the prohibitive cost of continuing to run
> commercials in the Wolverine State. A look at advertising in the last wee=
k
> in Michigan showed Obama dropping nearly $2.2 million as compared to
> $642=2C000 for McCain and just over $1 million by the RNC -- a difference=
 of
> nearly $600=2C000 in favor of the Illinois senator.
>=20
> A detailed look at campaign spending on ads over the last week shows clea=
rly
> how Obama is using his financial edge over McCain. In 13 of the 15 states
> where both candidates were on television=2C Obama outspent McCain -- in s=
ome
> states=2C drastically.
>=20
> In Florida=2C where recent
> polling<http://www.pollster.com/polls/fl/08-fl-pres-ge-mvo.php>suggests
> an Obama surge=2C the Illinois senator disbursed more than $2.8
> million for television ads in the last week while McCain spent $623=2C000=
 -- a
> massive $2.17 million spending gap.
>=20
> In North Carolina=2C Obama dropped approximately $1.5 million on televisi=
on
> commercials last week while McCain spent only $137=2C000. Such a wide spe=
nding
> disparity explains why a series of polls has shown Obama trending upward =
in
> the Tarheel State of late.
>=20
> Even in Pennsylvania=2C the state where McCain is now focusing much of hi=
s
> time and energy in the final month of the campaign=2C Obama's spending
> advantage is massive. Obama disbursed a little more than $3 million in th=
e
> Keystone State last month as compared to $1.2 million in ad spending by
> McCain and another $807=2C000 by the RNC. It adds up to a million-dollar =
edge
> for Obama on television -- meaning that he outspending Republican by roug=
hly
> 33 percent in Pennsylvania.
>=20
> In Virginia=2C a state that has gone Republican in every presidential ele=
ction
> since 1964=2C Obama's pronounced spending advantage is also being felt. O=
bama
> spent $1.6 million on ads in the Commonwealth last week while the combine=
d
> forces of McCain and the RNC spent $909=2C000 -- giving Obama a $700=2C00=
0
> spending lead.
>=20
> Only in Minnesota and Iowa did McCain have a spending edge on television
> over Obama in the last week.
>=20
> In Minnesota=2C the McCain spent $377=2C000 on television=2C far more tha=
n the
> $196=2C000 Obama spent during the same period. Republicans saw a signific=
ant
> uptick in their numbers in Minnesota following the national party convent=
ion
> in August although most recent
> surveys<http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2008/president/mn/minneso=
ta_mccain_vs_obama-550.html>show
> Obama reclaiming a statistically significant lead. History is also
> against McCain in the state as no Republican presidential nominee has
> carried Minnesota since 1972.
>=20
> In Iowa=2C McCain spent $297=2C000 on television as compared to $224=2C00=
0 for
> Obama. That's rough parity in a state where polling shows Obama with a
> comfortable lead. McCain has spent considerable time=2C attention and mon=
ey in
> Iowa=2C however=2C a strategy that has baffled many within the Obama camp=
aign.
> Iowa went for then Vice President *Al Gore* in 2000 by 4=2C000 votes in 2=
000
> but *George W. Bush* carried it by 10=2C000 votes four years later.
>=20
> Spending by the RNC's independent expenditure arm has kept McCain within
> shouting distance of Obama in several crucial states including Ohio and
> Wisconsin.
>=20
> In Ohio=2C Obama spent $2.86 million on television last week while the
> combination of McCain ($1.1 million) and the RNC ($1.66 million) gave
> Democrats just a $100=2C000 edge. The same was true in Wisconsin where Ob=
ama
> disbursed $1.24 million=2C compared to $1.03 million for McCain and the R=
NC.
>=20
> Is Obama's spending edge conclusive when it comes to determining the outc=
ome
> on Nov. 4? No. External events can -- and always seem to -- intrude on ev=
en
> the best laid of political plans and strategies. But=2C Obama's fundraisi=
ng
> prowess has provided him a major leg up in the final month of the campaig=
n
> that=2C when combined with the detrimental effects the focus on the econo=
my
> has had on McCain=2C make it an uphill climb to victory for the Arizona
> senator.

> Obama Outspending McCain Nearly 3 to 1 on Television
> Democratic presidential candidate Sen. Barack Obama, D-Ill., waves as he
> arrives for a technical walk through before a scheduled townhall-style
> presidential debate at Belmont University in Nashville, Tenn., Tuesday,
> Oct.
> 7, 2008. (AP Photo/Charles Dharapak)
>
> *Barack Obama* is outspending *John McCain* at nearly a three-to-one clip
> on
> television time in the final weeks of the presidential election, according
> to ad buy information obtained by The Fix, a financial edge that is almost
> certainly contributing to the momentum for the Illinois senator in key
> battleground states.
>
> From Sept. 30 to Oct. 6, Obama spent more than $20 million on television
> ads
> in 17 states including more than $3 million in Pennsylvania and more than
> $2
> million each in Florida, Michigan and Ohio. McCain in that same time frame
> spent just $7.2 million in 15 states. Even when the Republican National
> Committee's independent expenditure spending in Indiana, Michigan, Ohio,
> Pennsylvania, Virginia and Wisconsin is factored in (a total of $5.3
> million), Obama still outspent the combined GOP forces by roughly $8
> million
> in the last week alone. (See full distribution after the
> jump<
> http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/obamas_spending_edge.html#chart
> >.)
>
>
> The spending edge enjoyed by Obama has been used almost exclusively to
> hammer McCain as both a clone of the current president and someone who is
> out of touch on key domestic issues -- most notably the economy. The
> assertion of Obama's spending edge has coincided with the collapse of the
> financial industry and a refocusing by voters on the economy to turn the
> election from a toss up to one in which the Democratic candidate has moved
> into a discernible lead.
>
> While the struggles of McCain and his party over the Wall Street bailout
> bill that passed Congress last week after much *sturm und drang* have been
> well documented, the practical political impact of Obama's decision to
> forego public financing for the general election and McCain's choice to
> accept the $84 million in public funds has not been as fully explored.
>
> Obama's fundraising machine has continued to churn in recent months --
> bringing
> in $67.5 million in August
> alone<
> http://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/15/us/politics/15donors.html?_r=1&oref=slogin
> >and
> ending that month with more than $77 million on hand. (Reports for
> September are not due at the Federal Election Commission until Oct. 20.)
>
> Obama's ad spending strategy has been based on the idea of stretching
> McCain
> to the limit in a series of non-traditional battlegrounds (Indiana, North
> Carolina, Colorado, Virginia), knowing that such an approach would force
> the
> cash-poorer Republican's hand at some point.
>
> That decision paid off last week when McCain pulled down his television ads
> in Michigan<
> http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/10/mccain_moves_out_of_michigan_w.html
> >,
> a move due in large part to the prohibitive cost of continuing to run
> commercials in the Wolverine State. A look at advertising in the last week
> in Michigan showed Obama dropping nearly $2.2 million as compared to
> $642,000 for McCain and just over $1 million by the RNC -- a difference of
> nearly $600,000 in favor of the Illinois senator.
>
> A detailed look at campaign spending on ads over the last week shows
> clearly
> how Obama is using his financial edge over McCain. In 13 of the 15 states
> where both candidates were on television, Obama outspent McCain -- in some
> states, drastically.
>
> In Florida, where recent
> polling<http://www.pollster.com/polls/fl/08-fl-pres-ge-mvo.php>suggests
> an Obama surge, the Illinois senator disbursed more than $2.8
> million for television ads in the last week while McCain spent $623,000 --
> a
> massive $2.17 million spending gap.
>
> In North Carolina, Obama dropped approximately $1.5 million on television
> commercials last week while McCain spent only $137,000. Such a wide
> spending
> disparity explains why a series of polls has shown Obama trending upward in
> the Tarheel State of late.
>
> Even in Pennsylvania, the state where McCain is now focusing much of his
> time and energy in the final month of the campaign, Obama's spending
> advantage is massive. Obama disbursed a little more than $3 million in the
> Keystone State last month as compared to $1.2 million in ad spending by
> McCain and another $807,000 by the RNC. It adds up to a million-dollar edge
> for Obama on television -- meaning that he outspending Republican by
> roughly
> 33 percent in Pennsylvania.
>
> In Virginia, a state that has gone Republican in every presidential
> election
> since 1964, Obama's pronounced spending advantage is also being felt. Obama
> spent $1.6 million on ads in the Commonwealth last week while the combined
> forces of McCain and the RNC spent $909,000 -- giving Obama a $700,000
> spending lead.
>
> Only in Minnesota and Iowa did McCain have a spending edge on television
> over Obama in the last week.
>
> In Minnesota, the McCain spent $377,000 on television, far more than the
> $196,000 Obama spent during the same period. Republicans saw a significant
> uptick in their numbers in Minnesota following the national party
> convention
> in August although most recent
> surveys<
> http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2008/president/mn/minnesota_mccain_vs_obama-550.html
> >show
> Obama reclaiming a statistically significant lead. History is also
> against McCain in the state as no Republican presidential nominee has
> carried Minnesota since 1972.
>
> In Iowa, McCain spent $297,000 on television as compared to $224,000 for
> Obama. That's rough parity in a state where polling shows Obama with a
> comfortable lead. McCain has spent considerable time, attention and money
> in
> Iowa, however, a strategy that has baffled many within the Obama campaign.
> Iowa went for then Vice President *Al Gore* in 2000 by 4,000 votes in 2000
> but *George W. Bush* carried it by 10,000 votes four years later.
>
> Spending by the RNC's independent expenditure arm has kept McCain within
> shouting distance of Obama in several crucial states including Ohio and
> Wisconsin.
>
> In Ohio, Obama spent $2.86 million on television last week while the
> combination of McCain ($1.1 million) and the RNC ($1.66 million) gave
> Democrats just a $100,000 edge. The same was true in Wisconsin where Obama
> disbursed $1.24 million, compared to $1.03 million for McCain and the RNC.
>
> Is Obama's spending edge conclusive when it comes to determining the
> outcome
> on Nov. 4? No. External events can -- and always seem to -- intrude on even
> the best laid of political plans and strategies. But, Obama's fundraising
> prowess has provided him a major leg up in the final month of the campaign
> that, when combined with the detrimental effects the focus on the economy
> has had on McCain, make it an uphill climb to victory for the Arizona
> senator.

From: "Osby Oi Oi Jamz" <osby@viberation.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Reply-To: osby@viberation.com
User-Agent: SquirrelMail/1.4.10a

Importance: Normal
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] My Lovely Love Filled Lovin' YUmmy Weekend Review PT2

So friday, there were hella things to do that night, places to go, but i
just wanted to chill since i had to get up around like 6AM & be in the
staging area by 8AM... so I hella caught up on alota sleep lost & rested &
stuff...

Saturday came, got to the City, enjoyed a walk w/ this girl from Pismo
beach, who was a LF Virgin, to 2nd street, then got to Minna & hung out
with the Solid Gold Dancers!  LF Float headquarters wasn't even open yet &
i was sooooooooooooo buttfuckin' tired still... so I just hung out w/ the
Solid Gold Dancers & these 2 Skills Float Candy P Tot Dancers...

By like 10AM, most all the floats were there & we put the finishing
touches on the BADNB float, which wasn't really much 'cause it was just a
big ass bed w/ speakers & minimal, if any, decorations... then as soon as
the procession starts, i was told by the head float dude, Canadub, that I
was the head wheel monitor/ float monitor person & i hella freaked out...
like every year, I'm just a wheel monitor for the BADNB float 'cause I
like walking along the float & having a low impact kinda workout dealie &
just being responsible for my area. But I just figured I'd do it.... & I
did!!!

OK... Heeeeeeeeeeeeeello 2Daaay... Float Monitor is so not a Groovy job...
not only was i responsible for keeping the front clear of retards who like
walking in front of moving vehicles, but I had to pace the driver on when
to move & stop while yelling to the top of my lungs "MOVE MOVE MOVE MOVE,
WILL YOU FUCKIN MOVE YOU IDIOT, DON"T CROSS, GET BACK THERE, MOVE MOVE
MOVE MOVE"... yeah.. it wasn't so fun, or easy... 'cause apparently
drunkardly or etardedly crossing in front of a big ass truck 2 feet away
from it is really smart!

So after like what... the hour & a 1/2 - 2 hour procession, the parking
confussion with the floats in our section, then just my own like walkin'
the float crazy walking decompression... it was kinda nice to finally
chill & just take in the madness :)  Like the festival started packing in
fast!!  It was kinda estimated that between 3:30-4PM, Civic Center was
already at 100,200!  By the time it was over, it was at 100,500.

But as soon as I got my bearings back (well... as much as I have anyway),
I had to find my camera crew 'cause we're finishing up the SFLF
documentary & extending it so we can have a full length & can make DVDs &
stuff!  So for the next 2 hours, we went around Civic interviewing
sooooooooooo many people & as exausting as it was, it was still kinda fun
& I actually got to enjoy alota floats I wasn't gonna go to.

Overall, it was fun!  LF this year was pretty Dope!  I mean... it was
reeeeeeeeally Groovy seein' Familia everywhere & all the dancers I brock
out on the floor with!  I will be biased & say that the BADNB float did
have a hugest crowd like we do every year with all the junglists for a
day!!  But the dance floors all around Civic were goin' on too.  It was a
really good day!!  YAAAAY!!!

So after I was at our lil BADNB afterparty at Anu.  LoL... yeah... I had a
rEally good timE thErE 'cause well... all I gotta say is when in Rome man
:P  But yeah... the DJs killed it, the bar was packed more than i've ever
seen it. Afterwards I ended up walkin' around SOMA & meeting alota LF
people.  Then I ended up crossing 7th street & someone like hella yelled
my name, Holy Shit, it was my Homegirl Marcine... I was tempted to tell
her to drop me off @ the dubstep afterparty, but she offered a ride home
instead & I sooo couldn't not pass that up! Lol... Hello 2day... so
yeah... but 4AM, i was home just like, yeah... totally good day & night!!!




-- 
Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> ObY {8O)

containing my entire Music Speech from SUBX01! I license to people, =
labels and projects where I see fit but to use my shit (not even =

asking me was & is jacked-up (way wrong).

use my vocals, have never even heard of the label and was never =
approached by anyone from Be Chosen.

taken. Any help you can give me by spreading the word about this label =
and what they did would be very helpful! They don't know me or how I =

On October 25th, 2008 Revival NYC invites you to an epic night of Drum and
Bass...


Featuring...



*THE PLANET OF THE DRUMS!*





*Dieselboy*


The jungle scene has always been centered in Britain, leaving Americans to
watch from afar, import the records, and spin occasionally (though rarely
very well). Damian Higgins reversed the trends a little bit with his
nation-trotting gigs and frequent mix albums released as Dieselboy. Born in
Pennsylvania, Higgins began DJing during the early '90s and organized house
parties in and around Philadelphia. By 1993, the sound of jungle had begun
pumping up America as well as Britain, and Dieselboy made the switch to
drum'n'bass. He DJed at jungle events all around America and helmed
1996's Suburban
Base jump-up compilation Drum & Bass Selection USA. Another Sub Base mix
album, 97 Octane, followed in 1997. Dieselboy's next two albums (A Soldier's
Story, System Upgrade) appeared on Moonshine, the premier American mix
label. In mid-1999, Higgins began his production career with a single
("Atlantic
State") for the respected British concern Technical Itch Recordings, and
another single, "Descent," followed later that year for Palm Pictures.
Dieselboy's 2000 release, The 6ixth Session, combined a mix disc with a full
one of productions.



*Dara*


Besides the Liquid Sky community, DJ Dara is probably New York's leading
exponent of drum'n'bass. He has led several club nights around the city and
began recording for Sm:)e Communications with his first album, Rinsimus
Maximus, released in July 1997. The following year, he returned with the mix
album Full Circle:Drum && Bass DJ Mix, while both Renegade Continuum and
Halfway Home appeared in 1999. His New York City based jungle record
store, Breakbeat
Science, established itself as an important contribution to the American
growth of drum n' bass and it's younger talent. DJ Dara continued his
prolific output in early 2000 with From Here to There. He returned a year
later on Moonshine with Future Perfect.



*AK1200*


When Orlando native AK 1200 started his career in electronic music in the
late '80s, almost no one in the country had ever heard of it. Nevertheless,
the artist managed to carve out an extremely successful career in the realm
of underground electronic music while simultaneously introducing countless
people to the up-and-coming genre. At this point, he boasts one of the most
illustrious careers of anyone in the business. He is not only a DJ, but also
a producer, promoter, remixer, magazine publisher, and record store owner,
not to mention a pioneer of breakbeat, jungle, and drum'n'bass.


..
*MC MESSINIAN*


Born in Los Angeles, California, J-Messinian (nee James Fiorella) bounced
around the country nomad-like, eventually ending up in Philadelphia in the
late 90's. As a child growing up, James developed a love for MC'ing:
head-nodding to HipHop in oversized headphones and engaging in freestyle
'ciphers' with other "staircase artists". His formative musical roots ranged
from Soul, to Hip Hop, to Latin percussion and Dancehall, to his mother
Helena's emotional piano and guitar sessions. In the early nineties, James
began frequenting parties, from b-boy summits to raves with breaks and tribal
house. As his journey into the underground progressed, he eventually fell in
love with the raw snares and basslines of Drum and Bass music. Click Here
for Full Bio<http://www.msplinks.com/MDFodHRwOi8vd3d3LnBvdGRueWMuY29tL2luZGV4LnBocD9vcHRpb249Y29tX2NvbnRlbnQmdmlldz1hcnRpY2xlJmlkPTEmSXRlbWlkPTY=>

Also featuring many of your favorite locals:


*
ODI

Havok

Soma

Odyssey

I-Cue

Big Ears

Cereal Kila

Courage

Tommy Diaz
*

*The Knitting Factory - New York*

New York, NY 10013
