Leonard, turn left and walk a block & a half to the club.

You can take the A, C or E train to Canal Street, walk 4 blocks south and
turn left on Leonard. You could also take the N or R train to Canal Street,
walk down Broadway 4 blocks to Leonard, turn right, and see the club at the
far end of the block. If you are unfamiliar with the the downtown area click

sail

By Eddie Wrenn
Last updated at 7:44 AM on 29th September 2008

retirement.

For this mighty vessel, the largest ever passenger ship, dwarfs all that
stands next to it, making the thousands of spectators which came to see it's
launch look little more than ants as they waved the graceful ship out of the
port.

The 315m-long ship is so wide it barely squeezed out of the Papenberg
watergates, but ably helped by two tug-boats it escaped on it's to the North
sea, where it will head to Denmark.
People watch the cruiser 'Celebrity Solstice' dragged through the watergate
of the Meyer Dockyard in Papenburg

People watch the cruiser 'Celebrity Solstice' dragged through the watergate
of the Meyer Dockyard in Papenburg

carry nearly 3,000 passengers.

phobia of the sea... This cruiser is the first one to boast an authentic
grass lawn on its top deck.

ship.

> nation-trotting gigs and frequent mix albums released as Dieselboy. Born
in
> Pennsylvania, Higgins began DJing during the early '90s and organized
house
> parties in and around Philadelphia. By 1993, the sound of jungle had begun
> pumping up America as well as Britain, and Dieselboy made the switch to
> drum'n'bass. He DJed at jungle events all around America and
helmed
> 1996's Suburban
> Base jump-up compilation Drum & Bass Selection USA. Another Sub Base
mix
> album, 97 Octane, followed in 1997. Dieselboy's next two albums (A
Soldier's
> Story, System Upgrade) appeared on Moonshine, the premier American mix
> label. In mid-1999, Higgins began his production career with a single
> ("Atlantic
> State") for the respected British concern Technical Itch Recordings,
and
> another single, "Descent," followed later that year for Palm
Pictures.
> Dieselboy's 2000 release, The 6ixth Session, combined a mix disc with
a full
> one of productions.
> 
> 
> 
> *Dara*
> 
> 
> Besides the Liquid Sky community, DJ Dara is probably New York's
leading
> exponent of drum'n'bass. He has led several club nights around the
city and
> began recording for Sm:)e Communications with his first album, Rinsimus
> Maximus, released in July 1997. The following year, he returned with the
mix
> album Full Circle:Drum && Bass DJ Mix, while both Renegade
Continuum and
> Halfway Home appeared in 1999. His New York City based jungle record
> store, Breakbeat
> Science, established itself as an important contribution to the American
> growth of drum n' bass and it's younger talent. DJ Dara continued
his
> prolific output in early 2000 with From Here to There. He returned a year
> later on Moonshine with Future Perfect.
> 
> 
> 
> *AK1200*
> 
> 
> When Orlando native AK 1200 started his career in electronic music in the
> late '80s, almost no one in the country had ever heard of it.
Nevertheless,
> the artist managed to carve out an extremely successful career in the
realm
> of underground electronic music while simultaneously introducing countless
> people to the up-and-coming genre. At this point, he boasts one of the
most
> illustrious careers of anyone in the business. He is not only a DJ, but
also
> a producer, promoter, remixer, magazine publisher, and record store owner,
> not to mention a pioneer of breakbeat, jungle, and drum'n'bass.
> 
> 
> ..
> *MC MESSINIAN*
> 
> 
> Born in Los Angeles, California, J-Messinian (nee James Fiorella) bounced
> around the country nomad-like, eventually ending up in Philadelphia in the
> late 90's. As a child growing up, James developed a love for
MC'ing:
> head-nodding to HipHop in oversized headphones and engaging in freestyle
> 'ciphers' with other "staircase artists". His formative
musical roots ranged
> from Soul, to Hip Hop, to Latin percussion and Dancehall, to his mother
> Helena's emotional piano and guitar sessions. In the early nineties,
James
> began frequenting parties, from b-boy summits to raves with breaks and
tribal
> house. As his journey into the underground progressed, he eventually fell
in
> love with the raw snares and basslines of Drum and Bass music. Click Here
> for Full Bio
> 
> Also featuring many of your favorite locals:
> 
> 
> *
> ODI
> 
> Havok
> 
> Soma
> 
> Odyssey
> 
> I-Cue
> 
> Big Ears
> 
> Cereal Kila
>

> 
> Tommy Diaz

>> *Dieselboy*
>>
>>
>> The jungle scene has always been centered in Britain, leaving Americans
>> to
>> watch from afar, import the records, and spin occasionally (though
>> rarely
>> very well). Damian Higgins reversed the trends a little bit with his
>> nation-trotting gigs and frequent mix albums released as Dieselboy. Born
> in
>> Pennsylvania, Higgins began DJing during the early '90s and organized
> house
>> parties in and around Philadelphia. By 1993, the sound of jungle had
>> begun
>> pumping up America as well as Britain, and Dieselboy made the switch to
>> drum'n'bass. He DJed at jungle events all around America and
> helmed
>> 1996's Suburban
>> Base jump-up compilation Drum & Bass Selection USA. Another Sub Base
> mix
>> album, 97 Octane, followed in 1997. Dieselboy's next two albums (A
> Soldier's
>> Story, System Upgrade) appeared on Moonshine, the premier American mix
>> label. In mid-1999, Higgins began his production career with a single
>> ("Atlantic
>> State") for the respected British concern Technical Itch Recordings,
> and
>> another single, "Descent," followed later that year for Palm
> Pictures.
>> Dieselboy's 2000 release, The 6ixth Session, combined a mix disc with
> a full
>> one of productions.
>>
>>
>>
>> *Dara*
>>
>>
>> Besides the Liquid Sky community, DJ Dara is probably New York's
> leading
>> exponent of drum'n'bass. He has led several club nights around the
> city and
>> began recording for Sm:)e Communications with his first album, Rinsimus
>> Maximus, released in July 1997. The following year, he returned with the
> mix
>> album Full Circle:Drum && Bass DJ Mix, while both Renegade
> Continuum and
>> Halfway Home appeared in 1999. His New York City based jungle record
>> store, Breakbeat
>> Science, established itself as an important contribution to the American
>> growth of drum n' bass and it's younger talent. DJ Dara continued
> his
>> prolific output in early 2000 with From Here to There. He returned a
>> year
>> later on Moonshine with Future Perfect.
>>
>>
>>
>> *AK1200*
>>
>>
>> When Orlando native AK 1200 started his career in electronic music in
>> the
>> late '80s, almost no one in the country had ever heard of it.
> Nevertheless,
>> the artist managed to carve out an extremely successful career in the
> realm
>> of underground electronic music while simultaneously introducing
>> countless
>> people to the up-and-coming genre. At this point, he boasts one of the
> most
>> illustrious careers of anyone in the business. He is not only a DJ, but
> also
>> a producer, promoter, remixer, magazine publisher, and record store
>> owner,
>> not to mention a pioneer of breakbeat, jungle, and drum'n'bass.
>>
>>
>> ..
>> *MC MESSINIAN*
>>
>>
>> Born in Los Angeles, California, J-Messinian (nee James Fiorella)
>> bounced
>> around the country nomad-like, eventually ending up in Philadelphia in
>> the
>> late 90's. As a child growing up, James developed a love for
> MC'ing:
>> head-nodding to HipHop in oversized headphones and engaging in freestyle
>> 'ciphers' with other "staircase artists". His formative
> musical roots ranged
>> from Soul, to Hip Hop, to Latin percussion and Dancehall, to his mother
>> Helena's emotional piano and guitar sessions. In the early nineties,
> James
>> began frequenting parties, from b-boy summits to raves with breaks and
> tribal
>> house. As his journey into the underground progressed, he eventually
>> fell
> in
>> love with the raw snares and basslines of Drum and Bass music. Click
>> Here
>> for Full Bio

  WWE & My9's Block Party helps kick off SmackDown on MyNetwork TV By:

  *NEW YORK =96* Early this morning on the streets of New York City,
WWE<http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/smackdownmoving/blockpartykickoff#>S=
uperstars
Jeff
Hardy <http://www.wwe.com/superstars/smackdown/jeffhardy/>, Curt
Hawkins<http://www.wwe.com/superstars/smackdown/curthawkins/>and Zack
Ryder <http://www.wwe.com/superstars/smackdown/zackryder/> were on hand for
the "My9 SmackDown <http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/> Block Party,"
helping to launch
SmackDown<http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/smackdownmoving/blockpartykick=
off#>on
MyNetwork TV, tonight at 8/7 CT.
WATCH<http://www.wwe.com/content/media/video/vms/smackdown/2008/october1-7/=
8233236>
|
PHOTOS<http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/smackdownmoving/blockpartyphotos/=
>

WWE fans Jagger & Alfred Nastro came out early to be part of the event, wit=
h
7-year-old Jagger waiting in line beginning at 4:30 a.m. "I came to see Jef=
f
Hardy," is all Jagger could get out through his excitement, but his father
made it clear that this trip was tradition. "This is great to share with my
son; I shared a lot of wrestling with my father years ago, during the days
of Andre the Giant
<http://www.wwe.com/superstars/halloffame/andrethegiant/>and Mil
Mascaras, and to have Jagger here with me is fun for both of us."

While young Jagger had trouble with his words this morning, Joey Rotella wa=
s
crowned the Hot 97 trivia champion at 6:45 a.m.

"It was really cool to be up there in front of everyone =96 I never thought
all the sports-entertainment knowledge I had would win me anything, but thi=
s
morning it did," Rotella explained.

For native New Yorkers Curt Hawkins & Zack Ryder, being back in the Big
Apple at a WWE event as Superstars was a welcome change, one that has
brought them both full circle.

"This is awesome for both of us to be here," said Hawkins. "To have been at
WWE events as fans just a couple of years ago, and now to be up here as WWE
Superstars<http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/smackdownmoving/blockpartykic=
koff#>is
just mind-blowing." As for the crowd reaction the duo received when
they
hit the stage early in the morning, Hawkins shook his head and laughed.
"That's what I would like to call a mixed reaction, but it's New York, and
home or not, New Yorkers are the hardest fans to please."

Ryder echoed his tag team partner's sentiments. "This is just what it is al=
l
about, the fans. Love us or hate us, cheer us or boo us, we have been on th=
e
other side of these crowds many times, and for us to come back after making
it, no matter the reaction, is just great."

The experience was a bit different for No. 1 contender Jeff Hardy, who the
crowd began chanting for at 5:30 a.m.

"It's always cool to be in New York, it's kind of a different world to me
being from North Carolina. But especially on a day like this, when we are
celebrating such a huge event for SmackDown, it's just the place to be."
Hardy continued, "I know this move to MyNetwork TV is going to be huge, and
I am glad to be a part of it, as I have been all week with promotional
tours."

That schedule hasn't lessened Hardy's focus, as he is just two days away
from challenging WWE Champion Triple
H<http://www.wwe.com/superstars/smackdown/tripleh/>for the gold.

"It's really hard to think about what is going on at No Mercy, but I'm
ready. I will get back to North Carolina tonight, but my mind is definitely
right =96 mentally and physically, I'm good to go."

Hardy, Hawkins & Ryder did more than just appear on *Good Day New York*,
they also judged the "My9 Biggest SmackDown Fan Contest," which saw nine
participants strut their stuff on stage =96 and also gave the contestants o=
ne
minute with a live microphone in their hands.

Matthew Saxon Rivera came dressed as his favorite SmackDown Superstar =96 M=
ontel
Vontavious Porter <http://www.wwe.com/superstars/smackdown/mvp/>. Though he
didn't win, Rivera and his friend Gino Cabrera, who dressed as
Carlito<http://www.wwe.com/superstars/smackdown/carlito/>,
put on quite a show for the WWE Universe =96 including the three Superstar
judges. Cabrera spent his minute on the microphone challenging the
Superstardom of Hawkins & Ryder =96 who took exception and disqualified
Cabrera. As for being part of the contest and being in front of their fello=
w
fans, Cabrera spoke for he and Rivera, but could only utter two words:
"That's cool." (He assured no pun intended.)

But Hardy, Hawkins and Ryder did choose a winner of the My9 Biggest
SmackDown Fan Contest =96 Jose Vasquez and his son, Jose Vasquez Jr., who
walked away with tickets to the 2008 Survivor Series in Boston. The
father-son duo charmed the judges with their talk of family, and Vasquez Jr=
.
made sure to get the crowd behind him when he exclaimed that Hardy would
walk out of No Mercy the new WWE Champion.

"To be here in Manhattan with all of these WWE fans, and to be part of the
whole experience today has been nothing short of incredible," Vasquez said.
"I grew up watching WWE, and my son has started getting into it over the
past few years, and we both just think it is great family
entertainment<http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/smackdownmoving/blockparty=
kickoff#>
."

The wide-eyed, 10-year-old Vasquez Jr. only wished one thing after learning
of the Biggest Fan victory: "I hope the seats are good for Survivor Series.=
"

The most touching moment of the morning came when Jeff Hardy was approached
by 20-year-old Linda Torres of Manhattan =96 a lifelong Hardy fanatic.
Accompanied by her friends, Nathan Storm, Dan Szymanowicz and Jeff
Rivadenerya, the wheelchair-bound Torres came to tears when she finally met
Hardy. After calming her emotions, Torres expressed her love for The Hardys=
,
and Jeff made sure she didn't go away empty-handed, signing her Hardys
poster and sealing the meeting with a kiss on the cheek.

As Hardy prepares to help SmackDown kick-off tonight at 8/7 CT on its new
home of MyNetwork TV as part of the All Star Eight-Man Tag Team Match, he,
Hawkins & Ryder made sure that every fan went home satisfied, all before
breakfast was over.

Subject: [sfraves] SRR: (?)  New machine prints sheets of light

------=_NextPart_000_0008_01C92B26.C1037270
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset="US-ASCII"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

>>>  http://www.cnn.com/2008/TECH/10/10/sheets.of.light.oleds.ap/index.html

 

 

>>> NISKAYUNA, New York (AP) -- On a bank of the Mohawk River, a windowless
industrial building of corrugated steel hides something that could make
floor lamps, bedside lamps, wall sconces and nearly every other household
lamp obsolete.

 

It's a machine that prints lights.

The size of a semitrailer, it coats an 8-inch wide plastic film with
chemicals, then seals them with a layer of metal foil. Apply electric
current to the resulting sheet, and it lights up with a blue-white glow.

You could tack that sheet to a wall, wrap it around a pillar or even take a
translucent version and tape it to your windows. Unlike practically every
other source of lighting, you wouldn't need a lamp or conventional fixture
for these sheets, though you would need to plug them into an outlet.

The sheets owe their luminance to compounds known as organic light-emitting
diodes, or OLEDs. While there are plenty of problems to be worked out with
the technology, it's not the dream of a wild-eyed startup.

OLEDs are beginning to be used in TVs and cell-phone displays, and big names
like Siemens and Philips are throwing their weight behind the technology to
make it a lighting source as well. The OLED printer was made by General
Electric Co. on its sprawling research campus here in upstate New York. It's
not far from where a GE physicist figured out a practical way to use
tungsten metal as the filament in a regular light bulb. That's still used
today, nearly a century later.

The invention of the incandescent bulb created the pattern for home
lighting: Our light sources are small and bright. Maybe there are a few in
the center of the ceiling, and a few in the corners of the room. Because
they're too bright to look at, they need to be reflected and diffused with
lamp shades and frosted glass.

OLEDs could overturn all that, with broad, diffuse light sources bathing
rooms in a gentle glow. Photographers go to great lengths to diffuse the
illumination they use when shooting portraits, because they know we look our
best in soft light.

The big glowing sheets could also make light sources out of everyday things.
GE imagines putting OLEDs on the inside of window blinds -- pull them down,
light them up, and you have light streaming from the window, even at night.
You could even make OLED wallpaper, since the material is flexible.

"We have a lot of ideas for what we can do with it," said German lighting
designer Ingo Maurer.

He and his firm have already created the first commercially available OLED
lamp, and is selling it in a limited edition of 25. He expects to deliver
the first two this month, at an undisclosed but presumably collector-level
price. 

The lamp is more of a curiosity than a practical product: the light is dim,
and gradually grows dimmer, losing half its brightness after 2,000 hours.
Its OLED panels are only a few inches wide, and made of glass rather than
plastic. They protrude from a central stem like the leaves of a fern.

The panels in Maurer's lamp are made by Osram Opto Semiconductors, a
subsidiary of German industrial conglomerate Siemens AG, which is also the
parent of Osram Sylvania, a competitor to GE in the general lighting market.

Osram Opto made them with an expensive, slow process known as vacuum
deposition that has dominated OLED development so far. One virtue of this
method is that it can be combined with the technologies that produce LCD
displays to make full-color OLED TVs. Sony Corp. sells an 11-inch model for
$2,500.

OLED TVs have to become much cheaper (and larger) to become mass-market
products, and OLED lights have to be cheaper still. That's the issue GE is
tackling with its printer, which dispenses with vacuum deposition in favor
of a process that's not much more complicated than the printing of a
newspaper.

"We're trying to be as low-tech as possible," said Anil Duggal, head of GE's
OLED research team.

In the next step, GE plans to build a larger machine that can print panels
several feet wide. Its output could be sold commercially as early as 2010,
Duggal said, but he acknowledged that's a "very aggressive" goal.

Since the production runs will be small by then, the prices won't be
accessible to the average consumer. But the luminous OLEDs could show up in
niche, luxury settings, like casinos or fancy restaurants, where the thin
and flexible lights could allow the creation of striking architectural or
artistic effects.

Looking ahead a few more years, printing could reduce the cost of OLEDs to
little more than the cost of the stuff it's printed on, said Janice Mahon,
vice president of technology commercialization at Universal Display Corp. in
Ewing, New Jersey. The company is a leader in OLED research, and develops
some of the organic compounds, which are akin to the dyes used to color
clothes. If printed on metal foil, the cost of an OLED light could be less
than a dollar per square foot, Mahon said.

This sets OLEDs apart from another promising technology that has been hailed
as the future of lighting. Inorganic LEDs, the pinhead-sized lights that
adorn electronic gadgets, are beginning to show up in commercial lighting,
where their extreme longevity compared to bulbs makes up for their high
production cost. Since they're made with semiconductor manufacturing
techniques, a cluster of LEDs that produces as much light as a standard bulb
costs more than $100.

LEDs and OLEDs both hold the potential for big energy savings over standard
incandescent bulbs. Matching fluorescents is tougher. Universal Display this
year created OLEDs that exceeded the energy efficiency of fluorescents, but
combining that feature with longevity and mass production will be a
challenge.

"It's not going to be competitive with fluorescents in 2010," Duggal said.

As point light sources, LEDs are likely to coexist with the big, diffuse
OLEDs, said analyst Lawrence Gasman at Nanomarkets LLC, a research firm in
Glen Allen, Virginia. "Together, they make for a nice lighting future,"
Gasman said.

He projects that OLED lighting sales could reach $5.9 billion by 2015.

Bob Sagebiel, technical marketing manager for lighting at distributor Arrow
Electronics Inc., is less optimistic. Because OLEDs are so different from
current lighting technology, they could have a hard time being accepted by
the market, he believes. An OLED panel won't fit in any of the 20 billion
light-bulb sockets worldwide, he noted. Commercial buildings will probably
need rewiring to take advantage of big panels that don't fit into existing
fixtures for fluorescent tubes.

Also, for GE and Osram to reach customers with their panels, they'll need to
go through makers of light fixtures, and "that's an industry that is
tremendously conservative," Sagebiel said.

On the manufacturing side, there are still challenges to overcome for the
technology, particularly in making OLEDs long-lasting in addition to being
power-efficient. They're gradually worn out by use. Exposure to atmospheric
oxygen, which can seep through plastic, destroys them quickly.

But OLED technology is, at least, in much better shape to take on the
lighting market than an older technology that also produces thin and
printable light sources. Electroluminescent lights, which glow in Indiglo
watches and car dashboards, have been made for decades. Despite early hopes,
they've never become competitive when it comes to brightness or energy
efficiency.

"In the 1950s, people were talking about electroluminescence the way we talk
about OLEDs today," Duggal said. "It's humbling."

>>> NISKAYUNA, New York (AP) -- On a bank of the Mohawk River, a windowless
industrial building of corrugated steel hides something that could make
floor lamps, bedside lamps, wall sconces and nearly every other household
lamp obsolete.

 

It's a machine that prints lights.

The size of a semitrailer, it coats an 8-inch wide plastic film with
chemicals, then seals them with a layer of metal foil. Apply electric
current to the resulting sheet, and it lights up with a blue-white glow.

You could tack that sheet to a wall, wrap it around a pillar or even take a
translucent version and tape it to your windows. Unlike practically every

Berlusconi Says Leaders May Close World's Markets (Update1)
By Steve Scherer
Oct. 10 (Bloomberg) -- Italian Prime Minister Silvio
Berlusconi<http://search.bloomberg.com/search?q=Silvio%0ABerlusconi&site=wnews&client=wnews&proxystylesheet=wnews&output=xml_no_dtd&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&filter=p&getfields=wnnis&sort=date:D:S:d1>said
political leaders are discussing the idea of closing the world's
financial markets while they ``rewrite the rules of international finance.''

``The idea of suspending the markets for the time it takes to rewrite the
rules is being discussed,'' Berlusconi said today after a Cabinet meeting in
Naples, Italy. A solution to the financial crisis ``can't just be for one
country, or even just for Europe, but global.''
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell as much 8.1 percent in early trading
and pared most of those losses after Berlusconi's remarks. The Dow was down
0.5 percent to 8540.52 at 10:10 in New York.
Group of Seven finance ministers and central bankers are meeting in
Washington today, and will stay in town for the International Monetary Fund
and World Bank meetings this weekend. European Union leaders may gather in
Paris on Oct. 12, three days before a scheduled summit in Brussels,
Berlusconi said today, while Group of Eight leaders may hold a meeting on
the crisis ``in coming days,'' he said.
Berlusconi didn't give any details about what kind of rules leaders were
looking to change, except to say that leaders are ``talking about a new Bretton
Woods<http://search.bloomberg.com/search?q=Bretton+Woods&site=wnews&client=wnews&proxystylesheet=wnews&output=xml_no_dtd&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&filter=p&getfields=wnnis&sort=date:D:S:d1>.''

The Bretton Woods Agreements were adopted to rebuild the international
economic system after World War II in a hotel in Bretton Woods, New
Hampshire. The aim of the agreements was to establish a monetary management
system, initially by pegging currencies to gold. The IMF was set up later to
help manage the international financial system.
To contact the reporter on this story: Steve
Scherer<http://search.bloomberg.com/search?q=Steve+Scherer&site=wnews&client=wnews&proxystylesheet=wnews&output=xml_no_dtd&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&filter=p&getfields=wnnis&sort=date:D:S:d1>in
Rome at
scherer@bloomberg.net<http://us.mc589.mail.yahoo.com/mc/compose?to=scherer@bloomberg.net>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Know your grower....

Well the whole problem originates in the crazy prohibition of a plant.  If it was legal to grow weed, it would be grown on existing farm land (and in backyards, basements, etc.)  instead of secretly in the national forests.  Also, with proper labeling, consumers would be able to buy organic products if they chose to do so.

Prohibition and the insane war on drugs are the problem.  Legalize growing and the entire black market would evaporate overnight as would the illegal growing in national forests.  Continuing with prohibition damages public lands and enriches these dangerous criminal gangs.  Its a bad deal all around.

Peter

I'd have to say, based on the article, you're absolutely correct 
environmentally.  Methlabs are in an existing building, and I don't 
think they are clear cutting areas to make a harvest field.  The methlab 
downside of course are the used chems going into the sewer system, or 
septic tank, which may or may not be a problem.  Of course exploding 
meth labs can cause harm to humans, but I don't consider that an impact, 
more like nature scores one.  Then you have beautiful California public 
lands getting trashed vs Cletus and his snowbound mobile home.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Know your grower....

See, I don't disagree with legalizing weed.  It's far less damaging than 
the legal drugs, and less addictive.  Thus, it's a threat to those 
industries.

Don't blame the Gov't alone in this.  The Tobacco industry and the booze 
market have a lot to lose of weed were openly legal to produce.  They 
have a big stake in keeping it illegal, as do all the mafia growing 
rings.  However, both of those pale in the power of who really made it 
illegal:  Hurst Publishing.  Why?  He owned the woodmills for the 
papers. Hemp paper was a threat to his business so, he started running 
slur campaigns in his papers that got the public terrified, demanding 
action by the Gov't, and they got it.  Hurst got to make billions on his 
toxic wood pulp plants, and the harmless hemp industry was wiped out.

Don't talk about the plight of the poor migrant weed grower on public 
lands.  They are cartel and you know it.  Amatures would be happy with a 
little Roundup, and they certainly wouldn't be buying enough PVC pipe to 
divert water ways.  So, these same guy trashing our land want to keep it 
illegal as well.

The first step though is to decriminalize it. 

So who do we ultimately blame?  That's right - The voters.

Voters influenced by the media, who were controlled by big business, who 
have the politicians in their pockets.

Nothing has changed in 80 years.

--S

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Know your grower....


Who ever is behind it, there can be no doubt that it takes some serious political muscle to prevent the state's number one cash crop from being taxed.

At around $14 billion annually*, its clear that the state is leaving at least several billion on the table here.  And that's not counting the cost savings from now unnecessary eradication efforts, wasted law enforcement spending, and unneeded incarcerations of people involved with growing and consuming marijuana.  

When the state is looking at a budget deficit of $14.5 billion this year, I have a simple question.  How can we as California taxpayers afford to keep marijuana illegal?  Its simply a fiscal decision.  We can no longer afford prohibition regardles sof how one might feel about it, especially during the current economic crisis.

Now legalization won't solve the state's budget problems, but it could make a large impact contributing perhaps $2-3 billion annually (my estimate) to the state coffers.  

Write your representatives etc.

Peter

*Compare to the value of the state's almond crop which is just over $2 billion annually.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Know your grower....

Marijuana accounts for over 25% of the state's agricultural production on a revenue basis and yet remains entirely untaxed.  See http://www.cdfa.ca.gov/

This does not account for other economic activity related to growing.  If that developed similarly to other agricultural products, it might be another $30 billion in related economic activity which would also be taxed.  And none of this includes a tax at retail similar to alcohol or tobacco products.  Tobacco taxes in California amount to somewhat over $1 and its not unreasonable to estimate something similar for marijuana.

Finally, over time, one could look to the wine industry as a model of the future development of marijuana farming in California.  The wine industry is valued at $51.8 billion to  the state's economy, and has an economic impact of $125.3 billion on the U.S. economy.  See http://www.wineinstitute.org/company/pressroom/12072006

In summary, legalizing marijuana could produce a over $4 billion of directly related tax revenue to the state and related economic activity might be 2-3x this amount.  This one act alon could bring the state near a balanced budget.  And none of this includes reductions in law enforcement and related costs.  Longer term, the industry might be worth several times this amount to the state's economy similar to the wine industry.  

If you pay taxes in California, this money is coming directly out of your pocket.  It does not matter if you aren't a weed smoker, you are paying to keep weed illegal.  And Marijuana prohibition is costing state taxpayers plenty, as you can see its literally billions of dollars.

Regards,

Peter



----- Original Message ----
From: "dangrsmind@yahoo.com" <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
To: electrofunk138@hotmail.com; Shatter <shatter@sonic.net>; Nyc Labrets <digitalcomponents@gmail.com>
Cc: Ben Feldman <bfeldman@eccentric.org>; sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Sunday, October 12, 2008 12:27:34 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Know your grower....


Who ever is behind it, there can be no doubt that it takes some serious political muscle to prevent the state's number one cash crop from being taxed.

At around $14 billion annually*, its clear that the state is leaving at least several billion on the table here.  And that's not counting the cost savings from now unnecessary eradication efforts, wasted law enforcement spending, and unneeded incarcerations of people involved with growing and consuming marijuana.  

When the state is looking at a budget deficit of $14.5 billion this year, I have a simple question.  How can we as California taxpayers afford to keep marijuana illegal?  Its simply a fiscal decision.  We can no longer afford prohibition regardles sof how one might feel about it, especially during the current economic crisis.

Now legalization won't solve the state's budget problems, but it could make a large impact contributing perhaps $2-3 billion annually (my estimate) to the state coffers.  

Write your representatives etc.

Peter

*Compare to the value of the state's almond crop which is just over $2 billion annually.

Actually, it's not even tobacco and booze that are the major movers and shakers for keeping weed illegal. 

Dow, DuPont, and a number of other petro-chemical companies were the ones that 1st made it happen with the help of William Randolph Hearts's newspapers way the fuck back when, and they are still throwing SCADS of cash to insure it stays that way now. 

'Cuz hemp and/or weed are ten million times more versatile when it comes to developing new industrial cleaning agents, fuels, fibers, and a zillion other products that would kill sales at those companies once cheaper/easier to manaufacture hemp/marijuana comes into the picture.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Know your grower....

all i know is that the govt isn't stupid and there are reasons why it is 
illegal to date. maybe if you looked at it from their point of view it 
would be easy to see why they are doing what they are doing. my retort 
was largely a tongue and cheek reply to this debate..how can anybody 
interested in pot take this shit too seriously? anybody militant about 
pot rights raise your hand..

i would have to say everyone's different about their pot usage too. i 
have a friend who actually uses it as an ADD cure. pretty effective in 
my book and way better for you than dexedrine. but i also know that 
there are also alot of people that cannot handle it and i'm sure this 
has been taken into consideration. i just don't think legalization 
should be tossed out there all willy nilly. i voted for the use of 
medical marijuana back when it was a state initiative. i'm for the 
legalization of marijuana but i'm also for regulation of its use. call 
me a stickler for the rules.

i also think that the govt doesn't care about pot dealers. i think the 
reason why this article surfaced is cause violent, environmentally 
destructive criminals are making money off of a largely peaceful 
industry that the govt easily turns a blind eye to. when this industry 
turns into a problem, shit gets handled. as it is now, pot is already 
growing in basements and backyards, sometimes whole apartments in 
oakland.. the mere fact that the govt calls it illegal, limits the 
number of factors that contribute to pot being a nuisance.

if you want a list of nuisances that pot has contributed to, i'll give a 
few examples of what i have seen growing up as a kid in marin:

my friend going completely paranoid schizo and collecting guns
10 year olds smoking pot before they are intellectually mature
people losing their jobs cause they just didn't give a shit.
people completely misunderstanding each other
people owing me money who are psychologically addicted to pot blowing it 
on more pot.
too much pot causing an emotional imbalance when sober leading to cranky 
feelings and irritability.
an irrational sense of what is true.
love of unicorns, peuter wizards with crystal balls, and D&D ( lol )

i'm not going to argue that pot is entirely bad there are lots of 
reasons why it is good. i'll even go out on a limb and say i actually 
enjoy the effects but i feel instant deregulation could lead to some 
serious societal problems.

that's my opinion and i'm standing by it. prove me wrong if you like.

peacy
sean.

Funny thing about freedom. It's about being allowed to do something, even
when some other people are against it.
If everyone agrees, then the concept of freedom doesn't even enter into it.
Following me so far? :)
Now, for one, I have a low tolerance for pot. And it probably DOES make you
stoopid-ish if you use too much.
But fuck all that shit. The idea of Freedom is paramount here. Drinking and
driving = danger to innocent people. This is a good prohibition.
Smoking pot? No danger to others. Studies show that pot doesn't even screw
up your driving (unless you are some moron who rolls while driving). Not a
good prohibition. Anyway, that simple dividing line is where our freedoms
should be.
Even if it means people can do stupid things.  Reagan's first step in
destroying the gov't (bearing fruit as we speak!) was to create the 'drug
war' goblins. (and then abortion, gays, etc)  There is a lot of political
power (that is to say, $$$) riding on these prohibitions, and on the ability
of some to divide and conquer us by creating false hot button issues. They
will make you into a moron/political puppet if you listen to them. Don't let
it happen to you.

------=_Part_145626_27627448.1223856464017--

all i know is that the govt isn't stupid and there are reasons why it is

interested in pot take this shit too seriously? anybody militant about

i would have to say everyone's different about their pot usage too. i 
have a friend who actually uses it as an ADD cure. pretty effective in 
my book and way better for you than dexedrine. but i also know that 
there are also alot of people that cannot handle it and i'm sure this 
has been taken into consideration. i just don't think legalization 
should be tossed out there all willy nilly. i voted for the use of 
medical marijuana back when it was a state initiative. i'm for the 
legalization of marijuana but i'm also for regulation of its use. call 
me a stickler for the rules.

i also think that the govt doesn't care about pot dealers. i think the 
reason why this article surfaced is cause violent, environmentally 
destructive criminals are making money off of a largely peaceful 
industry that the govt easily turns a blind eye to. when this industry 
turns into a problem, shit gets handled. as it is now, pot is already 
growing in basements and backyards, sometimes whole apartments in 
oakland.. the mere fact that the govt calls it illegal, limits the 
number of factors that contribute to pot being a nuisance.

if you want a list of nuisances that pot has contributed to, i'll give a 
few examples of what i have seen growing up as a kid in marin:

my friend going completely paranoid schizo and collecting guns
10 year olds smoking pot before they are intellectually mature
people losing their jobs cause they just didn't give a shit.

reasons why it is good. i'll even go out on a limb and say i actually 
enjoy the effects but i feel instant deregulation could lead to some 
serious societal problems.

that's my opinion and i'm standing by it. prove me wrong if you like.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] any jobs?

looking into all options is a good idea. genentech and cal are good 
suggestions. anything to avoid drowning amid the other candidates on 
craigslist. i have found job postings on sites outside of craigslist 
that never make it to craigslist. i've been finding out that it's good 
idea to check all major employment sites. craigslist job posts are often 
crazy individuals with sole proprietorships they are more likely to hire 
you than any of the major companies looking for help. all the major 
companies out there are posting on craigslist in the hope that on the 
off chance a newbe to the job market has a  ton of talent right out of 
the box. or if they aren't looking for a green college grad they are 
looking to hook an uber qualified applicant that has an RSS feed who is 
bored while surfing on his desktop at his/her present job. but i feel 
like most major companies want you to go to them and take the initiative.

seems to me there are better options outside craigslist, including temp 
agencies, second rate style craigslist sites, news paper websites. i've 
even found listings for jobs just by typing in google search for my 
chosen field. often i'm actually qualified for the positions they describe.

whether all this works or not is still to be proven. but i have found 
alot better odds outside craigslist and urge other job applicants to do 
the same. i'd prefer not to drown amid all the crap resumes that make 
mine seem just as crappy... if my resume sucks i'd rather not have 
company. `;)

sean.

looking into all options is a good idea. genentech and cal are good 
suggestions. anything to avoid drowning amid the other candidates on 
craigslist. i have found job postings on sites outside of craigslist 
that never make it to craigslist. i've been finding out that it's good 
idea to check all major employment sites. craigslist job posts are often 
crazy individuals with sole proprietorships they are more likely to hire 
you than any of the major companies looking for help. all the major 
companies out there are posting on craigslist in the hope that on the 
off chance a newbe to the job market has a  ton of talent right out of 
the box. or if they aren't looking for a green college grad they are 
looking to hook an uber qualified applicant that has an RSS feed who is 
bored while surfing on his desktop at his/her present job. but i feel 
like most major companies want you to go to them and take the initiative.?
?

seems to me there are better options outside craigslist, including temp 
agencies, second rate style craigslist sites, news paper websites. i've 
even found listings for jobs just by typing in google search for my 
chosen field. often i'm actually qualified for the positions they describe.?
?

whether all this works or not is still to be proven. but i have found 
alot better odds outside craigslist and urge other job applicants to do 
the same. i'd prefer not to drown amid all the crap resumes that make 
mine seem just as crappy... if my resume sucks i'd rather not have 
company. `;)?
?

sean.?
?

I think the point that people miss that that pot doesn't need to be 
LEGALIZED.

It needs to be decriminalized.  Nobody goes to jail for huffing 
Whippits.  Why?  It's not Illegal.  It's not LEGAL, it's just nota  
crime.  To have some legal requires legislation and such.  Big pain in 
the ass.  It also validates something when it's legalized.

Now, legalizing for Medicinal use, that's a smart move, however for 
everyone else, decriminalize it.

Decriminalize now, Tax later.

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
Saturday, September 27, 2008
Contact: Jessica Robinson, 573-751-0290

http://governor.mo.gov/cgi-bin/coranto/viewnews.cgi?id=3DEkkkVFulkpOzXqGMaj&=
style=3DDefault+News+Style&tmpl=3Dnewsitem

Gov. Blunt Statement on Obama Campaign's Abusive Use of Missouri Law
Enforcement


JEFFERSON CITY - Gov. Matt Blunt today issued the following statement
on news reports that have exposed plans by U.S. Senator Barack Obama
to use Missouri law enforcement to threaten and intimidate his critics.

St. Louis County Circuit Attorney Bob McCulloch, St. Louis City
Circuit Attorney Jennifer Joyce, Jefferson County Sheriff Glenn Boyer,
and Obama and the leader of his Missouri campaign Senator Claire
McCaskill have attached the stench of police state tactics to the
Obama-Biden campaign.

What Senator Obama and his helpers are doing is scandalous beyond
words, the party that claims to be the party of Thomas Jefferson is
abusing the justice system and offices of public trust to silence
political criticism with threats of prosecution and criminal punishment.

This abuse of the law for intimidation insults the most sacred
principles and ideals of Jefferson. I can think of nothing more
offensive to Jefferson?s thinking than using the power of the state to
deprive Americans of their civil rights.=A0 The only conceivable purpose
of Messrs. McCulloch, Obama and the others is to frighten people away
from expressing themselves, to chill free and open debate, to suppress
support and donations to conservative organizations targeted by this
anti-civil rights, to strangle criticism of Mr. Obama, to suppress ads
about his support of higher taxes, and to choke out criticism on
television, radio, the Internet, blogs, e-mail and daily conversation
about the election.

Barack Obama needs to grow up. Leftist blogs and others in the press
constantly say false things about me and my family.=A0 Usually, we
ignore false and scurrilous accusations because the purveyors have no
credibility.=A0 When necessary, we refute them. Enlisting Missouri law
enforcement to intimidate people and kill free debate is reminiscent
of the Sedition Acts - not a free society.



---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

If someone commits slander or libel, you sue them in civil court.   
The First Amendment is there to protect unpopular speech.  You don't  
just go around arresting people because you don't like what they  
say.  That is facism. There is a lot more to this story than what is  
on the surface and the Huffington Post and Word Net Daily articles  
are both just he-said she-said without doing more research.

Is it not true that Obama's campaign was run by Zbignew Brezinski,  
the same man who brought you Al Qaeda and Jimmy Carter?  Are you  
saying this is not important information and it should be dismissed  
as "smear campaign nonsense"?

All right I'm done talking due to let someone else make their point  
and time constraints.  But I will say two things, I was never saying  
vote for McCain, though I have to wonder about that, and watch out  
for the left cover.  The country is being run by the crooks at the  
Federal Reserve anyway, under an Obama administration they are just  
going to mask it under saving the polar bears, etc.  The "choices"  
presented to the people to run the country and have the keys to the  
nuclear football are a joke.

Thanks, Ben.  I was in a bit of a rush at work (just got home,
actually) and wanted to get the word out.

One thing I've sent out to some e-mail lists has been
paraphrased from what Alex said on the FnF list:

"
"The No on 8" Campaign is being outspent 2-1 right now and only
30,000 people have donated to the cause.

There are easily over 1,000,000 LGBT's in California and unless
everyone starts stepping up and donating, equal marriage will
lose on Nov. 4th. Polling shows that amongst those who've seen
commercials both pro and against Prop 8, the amendment loses!
That's great news, which is all the more reason to get as much
$$ into the No on 8 Campaign as soon as possible.
"

Another friend sent me this link - it really speaks to me as to
why we can't let this proposition pass.

http://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200809/gay-marriage

Please, if you cannot attend our event, consider helping out or
donating directly to the cause.  Visit noonprop8.com to help.

Thanks!
Michael

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Tue)

In reading all these posts...

Gay Marriage:  I couldn't really care less.  The entire concept of 
marriage is one of religion.  Good time to bring up separation of church 
and state.  The state can form or dissolve legally binding contract 
between entities.  However, they've choses to put the word marriage on 
that contract.  So, its' simple.  Anyone can be married by whatever 
religion wants to perform the religious ceremony.  However, that 
ceremony is separate from two people who want to entire a legally 
binding contract as acknowledged by the state.

See?  It's simple.  The right wingers can continue to say no gay 
marriage, but they have to honor contracts because they are a legally 
binding agreement.  Atheists can further separate from religion.  Gays 
can continue to drive great cars, have amazing clothes, the best looking 
pads, and get invited to all the best parties.


Election:  Let's talk about money.  Here's two facts about Obama that 
turns my gizzard and really makes me NOT like the guy.  There's others, 
but here's two big points that are the preface to how his gov't would 
run if elected:

1.  Channeling $800,000 into ACORN which has on many occasions tried to 
register fictitious people to vote.  On top of that these "get out and 
VOTE!" org are driven by a single party and are only concerned with 
registering people for thier party.  I know of two other parties that 
did the same thing:  The Communist and the National Socialists.

2.  Within months of being elected senator, who was then Associate Dean 
of Student Services at the University of Chicago, was promoted to Vice 
President for Community and External Affairs at University of Chicago 
Hospitals and received a 160% pay increase by the UofC hospitals.  
Employer received $1,000,000.00 federal earmark, requested by husband, 
after her promotion.

Now, those alone annoy me.  They reek of dirty underhanded politics at 
the tax payers expense, padding personal pockets the whole time.  There

On Tue, Oct 14, 2008 at 09:47:50PM -0700, Shatter wrote:
> In reading all these posts...
> 
> Gay Marriage:  I couldn't really care less.  The entire concept of 
> marriage is one of religion.  Good time to bring up separation of church 
> and state.  The state can form or dissolve legally binding contract 
> between entities.  However, they've choses to put the word marriage on 
> that contract.  So, its' simple.  Anyone can be married by whatever 
> religion wants to perform the religious ceremony.  However, that 
> ceremony is separate from two people who want to entire a legally 
> binding contract as acknowledged by the state.


Right, the only actually sane way to settle this is to remove "marriage"
as a term from the government entirely.  Adding more rifuckulousness to
the existing law is NOT the way to do it.  Prop 8, if passed, absolutely
does respect establishment of religions that only allow straight marriage,
while prohibiting the free exercise of ones that allow same-sex marriage.

The real battle is to move every "marriage" license to a "domestic
partnership" or whatever license.


As to the POTUS election, well yeah, I'm seeing the usual blind fervor on
each side again.  Good thing I'm in CA and my vote there won't matter since
the Dem loyalists will support the guy no matter what he says.

-R.

Well, aside from what Shatter posted up about Obama, the crooked =20
kinds of things that all of these politicians being served up to us =20
as our only choices, which is a total joke in itself, let's look at =20
the facts:

that government officials, police and prosecutors, are joining the =20
Obama "Truth Squad".  If someone is out saying lies about Barack =20
Obama, why does he need criminal prosecutors to help him quell that?

Perhaps looking at another piece of the puzzle may not answer that =20
exact question, but we can see how the Obama campaign reacts when =20
*they* are under scrutiny of the legal system.  There is currently a =20
lawsuit out by Phil Berg, Attorney and lifelong Democrat, challenging =20=

Barack Obama's qualification to run for President of the United =20
States.    The Obama campaign response?  A motion to the court to =20
dismiss the case.  No facts or documentation, just a request to =20
dismiss.  factchecks.org apparently has a copy of the so-called =20
"real" birth certificate, and factchecks.org is an Annenberg =20
Foundation website, which Obama used to serve on the board of.

http://clipsyndicate.com/publish/video/718415?wpid=3D0

http://www.obamacrimes.com

Webster Griffin Tarpley is an expert on the finance oligarchs, and =20
his books, Obama The Postmodern Coup, and Barack H. Obama, The =20
Unauthorized Biography, are worth looking into.  Remember, this is =20
the same guy who tried to warn us about George H.W. Bush, so this is =20
not a Republican/Democrat - false left/right paradigm thinker.  I =20
would call Jerome Corsi a lot more of a right-wing person, Tarpley is =20=

more of an advocate of adjusting social security to real inflation =20
and New Deal programs to fix the economy.  By the way, I've been =20
meaning to write about this, but just haven't had the time - both =20
Tarpley and Richard C. Cook have good solutions to the current =20
economic crisis, or shall we say, fleecing of America.

One of the things Tarpley says about Obama is, that, if your country =20
is in turmoil, and you have the choice between a crooked bourgeois, =20
no matter how corrupt he is, and facism, you'd better choose the =20
corrupt bourgeois, and if you are not sure, just ask the 1922 =20
Italians or the 1933 Germans what they should have done.  They both =20
thought they were in facism, they soon realized that was not the =20
case.  So look into this, please, don't just poo-poo everything in =20
the name of "change".  What "change"?

Make no mistake, no matter who occupies the White House on 1-21-09, =20
Bernanke, Paulson, and Kash-karry will still be around threatening =20
martial law and printing more money.  So this idea that Obama or =20
Sarah Palin  is going to save the country is not realistic.  Both =20
campaigns have the Brezinski family involved.  Brezinski wants war =20
with Russia.  They are owned and controlled by the same people =20
ultimately.  People like Dennis Kucinich and Ron Paul were excluded =20
from the process by every underhanded means they had at their =20
disposal.  Isn't it interesting how everyone so quickly forgot about =20
the vote fraud in New Hampshire in the primaries, with "Butch and =20
Hoppy" running unsealed ballot boxes on high-speed chases throughout =20
New Hampshire?  This system is a joke!  So if you're going to vote, =20
keep that in mind and consider joining the movement to monitor the =20
polling stations on election day for election fraud.  Folks, things =20
are not going to get better until enough people stand up and say no =20
to this crap.  They are literally counting on you to just stay home, =20
watch tv, and be complacent.  It's time for that to end.

Shatter wrote:
> 1.  Channeling $800,000 into ACORN which has on many occasions tried 
> to register fictitious people to vote. 

Funny, a long time back, I used to work  tech support and we used to 
have a 40 calls a day quota, a quota system much like Acorn. When around 
4:30pm rolled around and i'd have something like 30 or so calls for the 
whole day, you know what I did? I MADE UP the remaining 10 names and 
phone numbers so no one would catch on that I was actually slacking off. 
Why did I do this? Because the job sucked. This is exactly what 
happened. It's not like some fictitious people named 'Mickey Mouse' are 
actually showing up to vote. Of course, if you're good, like I was,  you 
use much more subtler names.

You know who some of these Acorn people are? They're much like the 
people at the tables you see standing outside on a cold night in front 
of Safeway. Must get pretty old standing in the cold for 7 - 8 bucks an 
hour. Tempting to make up a few names here or there on slow days to make 
a quota... Doesn't seem very creative to me...

As for your other point,  McCain gave a headliner talk to ACORN in march 
2006 commending their efforts, whereas Obama worked with them upwards of 
13 years ago. Additionally, Acorn cannot register voters as they only 
SUBMIT voter applications.

We've been down this path before here and I don't really want to get into a thrash about it.

But this time it matters.  

We're going to be asked to vote in a few short weeks.  I don't love our choices like many of the people on this list.  And I have kids and I worry about their futures.

Think about.  This year you have a choice between the radical muslim un-American terrorist and a proven American maverick war hero.  Your choice should be clear right?.

Let's call this exactly what it is: lies.  

Obama isn't an American?  He's palling around with terrorists?  He's forming brown shirt "truth squads"?  

Come on people these things are outright lies and not worth repeating.  The same people that are shouting "terrorist" at Palin's rallies are the ones that believe this crap.  Just watch the videos.  And check out what talk shows hosts and ultra-right wingnuts are promoting this garbage.

The fact is that the Republican's have led this country to the brink of ruin just as many of us knew they would.  And now we have the chance to kick them in the nuts.  Do it!

Don't let their lies about phony forensic evaluations of a birth certificate image or even sillier lies about "truth squads" convince you to stay home.  And that's what they are hoping for here.  

Don't let them win.

Peter

humans walked the earth together 6000 years ago...    The people Obama has
surrounded himself with, and how he's ran his campaign should be a good
indicator or how he'd run the country.  You even have notable conservatives
coming out of the woodwork praising Obama's insight into domestic and
international politics, and his uncanny ability to recognize the benefit to
his presidency and the country to putting people in positions who are highly
qualified.  Neither of these candidates are perfect, and both definitely
have stains on their record.  Even in these grave economic times I'm voting
on two things, and two things only:

1.   Energy Policy
2.   Foreign Policy

A McCain-Palin ticket will clearly continue the dirty energy policy of
Bush-Cheney, er should I say ArBUSTo-Halliburton.   Biden was right when he
said there was no such thing as clean coal.  By moving towards clean,
renewable, and domestic energy sources, we free ourselves up from so many of
our domestic and international problems we see today.  Nobel Laureate
economist Joseph Stiglitz has warned of the economic catastrophe that may
loom if climate change and polar ice melting continues at its current pace.
Based on energy policy alone, anyone who cares about posterity should see
the consequences of voting for the party that loves yelling "Drill, baby
drill!"  Yes, drilling will solve all of our problems since we have less
than 5% of the world's oil reserves, yet use 20+% of the world's oil supply
on a daily basis.  Pushing a policy that is reliant on oil, will never move
us towards clean-renewable energy at the pace we need to, and it will
ultimately continue our reliance on oil from foreign lands if we don't begin
developing clean fuel technologies on a  massive scale today.

Foreign policy, and energy policy are so intricately linked while we remain
hooked on oil.  The neoconservative agenda has proved itself to be a
failure, that is unless your Paul Wolfowitz, Dick Cheney, or David Pearl,
you probably believe we have not used our military in its full and able
capacity and are wondering why Syria and Iran are still standing today...
We need a president who will engage the world, who recognizes that military
campaigns should be part of a larger strategy, not a tactical tit-for-tat
battle that eventually becomes a never ending war.   McCain has shrouded
himself as the foreign policy guru, but when he doesn't know the difference
between shi'ia and sunni muslims, I really gotta wonder does this guy have a
clue of the politics and culture of the middle east?  McCain makes comments
only an ignoramus would make like making a joke out of "bomb bomb Iran."
Even the feeble minded Bush was able to recognize of the consequences of
even a short stunted military campaign against Iran, and when he met with
the Israeli PM earlier this year and was asked for American's military
support should Israel engage with Iran, Bush told Israel that such support
was not there (only to the dismay of Cheney, I'm sure!).

Again, we need a leader who will engage the world, and one who understands
the advantages a globalized world economy that is interconnected by open
markets, one that is utimately more stable than a fledgling hyper-power
running on a quarter tank going full throttle ahead into the blackness of
the night.

This one will be a pretty easy one to vote no on.  The bill is one  
paragraph I think.  Why should sovereign citizens, who are above the  
government, not the other way around as the television set and the  
skinnerian outcome-based education system has indoctrinated a  
majority of Americans to believe, give up their rights and have the  
government tell people whether they can or cannot be married?  I'm  
sorry, it should be the other way around.  That's private information  
between two people, and the government shouldn't be involved at all,  
lest it come up in a civil court case.

How about a ballot initiative that is an amendment to the state  
constitution requiring the state marriage license program to be  
voluntary-based?

What you're talking about is not concerted voter oppression.  If you counted
what you're saying as voter oppression, it'd essentially be in the tens of
millions, with both sides being equally guilty I'm sure.  In recent decades,
most cases of voter suppression (in an organized sense) have lead back to
the Republican Party.  Mind you, as the article points out, it was the
dixiecrats of the Republican party who campaigned on large scale voter
suppression following the civil war, and one would have to say they were
quite successful at it.

Greg Palast is really the expert on vote fraud *and* vote  
suppression.  He's written quite a few books on this subject, and  
Armed Madhouse clearly lays out exactly how the election of both 2000  
and 2004 were stolen through a combination of vote fraud and vote  
oppression, i.e., rolling mass amounts of people off the voter rolls,  
not having enough machines, there were some instances of people  
showing up at the polls and being told they had already voted, then  
when they objected, they were told to come back later, and magically  
they could vote.

But these voting machines are still in like 40% of the country.  And  
even if your district doesn't have electronic machines, they still  
normally have those electronic scanning machines, those can be thrown  
too, though not as easily as the computerized systems, which can be  
hacked using wifi technology.  If we were a really smart body of  
people, we would get in small groups and start monitoring the polls.   
Remember, this same system of fraud gave us George Bush, we need to  
reclaim fair elections in this country if there is any hope of real  
change for the betterment of humanity, which I believe the finance  
oligarchs know is coming, and are scared to death of it.

cutter liberal or conservative, you have to choose to ignore things  
that go against the unrealistic rigidness of those two ideologies.

THE ENIGMA OF THE =E2=80=98PHAESTOS DISC=E2=80=99

It was on July 3, 1908 =E2=80=94 exactly one hundred years ago =E2=80=94 tha=
t an =20
Italian archaeologist, excavating a Minoan site in southern Crete =20
called Phaestos, discovered in its ruins a clay disc bearing unknown =20
symbols on both sides.

The discovered object, a disc about 4.5 inches in diameter, has since =20
come to be known as The Phaestos Disc; and for a century now has =20
baffled all who tried to unravel its mystery:  For there has been =20
found no other object like it, no writing as its pictographs, no =20
inkling regarding its language, or to what people it owes its =20
existence. Yet there it is, for anyone interested to see, in Crete=E2=80=99s=
 =20
Iraklion Museum.

On one of my Earth Chronicles Expeditions tours, we went to Crete.  A =20
must see are the ruins of Knossos, the Minoan capital excavated by Sir =20
Arthur Evans. We also went to the Museum to see the disc; and I told =20
the guide: I want to visit Phaestos.  No one goes there, she said; =20
there is nothing there to see, she said =E2=80=94 just ruins of some =20
buildings.  But I insisted: There=E2=80=99s something on the disc that =20
intrigues me!

We intended to spend a quick one hour there; we ended up being there =20
the whole day. It was a day of thrilling discoveries.  These were not =20
just =E2=80=9Csome buildings.=E2=80=9D  We found merchants=E2=80=99 stalls, =
each identified =20
with stone blocks inscribed with product symbols.  We found evidence =20
that the place was a copper processing facility, that it had a =20
connecting slideway to the seashore below.  This was a commercial and =20
industrial center, next to sea lanes!

What was it about the disc that made me want to come here? Our guide =20
asked.  Contrary to accepted wisdom that the disc=E2=80=99s pictographs are =
=20
unique, I said, I have seen some of them before: Ships and men with a =20
plumed headdress - in Egypt and in Mayan Chichen Itza in Mexico!

You can read more about my guess that they were the mysterious =E2=80=9CPeop=
le =20
of the Sea=E2=80=9D and might have reached the Mediterranean from the =20
Americas, in my book The Earth Chronicles Expeditions.  It=E2=80=99s an =20
appropriate centennial anniversary thriller.

Umm, yea, I kind of stayed away from Zecharia Sitchin for a long =20
time, the first time I heard about him was 10 years ago when I had a =20
job in Berkeley, and this guy that worked there was talking about it, =20=

and I thought he was strange, so I kind of glossed over it.  So, see, =20=

I am susceptible to influences just like anyone else is.

Now we fast forward to a month or two ago when I heard Jordan Maxwell =20=

being interviewed, found some of the things about esoteric symbols =20
placed in plain day for everyone to see, like the fasci bundle of =20
sticks that is on the stage of the Congress, that is apparently a =20
Roman symbol standing for facism.  And of course, the dollar bill, =20
etc.  Jordan has spent 45 years doing this kind of research, and his =20
wife left him because of it.  Shame on her.

Anyway, I watched another video he was in giving a talk, just type in =20=

Jordan Maxwell and there are hundreds of videos with him, where he =20
talks about how they are digging up things like utensils not from the =20=

bed of the seafloor, but from *underground* when they are drilling =20
for oil.  Is this true?  I think it's interesting if it is.

Then he also referenced that there is something coming toward Earth =20
that is already visible in the Southern Hemisphere.  Some kind of red =20=

spot.  The only thing about this, though, is if you watch the video, =20
there is basically one youtube account out there putting this stuff =20
up, with supposed pictures from the telescope in Antarctica.  That =20
video explains the trajectory of the orbit of Planet X, which some =20
say is a brown dwarf, a long elliptical orbit at perhaps a 30 degree =20
angle from our ecliptic plane.  So if all this stuff is true, we will =20=

all be able to see this big red spot starting next year, and guess =20
when they say this big red spot will happen to be here?

You guessed it.  December 21, 2012.  Laugh at it, love it, or leave =20
it.  Who cares.  The other thing I don't care so much for with these =20
videos is they start spewing out all this nonsense that the =20
government knows Planet X is coming and they've already selected all =20
the people that are going to be taken underground until the crisis =20
passes, and somehow this is a good thing that the government is doing =20=

it all in secret to prevent panic.  How the hell does this guy know =20
all this stuff?

Anyway, maybe we should have a QOD 2012 countdown.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP:  10/24/08 - NO on Prop 8 fundraiser party (FnF/Ambient Mafia)

Hey Everyone,

As you know, we're doing a "No on 8" Fundraiser with the
Friends and Family crew this Friday.

We've got a great lineup, and the party's for a good cause. 
There are easily over 1,000,000 LGBT's in California and unless
everyone starts stepping up and donating, equal marriage will
lose on Nov. 4th. Polling shows that amongst those who've seen
commercials both pro and against Prop 8, the amendment loses!
That's great news, which is all the more reason to get as much
$$ into the No on 8 Campaign as soon as possible.

Please come out and support!

--------

THIS Friday, October 24th, 2008
Friends & Family and the Ambient Mafia Present:
Equality ~ A Fundraiser for No on Prop 8

Please join us for a very special evening of music, dance, and
performance dedicated to raising awareness and funds to defend
marriage equality and defeat Prop 8.

Your Musical Equalizers:
* Forest Green (FnF, ForestGreen.org, Cute Fang Recordings,
myspace.com/forestgreen, Cute Things with Fangs, Daly City
Records)
* Dragn'fly (Strategik, djdragnfly.com, myspace.com/dragnfly)
* Mozaic (Nexus, Raindance)
* Raydeus (Pronoia)
* Alixr (FnF, Pulse, myspace.com/djalixr)
* Dhamma (Goodbeats, Pulse)

And a Very Special Encore PoiPlay Performance by Jm and the
PoiPlay Troupe! (www.poiplay.com)

Venue: Craneway Pavilion (www.craneway.com)
Shuttle Service from El Cerrito Del Norte BART

Chill Space by the Ambient Mafia (www.ambientmafia.com)
Sound by Bay Area Sound Service & Loud Sound Design
Lighting by Radiant Atmospheres
Medical Services Provided by Mutual Aid Response Services
(www.medicalresponse.org)

9pm till 6am, All Ages, 21+ to drink, $20 minimum donation at
the door, $5 parking.

Please check our website often for updates on guest speakers,
entertainment, and presale tix:  www.eccentric.org

All proceeds after expenses go directly to No on Prop 8. For
more info on the campaign please visit: www.noonprop8.com

the bill to see if there are any hidden agendas promoting things like  
the Animal ID Act which is really geared to shut down the family farm

like it would make things like free range eggs mandatory by law.   
Morally, probably a good thing.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: [political] Prop 2

Hmm, I' started here: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proposition_2

FWIW I already buy all cage free eggs and won't eat veal. 

One thing to consider might be the negative economic effects, which opponents suggest might cost the state over 3000 jobs.  While that seems to me to be somewhat overstated, it certainly would cost money to implement this law and that would either be passed on to the consumer (highly likely) and/or result in some egg production moving out of the state to locations where the law doesn't apply.  Voting for higher food prices seems like a bad idea to me right now, but I haven't voted yet.

If you are looking for an opposing viewpoint from an animal rights advocate read this: http://www.abolitionistapproach.com/?p=165

Peter

The Republican Party is the best thing that ever happened to the Democrats.

Numbers don't lie, the Dems have the majority of Governorships, State
Legislatures, Congress and The US Senate, and have for the last 2 years now,
except for the Presidency, and all those positions are expected to increase
by a significant margin in all those above categories.

Sarah Palin injected $150+ million into Obama's campaign just by being her
simple, down-home sexy self, and as a result of this fools comments her
Democratic opponent *for her Congressional seat, * *Elwyn Tinklenberg *of
Minnesota took just one weekend to raise just under a $1 million bucks for
his campaign, when it took him over a full year to raise his first million.

Al Franken for Senator in that State has been a long-shot from day one, but
he just moved up dramatically in the last month on the IEM:

http://www.biz.uiowa.edu/iem/markets/data_MNSen08.html
http://iemweb.biz.uiowa.edu/graphs/graph_MNSen08_WTA.cfm

This is largely because Franken's opponent, the current incumbent has been
running smear/character assasination ads and the voters there are just fed
up with that approach.

That sound you're hearing over the incessant backfiring of the Republican
campaigns nationwide is the sound of ropes and pulleys moving at a rapid
rate of speed as these assholes are getting lifted by their own petards, all
across the fruited plain, and from sea to motherfucking shining sea.

Couldn't happen to a better class of people, and I mean that in the nicest
way.

I can't stand sitting back and lurking anymore.
deepSMOG, you are intellectually void. You ramble in re-processed,
combination talking points. You believe any conspiracy theory, formulated as
they are by psychological salesmen, to pander to the C- crowd. A group of
the public who believes they are the A+ crowd, as they are too stupid to
understand that they are actually quite ignorant.. Your words are
meaningless, attempting to impress, and without logic.  You appear to be a
semi-uneducated military brat who grew up in a catholic household, having
closeted himself away, so as to avoid defaming his parents and thus shutting
off the flow of support.
Your kindergarten theory (in a previous rant)  is a perfect example of  you
perverse, wanna-be hippy, self-righteous blather. Pitch perfect with the
logic associated with the crazies who entertain on the soapbox in the square
at UCB.

To clarify: Nothing happens in a two party system where the executive branch
is in contrary motion to the legislative. It is so naive to believe that the
checks and balance system engineered 200+ years ago is rational in todays
climate. It is a righteous idea, but not working at the moment for many
reasons. If only they would amend Robert's Rules, to adjust for, and to
dismantle, the silent veto via a filibuster. Then, the checks and balances
you naively believe in would prove true. As of now, they are as broken as
earmarks, and the complete lack of Politics in politics.

What we do need is a vibrant young set of idealist politicians practicing a
craft lost to the slack-jawed, dim-witted people voting for us in Congress
and the Senate. Politics is an art born with communication and fine tuned by
"The Game of Houses" in the Roman Era, or the "Art of Courtly Love" in the
age of adventure. We need SMART, well-intentioned leaders, acting in the
common good, without reciprocity or self-interest to lead us into the
future. We need a reset, a fundamental change, an era of single-minded
coming together for the common good, while separating idealism from
fanaticism. We need to be better, cheer the elite, the smart, the warrior,
and the worker. We must end this sickening era where commoners have come to
power, and destroyed our civilization. Their ideas have proven ill-fated ans
narrow-minded. They need to be heard by others, not speaking for many.

Don't wish for a friend or Joe anybody to rule and make rules. Pray for
genius, ingenuity, tact, and skill as an orator. Hope that soon, common
people will again look to the Elitists for a remarkable new era, and stop
wishing for a man/woman they would like to chill with or fuck as the leader
of the free world.

We are an international joke. The Europeans seek elite leadership, and feel
pride when their leaders speak. They have a right to look down their noses
at us, as they are at this time better than we.

We are all patriots by birth. Nothing you say or do can change that. Rage
against the machine and you are as patriotic as a warrior, for in your rage
you expose our reason d'etre, and thus display your patriotism not by words,
but by the rights you evoke.

SO deepSMOG, you are no elitist. You are certainly not someone I would like
to have supper with. You were never "an old school SF DJ" as you often
claim. You are smog. You are smug. You are beatle beneath an off balance
boulder. SQUISH.

> you naively believe in would prove true. As of now, they are as  
> broken as
> earmarks, and the complete lack of Politics in politics.
>
> What we do need is a vibrant young set of idealist politicians  
> practicing a
> craft lost to the slack-jawed, dim-witted people voting for us in  
> Congress
> and the Senate. Politics is an art born with communication and fine  
> tuned by
> "The Game of Houses" in the Roman Era, or the "Art of Courtly Love"  
> in the
> age of adventure. We need SMART, well-intentioned leaders, acting  
> in the
> common good, without reciprocity or self-interest to lead us into the
> future. We need a reset, a fundamental change, an era of single-minded
> coming together for the common good, while separating idealism from
> fanaticism. We need to be better, cheer the elite, the smart, the  
> warrior,
> and the worker. We must end this sickening era where commoners have  
> come to
> power, and destroyed our civilization. Their ideas have proven ill- 
> fated ans
> narrow-minded. They need to be heard by others, not speaking for many.
>
> Don't wish for a friend or Joe anybody to rule and make rules. Pray  
> for
> genius, ingenuity, tact, and skill as an orator. Hope that soon,  
> common
> people will again look to the Elitists for a remarkable new era,  
> and stop
> wishing for a man/woman they would like to chill with or fuck as  
> the leader
> of the free world.
>
> We are an international joke. The Europeans seek elite leadership,  
> and feel
> pride when their leaders speak. They have a right to look down  
> their noses
> at us, as they are at this time better than we.
>
> We are all patriots by birth. Nothing you say or do can change  
> that. Rage
> against the machine and you are as patriotic as a warrior, for in  
> your rage
> you expose our reason d'etre, and thus display your patriotism not  
> by words,
> but by the rights you evoke.
>
> SO deepSMOG, you are no elitist. You are certainly not someone I  
> would like
> to have supper with. You were never "an old school SF DJ" as you often
> claim. You are smog. You are smug. You are beatle beneath an off  
> balance
> boulder. SQUISH.
