Subject: [sfraves] [BSP] 24 October (this friday!) Heroic Robot! Lil Roj! Forest Green! Snoek! No On 8!


Friday, 24 October 2008

RAY presents: 

F A K T I O N : san francisco's fastest growing techno cult!

Friday, 26 September 2008:
LIL ROJ: SubSensory [ Portland ]
FOREST GREEN: CuteFang|FnF|Faktion|SisterSF|DEF [ SF ]
SNOEK: Sick!|GoodBadGuy [ SF ]
live webcast via Radio Integrated!
visuals by HEROIC ROBOT!

LIL ROJ: Originally from the Big Easy, Lil Roj has been touring the US for a
decade now, making dance floors bump in big clubs and underground warehouse
alike.  Currently living in Portland, Roj is a superlative example of how
West Coast Techno challenges the bigger known regions with quality over
quantity.

FOREST GREEN: Standard bearer for techno in San Francisco through even its
most silent days, Forest remains one of the busiest DJs in this city by the
bay, yet always manages to make each set a fresh and unique experience.
Recently returning to focus on production, she's still known for her ability
to select and mix tracks that get every audience dancing.

SNOEK: Having played in locales as diverse as the Netherlands and the Middle
East, Snoek, aka That Fucking Guy/Meekrob heads up his own parties yet remains
humble and works tirelessly to further the local techno scene any way he can.



OK folks, with the election looming, we've found ourselves with a bit of a
decision to make.  We're certainly not trying to tell anyone else how to
feel politically.  We do, however, see a rather significant issue.  When
the state supreme court made its decision on gay marriage, it made the rather
clear statement that did so based on equal enforcement of the law, a basic
tenet of the state constitution.  If proposition 8 is allowed to pass, it
actually sets the rather dangerous precedent of saying a simple vote can
overturn basic constitutional rights simply because there is some tradition
in support of discriminating, whether it be on race, sex, age or anything
else.  This is something we cannot simply ignore, proceeds after expenses
from this month's Faktion, will go to support the No On Proposition 8
campaign.  What expenses?  Well, we're not just bringing out a bunch of free
local DJs for your money, we're flying LIL ROJ in from Portland!  Roj has
been playing in various locales in the US for a decade, but this will be his
first SF appearance.  We've also got local representation with Faktion
resident FOREST GREEN, who'll be playing 2 NoOn8 parties in one night
(Another party is happening in the east bay if you can't make it to SF),
and Sick! mastermind SNOEK coming in.  HEROIC ROBOT returns again with their
uniquely innovative visual style all night!



4th Fridays @ Anu

Anu-Bar 
43 Sixth St., San Francisco, CA
10 PM to 2 AM 21+
Cost: $5 donation, additional donations accepted for NoOn8 Campaign.

Official Site: http://www.faktionsf.com/
Official Site: http://www.heroicrobot.com/
Official Site: http://www.radiointegrated.com/
Official Site: http://www.noonprop8.com/

 
///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
 

---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: [sfraves] RSVP: Sunday 10-26 Fritz Lang vs. Jeff Mills  "Metropolis"

Since everyone's BSPing like mad for what's shaping up to be a nice 
weekend for techno.. Pulse on Thurs, Faktion on Fri.. I thought I would 
add to the mix and invite some people over this Sunday (10-26) for a 
video projector screening of the silent film epic:

*Metropolis*
directed by Fritz Lang 1927
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NarN046dDOQ

with the soundtrack thankfully removed and replaced by none other than

Jeff Mills ambient soundtrack: "Metropolis"
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BDh5h8QWL8c

Screening starts at 10pm this Sunday at the Bliss Factory Studio loft 
and will be followed by music and random debauchery.

If you would like to participate in the screening. Please contact me for 
directly for directions. Please be prepared to bring your own lawn 
chairs and enough byob and snacks to share.


respect,
Sean

More blabber.
You are just an insignificant, fat little troll, who spreads his meaningless
blabber via a QOTD to a music and culture list. You have more time to spend
than any 40 year old virgin should have on his hands. In the RAVE Scene, you
were never relevant. Even less so now. You are idea-less. So un-creative
that you miss the mocking of the term patriot, even when it is spelled out
so soundly in metaphor.

Your drivel about being a significant old school SF DJ is actually well
documented on SFR. Most recently in the era of your failed attempts at
writing critical reviews, which you posted to your own website, pretending
to have published them.

The most irritating and offensive part of your spittle, is the simple fact
that you seem to believe you are a philosopher. The fatal flaw, you create a
claim, find a ludicrous miscreant ranter to site as source, and thus reverse
engineer a supposed thought. Rather, you ought to immerse yourself in facts,
drink in the editorial, think about the psychology of mass manipulation, and
then derive a statement that has value and merit. Still, as shallow as your
thoughts are, when you find yourself coming to the same conclusions as the
"spin room," spare us your rant. Start over. When one day you come to
understand the fabric of population control ( government), when you start to
see the threads in the weave, and can understand what else unravels by
pulling a single thread from the weave,  only then will you understand the
irritation created by your prolific attempts at "being all smart and stuff."

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: first/last word on Palin

OK, this should be the last word on Sarah Palin, and in a way it's the
first.  This is her hometown, where she's from.

You probably heard of her saying a day or two ago that the SMALL towns are
the PRO-American parts of the country, where the REAL Americans live.  Jon
Stewart's show decided they should find out what she meant, and where better
than Wasilla!

http://crooksandliars.com/nicole-belle/daily-show-understanding-real-america

OK, so the footage of lunkheads and hypocritical christians are more
entertainment than news.  You can find them anywhere.  But then they
interview Dianne Keller, the current Mayor of Wasilla, by definition a
representative of the city, with obvious understanding of what it means to
be mayor there.  Get this:

* She says that being mayor there "absolutely" prepares one to be vice
president.  When asked, "how".  She's all moose in the headlights.

* The interviewer tries to help by suggesting some parallel between running
the fire department and some part of the US executive.  She says she doesn't
run the fire department.

* Then he tries a parallel with the schools.  She says she has nothing to do
with the schools.

* So what does she do?  On Mondays there's a staff meeting.  Thursday she
signs all the checks...

Oh yeah, they also DO interview a member of the Independence Party, who lets
it all hang out vis-a-vis being anti-American.

Sarah Palin's main elected experience (4 years vs 2 as governor) is running
a backwater with malls and churches, that doesn't even have a fire
department.  Her husband was until recently a member of the Independence
Party, which is BY DEFINITION anti-American.  After she became mayor, the
local police (which she DID control) started charging rape victims for their
"rape kits" (for gathering evidence).  She opposes all sex education except
the "abstinence only" sort, and look what that's done to Alaska's teen
pregnancy rate and her own family.  Just yesterday, she answered the
question of a third grader, "What does the vice president do" and answered
that he/she is IN CHARGE of the Senate.  Unbelievable but true!
     http://thinkprogress.org/2008/10/21/palin-vp-senate/

How can ANYONE vote for a ticket with this person on it!



--

Subject: Re: [sfraves] deepSMOG and the void. I cannot lurk anymore.

I was just about to write this reply when I saw yours further down the
thread. The messages Deepfog sends to this list are sprinkled with a
crunchy collection of hate, fear, and insanity. When I skim that crap
(I can't help it, I sometimes even read my viagra spam) I occasionally
get caught by what I think is a salient point... only to realize its a
bunch of twisted-up spin doctor shit, piggy backing twenty pounds of
completely unrelated madnesses on the bent back of a valid
observation.

Homeboy is obviously out of line with his vitriol, but it seems like
the guy is genuinely pissed off after years of reading this stuff. I
get only a little annoyed, but that's because I assumed nobody but my
dumb ass is reading this shit. God forbid DF actually find an audience
for his propaganda.

Subject: [sfraves] TOMORROW!  FnF/AM - no on 8 fundraiser (east bay)

Hey Folx!

I know it's goint to be on a Friday night and all, and there's
probably something you don't want to miss on the TV.  But this
is an important issue that really needs our help.  You can set
your Tivo and watch it later this weekend.  ;)

Hope to see you here!

---

Friday October 24th, 2008

Friends & Family and The Ambient Mafia Present:

Equality ~ A Fundraiser for No on Prop 8

Please join us for a very special evening of music, dance, and
performance dedicated to raising awareness and funds to defend
marriage equality and defeat Prop 8!

Main Room Musical Equalizers:

    * Forest Green (Friends & Family, ForestGreen.org, Cute
Fang Recordings, myspace.com/forestgreen, Cute Things with
Fangs, Daly City Records)
    * Dragn'fly (Strategik, djdragnfly.com,
myspace.com/dragnfly)
    * Scott Carrelli (Satellite, Looq Records)
    * Mozaic (Nexus, Raindance)
    * Raydeus (Pronoia, raydeus.com)
    * Alixr (Friends & Family, Pulse, myspace.com/djalixr)
    * Dhamma (Goodbeats, Pulse)

Chill Space by Ambient Mafia: (www.ambientmafia.com)

    * Sixty4k
    * Hickory
    * Harken
    * Skye
    * Olde Nasty
    * Boomerang Fidget
    * Big Sloppy
    * Squelchy

Belly Dancing by Marcine (Bellydance Mafia)
Hooping by Queen Califia (www.hooppain.com)
And a Very Special Encore PoiPlay Performance by Jm and the
PoiPlay Troupe! (www.poiplay.com)

Guest Speakers Include:

    * Jos Cisneros, San Francisco City & County Treasurer
    * Shayna Gelender & Elizabeth Gill of ACLU Northern
California

Venue: Craneway Pavilion (www.craneway.com)
1414 Harbor Way South, Richmond
Shuttle Service from El Cerrito Del Norte BART
Event Info Line: (510) 495-1439

Sound by Bay Area Sound Service & Loud Sound Design
Lighting by Radiant Atmospheres
Visuals by Viberation
Medical Services Provided by Mutual Aid Response Services
(www.medicalresponse.org)

9pm till 6am, All Ages, 21+ to drink, $20 minimum donation at
the door, $5 secure parking.

Please check our website for entertainment updates and info on
BART shuttle schedule: www.eccentric.org

All proceeds after expenses go directly to No on Prop 8. For
more info on the campaign please visit: www.noonprop8.com

> checks and balance system engineered 200+ years ago is rational in todays
> climate. It is a righteous idea, but not working at the moment for many
> reasons. If only they would amend Robert's Rules, to adjust for, and to
> dismantle, the silent veto via a filibuster. Then, the checks and balances
> you naively believe in would prove true. As of now, they are as broken as
> earmarks, and the complete lack of Politics in politics.
>
> What we do need is a vibrant young set of idealist politicians practicing a
> craft lost to the slack-jawed, dim-witted people voting for us in Congress
> and the Senate. Politics is an art born with communication and fine tuned by
> "The Game of Houses" in the Roman Era, or the "Art of Courtly Love" in the
> age of adventure. We need SMART, well-intentioned leaders, acting in the
> common good, without reciprocity or self-interest to lead us into the
> future. We need a reset, a fundamental change, an era of single-minded
> coming together for the common good, while separating idealism from
> fanaticism. We need to be better, cheer the elite, the smart, the warrior,
> and the worker. We must end this sickening era where commoners have come to
> power, and destroyed our civilization. Their ideas have proven ill-fated ans
> narrow-minded. They need to be heard by others, not speaking for many.
>
> Don't wish for a friend or Joe anybody to rule and make rules. Pray for
> genius, ingenuity, tact, and skill as an orator. Hope that soon, common
> people will again look to the Elitists for a remarkable new era, and stop
> wishing for a man/woman they would like to chill with or fuck as the leader
> of the free world.
>
> We are an international joke. The Europeans seek elite leadership, and feel
> pride when their leaders speak. They have a right to look down their noses
> at us, as they are at this time better than we.
>
> We are all patriots by birth. Nothing you say or do can change that. Rage
> against the machine and you are as patriotic as a warrior, for in your rage
> you expose our reason d'etre, and thus display your patriotism not by words,
> but by the rights you evoke.
>
> SO deepSMOG, you are no elitist. You are certainly not someone I would like
> to have supper with. You were never "an old school SF DJ" as you often
> claim. You are smog. You are smug. You are beatle beneath an off balance
> boulder. SQUISH.
>
>   

---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

after this yummy ride on the N Judah with the guy who color coordinates
his clothes & this Nice old lady & the Hippy Geek who gave up his seat to
the old lady... and the mean girl who wouldn't shut the fuck up &
complained about eeeeeeeeeverything & her friend who stood in front of her
ignoring her... anywaze, yeah... i spent the eary part of the eveningin

with the author of the book "Stuff White People Like", ummm, Christain
Lander I think his name is...

book, the book discussion, & just the whole dealie at the bookstore. I
mean... it totally just validates me telling a white person to stop acting
white >:)  LoL.. jokingly of course :) LoL! But yeah, it got kinda
annoying afterwards when i was in line to get his signing thingie (& I had
to use the flyer 'cause I couldn't buy a book), like all everyone wwho was
around me had like their normal conversations, but would add "that's
something that white people like too"... LoL, yeah

So I bussed it down Lower Haight & went to UGSF & Wow.. it was soo much
fun!!  Like I mean... it wasn't packed house like I was hoping 'cause
hella people who said they were gonna be there weren't... but I mean..
it's all good :)  I mean.. I just hope that they're all alright and stuff
:)

But yeah.. it was a Raga Jungle night... the only DJ that didn't spin Raga
was Eskae & he dropped like alot ummm... like dubby kinda stuff, some
liquid, & alota atmo!  I tried dancing as much as possible.. but like with
raga, it's kinda hard.. but it was still fun :)  Yeah man.. & the energy
of the crowd that night was Awesome!!!  I mean

I didn't get too wasted, like i got really buzzed at 1 point & that was
it!!  BUt yeah.. so many yummy people showed & it was a fuckin' Groovy ass
time!!!  To people on the list who made it, Thank U Millions 4 sharing
that Groovy fuckin' night with me!!!  Oh My Goodness.. even Chazz Fuckin'
Gold showed up & gave me a yummy present.

Oooh... yeah.. afterwards I kinda ended up at Ray & Nico's pad & like
chilled there for a long while playing with my wallet chain, chillin' with
Ray, watching the whole 1st season of Futurama, & chatting with Homies in
the chat rooms... I got to hang out with Nico for like 1/2 hour, then got
home at some point on Sunday.. Hello 2day!!

Yeah... it was a good yummy Birthday!!!  Thanks again everyone for the
Groovy wishes & calls & stuff!!

Subject: [sfraves] BSP - Tonal: Grinch Green - Saturday 12/13/08!

Rock It Science & Prismatic present:

Tonal: Grinch Green

Saturday, December 13th

---

Every dancer down in Tonal-ville
Liked undergrounds a lot...
But the Grinch, who lived just north of Tonal-ville
Did NOT!  

The Grinch hated undergrounds!
The whole underground season!
Now, please don't ask why.
No one quite knows the reason.

It could be his head
Wasn't screwed on just right.
It could be, perhaps, that his shoes
Were too tight.

But I think that the most likely
Reason of all
May have been that his heart
Was two sizes too small.

He hated the NOISE!
NOISE! NOISE! NOISE!

The dancers, young and old, 
Would get down to the beat.
Pop, slide and groove to the BEAT!
BEAT! BEAT! BEAT!

They would dance to Tonal DJs
In fresh venues for the season
Which was something the Grinch
Couldn't stand for no reason! 

But one day the Grinch 
Snuck into Tonal through the back door
And felt the bass of dance music
Rising up through the floor

"That's a noise," grinned the Grinch
"That I simply MUST hear!"
So he paused.
And the Grinch put his hand to his ear.

And he did hear a sound
Consuming the place.
A beat resonating
All over the space. 

But the sound wasn't sad!
Why, this sound sounded merry!
It couldn't be so!
But it WAS merry! VERY! 

He stared down at Tonal-ville!
The Grinch popped his eyes!
Then he shook!
What he saw was a shocking surprise! 

Every dancer down in Tonal-ville
The tall and the small
Was getting down in unison!
The love of music was filling them all! 

And what happened then...?
Well...in Tonal-ville they say
That the Grinch
Got down to house music that day! 

---

Full lineup to be announced soon!


---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

> And the Grinch put his hand to his ear.
>
> And he did hear a sound
> Consuming the place.
> A beat resonating
> All over the space.
>
> But the sound wasn't sad!
> Why, this sound sounded merry!
> It couldn't be so!
> But it WAS merry! VERY!
>
> He stared down at Tonal-ville!
> The Grinch popped his eyes!
> Then he shook!
> What he saw was a shocking surprise!
>
> Every dancer down in Tonal-ville
> The tall and the small
> Was getting down in unison!
> The love of music was filling them all!
>
> And what happened then...?
> Well...in Tonal-ville they say
> That the Grinch
> Got down to house music that day!
>
> ---
>
> Full lineup to be announced soon!
>
>
> ---------------------------------------------------------------------
> To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
> For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org
>
>
>
>

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

The US is:  "...a nation of 200 million used-car salesmen with all the  
money we need to buy guns and no qualms about killing anybody else in  
the world who tries to make us uncomfortable."
-Hunter S. Thompson

"Friend, hope for the truth while you are alive.  Jump into experience  
while you are alive!  What you call "salvation" belongs to the time  
before death.  If you don't break your ropes while you are alive, do  
you think ghosts will do it after?"
-Kabir

> >
> > Saturday, December 13th
> >
> > ---
> >
> > Every dancer down in Tonal-ville
> > Liked undergrounds a lot...
> > But the Grinch, who lived just north of Tonal-ville
> > Did NOT!
> >
> > The Grinch hated undergrounds!
> > The whole underground season!
> > Now, please don't ask why.
> > No one quite knows the reason.
> >
> > It could be his head
> > Wasn't screwed on just right.
> > It could be, perhaps, that his shoes
> > Were too tight.
> >
> > But I think that the most likely
> > Reason of all
> > May have been that his heart
> > Was two sizes too small.
> >
> > He hated the NOISE!
> > NOISE! NOISE! NOISE!
> >
> > The dancers, young and old,
> > Would get down to the beat.
> > Pop, slide and groove to the BEAT!
> > BEAT! BEAT! BEAT!
> >
> > They would dance to Tonal DJs
> > In fresh venues for the season
> > Which was something the Grinch
> > Couldn't stand for no reason!
> >
> > But one day the Grinch
> > Snuck into Tonal through the back door
> > And felt the bass of dance music
> > Rising up through the floor
> >
> > "That's a noise," grinned the Grinch
> > "That I simply MUST hear!"
> > So he paused.
> > And the Grinch put his hand to his ear.
> >
> > And he did hear a sound
> > Consuming the place.
> > A beat resonating
> > All over the space.
> >
> > But the sound wasn't sad!
> > Why, this sound sounded merry!
> > It couldn't be so!
> > But it WAS merry! VERY!
> >
> > He stared down at Tonal-ville!
> > The Grinch popped his eyes!
> > Then he shook!
> > What he saw was a shocking surprise!
> >
> > Every dancer down in Tonal-ville
> > The tall and the small
> > Was getting down in unison!
> > The love of music was filling them all!
> >
> > And what happened then...?
> > Well...in Tonal-ville they say
> > That the Grinch
> > Got down to house music that day!
> >
> > ---
> >
> > Full lineup to be announced soon!

that there's a right and wrong=2C
and that punishment
would come to those
who dare to cross the line.
   =20

     for jerk-offs like you.

     but I'm tired of waiting.

     Maybe it's just bullshit and I should play GOD=2C

     and shoot you myself.

     Because I'm tired of waiting.

     our course of action

     my course of action

Saw this cat at the DEMF this year and he rocked the
shit out of the place. Everywhere he goes he leaves the

_________________________________


Saturday, November 1st, 2008

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 1st Saturday at The Endup


featuring from Barcelona, Spain:

PACO OSUNA  - 3 hour DJ set

(plus 8 . zenit . mindshake . m_nus . ovum)

In the last several years, Paco Osuna has made a
steady ascent from "Paco who?" to one of the most
in-demand headliners on the international scene.
Starting his DJ career in the mid 90's, his mastery
behind 3 decks and unconventional sense of groove
soon landed him a  residency at Ibiza's famed
Amnesia club, where he continued to hone his craft
alongside Sven Vath and other elite DJs. His
famously intense sets, which fuse the best of
techno and house in a dramatic ride of tension-
building and release, have won him prime slots at
most major international clubs and music festivals
including Sonar, Love Parade, WMC, and the DEMF,
to name just a few. If you're a fan of peak hour
"hard minimal" a la Richie Hawtin, Marco Carola,
and Adam Beyer, Paco's 3 hour SF debut is
something you definitely don't want to miss!


with [KONTROL] residents:

CRAIG KUNA  (platform . esdjco)

ALLAND BYALLO  (nightlight . auralism . leibe*detail)

NIKOLA BAYTALA  (s.w.a.t. . robsoul . junior boys own)

SAMMY D  (dirtybird . utensil . magnificent 7)


____________________________________________________


The ENDUP
401 6th St @ Harrison, SF
10pm - 6am / 21+ / $15
http://www.theendup.com

FREE before 11pm!

____________________________________________________


Full bios, pics and FREE music:
http://www.kontrolsf.com

[KONTROL] on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/kontrolsf

Flyer front:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K41/K41F.jpg

Flyer back:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K41/K41B.jpg

Poster:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K41/K41P.jpg

___________________________________________________


PACO OSUNA (aka Osuna, Smoke Paper Inc.)

Paco Osuna Perez was born in Barcelona in 1974, and his passion for music
started out when he was very young. At the tender age of 14 he was part of =
a
regular crowd at Studio 54, where the most charismatic DJ, Raul Orellana,
was spinning Acid House, marking Paco in the way of understanding DJing. In
'94 Paco moved to Valencia where he had his first contact with the decks as
a hobby. In '95 Paco made his first DJ set as a professional at the ACTV
club, where he gained a year residency. After that, he started playing in
many different clubs including Heaven and Universal.

In the meanwhile he worked in a record shop, where he got access to a
recording studio in which he produced three singles for the label Lucas
Records. In '99 he got a residency at Amnesia in Ibiza. There he had the
brilliant opportunity to be lined up with the biggest DJs and could learn
the different styles, looking to build his own. Amnesia was also the place
where Paco got in touch with the person who most influenced his future as
much personally as professionally, Sven V=E4th, who soon discovered Paco to=
 be
very talented and introduced him in his Cocoon Booking agency. Paco was the
first Spanish DJ to play for this prestigious agency.

In 2001 Paco decided to migrate away from House music, moving closer to
Techno. From then on his career has gotten better and better, leading him t=
o
the best clubs and festivals in the world. Being at home in both House and
Techno, as well as in the fusion between them, Paco Osuna understands his
sets as an "in-crescendo"-journey causing variations of tension that drive
the dancefloor crazy. The combination of this factor and his unquestionable
technical skills has led to Paco being considered one of the most solid
promises of the international scene.

Anyone know what's up with "Ghost Ship"?

I just got an email about this party.  It's supposedly the night after  
halloween; which is good, because I'm taking my CCNA class every  
saturday morning for the rest of this semester, so going out on the  
31st itself is out this time around.  It's also supposedly within  
walking distance of my house... a rarity, but a plus.  And I've no  
inclination to cart myself out to richmond (ugh) for Skills this time  
around (Last time I went to a party out thataways, the locals broke  
into better than half the cars, and a couple of people I know got  
mugged.).  So I'm considering it.

But the guy who emailed me isn't always the most up to speed on  
upcoming parties; I don't see a BSP in my SFRaves folder; nor do I see  
mention of it on Bayraves.  I've never heard of the crew before and  
aside from Aaron Jae and Bam, the advertised DJ lineup is mostly  
unfamiliar too... but hey... I can WALK there and home!

So I figured I'd ask here first in case it was the sort of party that  
shouldn't be known about on bayraves.  (But being in an airplane  
hangar would seem to indicate it's at least a mini-massive and right  
up BR's alley.)  Anyone know anything useful?

Good?  Bad?  So-so?
Go?  Stay away?  Take a chance?
Ask on Bayraves?

Thanks!


cya,

looking like a great event, with the Rondo Brothers doing the
after party. I'm really looking forward to seeing them, as I've
made a live mashup with one of their songs (a remix by Dan the
Automator).

http://www.genart.org/event.view.htm?itemid=2367&

Thursday, October 30
7:00 - 8:00pm: VIP Reception
8:00  Midnight: Runway Show & After Party

The Regency Center
1300 Van Ness @ Sutter Street
San Francisco, CA

Gen Art invites you to the legendary Fresh Faces in Fashion,
showcasing cutting-edge womenswear and menswear designers on a
60-foot runway for an audience of over 1,000 fashion industry
insiders and design aficionados. A post-party will take place
in the Sutter Room of the Regency Center directly following,
featuring Fresh Faces accessories designers, DJ, and
complimentary cocktails.

Don't miss the show that debuted designers including Zac Posen,
Rebecca Taylor, Shoshanna, Milly, Twinkle, Hollywould, Sari
Gueron and many others.

"Promises" by Fugazi

Words

Words and expressions

All these confessions

Of where we stand

How I see you

And you see me

Dedications of symmetry

Together we will be

forever.

Promises are shit

We speak the way we breathe

Present air will have to do

Rearrange and see it through

Stupid fucking words

They tangle us in our desires

Free me from this give and take

Free me from this great debate

There were no truer words than when spoken

Let that stand as it should

There was nothing left when broken

We grab anything when we fall

Promises are shit

We speak the way we breathe

Present air will have to do

Rearrange and see us through

Stupid fucking words

They tangle us in our desires

Free me from this give and take

Free me from this great debate

You will do what you do

I will do what I do

We will do what we do

Rearrange and see it through

Go where you think you want to go

Do everything you were sent here for

Fire at will if you hear that call

Touch your hand to the wall at night

Promises.

Words.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] TOTALLY RR! Check this shit out...

he's saying what i've been feeling about djing actually. djing is kind 
of pointless when you can get several thousand bucks a night touring as 
a live performer. i think djing served its merit when it was harder to 
carry your ELO style keyboard setup on the plane with you, but now that 
laptops serve as the main function for playing live.. (hell even i 
phones let you play live) and dj's play on laptops.. what's the 
difference? djs should contribute and make their own and be original. 
i've always found that djing's greatest trick was to be able to make 
music with two different tracks, to create an original sound. but 
essentially you have a greater power to do that on your own now at this 
point in history.

i will concede that djing is alot like curation and performing a set of 
tracks is like giving a gallery walk through; also deadmaus is wrong to 
have dissed every one on beatport from where he got his fame, but i do 
say he's got a valid point.

hypothetically, the problem i see with the change over to a purely a 
producer based genre, is the sheer amount of crap that will immediately 
fill the international market. beatport is a good example of this. but 
the solution to it would be to deal more with local artists and develop 
the local sound. from there the cream will rise to the top and those 
producers will travel as representatives of the SF electronic music 
sound. more peopleand djs will just collect tracks for their multi 
terabyte hard drives and more people will be fans of just the music 
rather than the awkward social climbing that goes along with DJing. only 
the truly talentled people will be allowed to survive as performers in 
the electronic music world. the rest will go onto free sites like what 
deviant art has become for artists.. just trying to get noticed. paying 
for music is already becoming obsolete.

short synopsus of how we got here loose chronological order:

    * how to dj books and videos flooded the market.
    * young kids realise its easy to be just like their trance hero.
      turntables outsell guitars (though food for thought here it takes
      2 turntable to become a tiesto dj, one guitar to become eddie van
      halen). the mystique of DJing is rendered obsolete.
    * digital music becomes cheap and easy to get making people wonder
      is it worth it to get a whitelabel.
    * laptop producing becomes a big thing
    * wiht the advent of a truly powerful pioneer cd player john digweed
      declares he will only play on cds
    * richie hawtin throws the djing world into complete confusion with
      final scratch
    * other companies rush to follow suit causing more confusion as well
      as a 15-20 minutes looking at a dj's dumpy ass setting up serato
      final scratch etc.
    * ableton live blurs the line between performing live and djing
    * richie hawtin again tries to justify the way he thinks about djing
      by pushing traktor which is essentially remixing and making music
      on the fly
    * deadmaus declares djing dead.
    * sean said told you so 2 years ago. i'm probably not the only one.

mike pickering was right way back when  he said you don't need bands to 
play live to make people dance.. but when the dj has become the band, 
then what? no dj.

deadmaus' hat is off the hook though. nice use of taplights as eyes.


respect.
sean.

>   * richie hawtin throws the djing world into complete confusion with
>     final scratch
>   * other companies rush to follow suit causing more confusion as well
>     as a 15-20 minutes looking at a dj's dumpy ass setting up serato
>     final scratch etc.
>   * ableton live blurs the line between performing live and djing
>   * richie hawtin again tries to justify the way he thinks about djing
>     by pushing traktor which is essentially remixing and making music
>     on the fly
>   * deadmaus declares djing dead.
>   * sean said told you so 2 years ago. i'm probably not the only one.
>

i agree that the music is the most important.. but point being, the way 
it is presented will be changing drastically in the next couple of 
years, and it would be best to advance your local scene artistically by 
being an originator in your own scene, rather than an ambassador of 
electronic music for another scene. that's my point.

> On Thu, Oct 30, 2008 at 1:28 PM, sean ocean <seanocean@defsf.com> wrote:
>
>   
>> he's saying what i've been feeling about djing actually. djing is kind of
>> pointless when you can get several thousand bucks a night touring as a live
>> performer. i think djing served its merit when it was harder to carry your
>> ELO style keyboard setup on the plane with you, but now that laptops serve
>> as the main function for playing live.. (hell even i phones let you play
>> live) and dj's play on laptops.. what's the difference? djs should
>> contribute and make their own and be original. i've always found that
>> djing's greatest trick was to be able to make music with two different
>> tracks, to create an original sound. but essentially you have a greater
>> power to do that on your own now at this point in history.
>>
>> i will concede that djing is alot like curation and performing a set of
>> tracks is like giving a gallery walk through; also deadmaus is wrong to have
>> dissed every one on beatport from where he got his fame, but i do say he's
>> got a valid point.
>>
>> hypothetically, the problem i see with the change over to a purely a
>> producer based genre, is the sheer amount of crap that will immediately fill
>> the international market. beatport is a good example of this. but the
>> solution to it would be to deal more with local artists and develop the
>> local sound. from there the cream will rise to the top and those producers
>> will travel as representatives of the SF electronic music sound. more
>> peopleand djs will just collect tracks for their multi terabyte hard drives
>> and more people will be fans of just the music rather than the awkward
>> social climbing that goes along with DJing. only the truly talentled people
>> will be allowed to survive as performers in the electronic music world. the
>> rest will go onto free sites like what deviant art has become for artists..
>> just trying to get noticed. paying for music is already becoming obsolete.
>>
>> short synopsus of how we got here loose chronological order:
>>
>>   * how to dj books and videos flooded the market.
>>   * young kids realise its easy to be just like their trance hero.
>>     turntables outsell guitars (though food for thought here it takes
>>     2 turntable to become a tiesto dj, one guitar to become eddie van
>>     halen). the mystique of DJing is rendered obsolete.
>>   * digital music becomes cheap and easy to get making people wonder
>>     is it worth it to get a whitelabel.
>>   * laptop producing becomes a big thing
>>   * wiht the advent of a truly powerful pioneer cd player john digweed
>>     declares he will only play on cds
>>   * richie hawtin throws the djing world into complete confusion with
>>     final scratch
>>   * other companies rush to follow suit causing more confusion as well
>>     as a 15-20 minutes looking at a dj's dumpy ass setting up serato
>>     final scratch etc.
>>   * ableton live blurs the line between performing live and djing
>>   * richie hawtin again tries to justify the way he thinks about djing
>>     by pushing traktor which is essentially remixing and making music
>>     on the fly
>>   * deadmaus declares djing dead.
>>   * sean said told you so 2 years ago. i'm probably not the only one.
>>
>> mike pickering was right way back when  he said you don't need bands to
>> play live to make people dance.. but when the dj has become the band, then
>> what? no dj.
>>
>> deadmaus' hat is off the hook though. nice use of taplights as eyes.

yes i know, it's everyone's
favorite holiday of the year. candy (yummy yummy candy) and costumes
and thwompy bass and you'd think that i'd be so excited about this
weekend i could hardly contain myself but there's this tunnel and the
light at the end of it is flickering and not so bright...

oh i
don't know what to do! i mean, i know what i'm doing this weekend and
i'm sure most of you have decided too... that's not the problem... i
just can't focus on what's directly ahead of me my mind keeps fast
forwarding to tuesday,=A0 quite possibly the most important day of any of
our lives so let me get this out of the way before i highlight a couple
of the many many events going on this weekend...

GO VOTE!!! if
you haven't already, and i know many of you have. yes i know many of
you don't believe it makes much difference if there's a democrat or a
republican in the white house but the symbolic importance of this
election trumps any concerns we might have about the realistic
possibility of change in government. swallow whatever third party
loving government needs to be destroyed what are they ever going to do
in DC that realistically helps the world ideology you subscribe to and GO V=
OTE!!!!

(and then come to mighty tuesday night for End Of an Error and dance and dr=
ink and hold your breath...)=20

okay, i feel a little better, having gotten that out of the way.=20


THURSDAY OCT. 30th


all epic weekends start on thursday, and this one is no different! take the=
 short bus to school!!!!

Trasnsported SF
from the bus stop (135 Dore St unit C) to shine!
7:30pm - 11:30pm $20
http://www.transportedsf.com/schedule.html

party and this year is no different!!

so if you still have energy after the brass tax 6:66 renegade there are
a couple good parties saturday night... and then a moment of rest
before the entire nation awaits with baited breath the sure sign that
this country is headed in the right direction... i thought weekends
that started on wednesday were bad but you know none of us are doing
anything until we know the outcome of the election!!! 


SATURDAY NOV 1st


many of us were disappointed when the symbiosis crew didn't come
through with their amazing campout this year, but they are quickly
making up for it with a series of amazing events! tonight they take
over the beautiful kelly's mission rock...

DAY OF THE DEAD
Kelly's Mission Rock
817 Terry Francois Blvd.
9:30pm - 5am 21+
$10 adv/ $15 door

Lazer Sword
Random Rab
3WS
Sexytime
Majitope
DJ Bogl
Ribotto
dj Christopher
Tony Inorbit
John Holiday

and
what epic weekend would be complete without a blowout from the space
cowboys? there's too much info so i'm just gonna give you the basics...
all your favorite sf ug djs, a bunch of art cars, there's a biodiesel
shuttle and god knows how long it will go for... 

GHOST SHIP
Treasure Island
$20 at the door in costume, 21+, full bars on premises
Limited Presales available at groovetickets.com
more info at  WWW.SPACECOWBOYS.ORG



ok
so now that we got the weekend out of the way... it's time to look
towards the future. if you haven't already, tuesday november 4th you
should go vote. i know many
have noticed that i'm a little distracted today... it's because all i
can think about is tuesday. and it's not just because i'm hosting an
awesome election night party at mighty and hope that you all come drink
and dance with me as we await the election results... it's because for
the first time in a long time politics is front and center in my mind,
supplanting that part of me that loves only throbbing bass and beats. i
know, amazing, possibly apocalyptic, for sure mind blowing, but true.
so GO VOTE ALREADY!!! and then come to mighty. at least we can celebrate



we'll
be broadcasting election coverage all night, the bus will be chillin
outside with the Ambient Mafia and some old and new favorites throwin
down ill beats inside! 

MIGHTY
119 Utah @ 15th
9pm - 2am
free all night if you volunteered at a polling station
free before 11pm with you "I VOTED" sticker or ballot receipt
$5 otherwise

w/
Aaron Jae & Michael the Redstickman
Pym w/ Laela on violin
Niles

Dr. Toast
The Captain
Drop
Peek
Squelchy




and with that it's time for me to start the weekend. i'll see you on the dancefloor!!!
peace love and beats- pufuchu

I really have no idea how I somehow totally missed knowing about  
them.  I mean... I know I don't get out nearly so much as I used to...  
nor am I as clued in to UGs and renegades as I used to be.  But  
somehow I never actually noticed this crew.

Which really IS pretty ridiculous if they're in the habit of throwing  
aircraft-hanger-sized mini-massives and I've STILL cruised through  
without noticing them,  I really have no excuse for that one.

And just who DO you have to schmooze with to get to throw a rave in  
those hangers anyway?  I've heard from other promoters, in the past,  
who wanted to do so, but said it's well-nigh impossible.


cya,
john

when it comes to bay area parties i'm a newbie so ug = cracktory (fuckin miss that place!) the best being when we got the mog inside there after love parade a couple years ago and burning man being the epitome of all that is good in sf? (minus the feather hats and leather and attitude and yeah..) but the unimog was one of the first beauties of its kind that i did meet, now i know disorient and the purgatory cruiser and the neuroweapon and the nexxus mobile and then the unimog has martha and the nexxus mobile has the frito lay truck and oh how do i LOVE my mobile sound systems!!! but i can see how you wouldn't really associate the cowboys with ugs and definitely not raves as i imagine they were born from the barren dust...

but it seems that it's a distinct possibility that those spots on the island might open up to more events.. though i must say the younger crowd has ruined more that one spot for us geriatrics...

so bigger and better yes please!!! (rave at NASA anyone? helped with both so far) but please with respect and love and remember to clean up after yourselves (mexicans will do it for cheap. no i'm serious.)

but most importantly... quiet in and quiet out and control your parking areas and seruously?? RAVE ON!!!!

Hey y'all.

Just want to take a second to really give a heartfelt recommendation about
this Paco Osuna character. For those of you who follow new techno closely,
there's no doubt you've either seen or heard about Paco by now. For the res=
t
of you who this may be a somewhat new name to, let me tell you, this guy is
pretty amazing. I first saw him in person at this years DEMF, where he
played a prime slot in the Beatport tent alongside his M-nus cohorts
including Richie Hawtin, Magda, Heartthrob and Konrad Black.

HO. LEE. CRAP. He looked like the Ice Man up there, but I'll be damned if h=
e
didn't have the place going absolutely apeshit! In addition to his amazing
technical abilities, Paco's got a real talent for manipulating the energy
and tension in the room in a way that just makes the dancefloor explode int=
o
a bunch of jumping, screaming, techno-loving freaks.
Sounds kinda like us, huh? :)

Anyway, there seems to be a lot going on tomorrow night, but I assure you
that making it down to the Endup will be considered a wise move on your par=
t
come Sunday morning. If you don't make it, at least prepare yourself for al=
l
those "OMG, Paco Osuna was soooo sick! I can't believe you missed it!"
conversations down the road.
;)

Hope to see lots of friendly faces and dancing machines tomorrow. It's
definitely gonna be another one of those "I was there" nights.


-----> Greg Bird and the [KONTROL] crew

_______________________________________


Saturday, November 1st, 2008

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 1st Saturday at The Endup


featuring from Barcelona, Spain:

PACO OSUNA  - 3 hour DJ set

(plus 8 . zenit . mindshake . m_nus . ovum)

In the last several years, Paco Osuna has made a
steady ascent from "Paco who?" to one of the most
in-demand headliners on the international scene.
Starting his DJ career in the mid 90's, his mastery
behind 3 decks and unconventional sense of groove
soon landed him a  residency at Ibiza's famed
Amnesia club, where he continued to hone his craft
alongside Sven Vath and other elite DJs. His
famously intense sets, which fuse the best of
techno and house in a dramatic ride of tension-
building and release, have won him prime slots at
most major international clubs and music festivals
including Sonar, Love Parade, WMC, and the DEMF,
to name just a few. If you're a fan of peak hour
"hard minimal" a la Richie Hawtin, Marco Carola,
and Adam Beyer, Paco's 3 hour SF debut is
something you definitely don't want to miss!


with [KONTROL] residents:

CRAIG KUNA  (platform . esdjco)

ALLAND BYALLO  (nightlight . auralism . leibe*detail)

NIKOLA BAYTALA  (s.w.a.t. . robsoul . junior boys own)

SAMMY D  (dirtybird . utensil . magnificent 7)

___________________________________________________


PACO OSUNA (aka Osuna, Smoke Paper Inc.)

Paco Osuna Perez was born in Barcelona in 1974, and his passion for music
started out when he was very young. At the tender age of 14 he was part of =
a
regular crowd at Studio 54, where the most charismatic DJ, Raul Orellana,
was spinning Acid House, marking Paco in the way of understanding DJing.

In '94 Paco moved to Valencia where he had his first contact with the decks
as a hobby. In '95 Paco made his first DJ set as a professional at the ACTV
club, where he gained a year residency. After that, he started playing in
many different clubs including Heaven and Universal.

In the meanwhile he worked in a record shop, where he got access to a
recording studio in which he produced three singles for the label Lucas
Records. In '99 he got a residency at Amnesia in Ibiza. There he had the
brilliant opportunity to be lined up with the biggest DJs and could learn
the different styles, looking to build his own. Amnesia was also the place
where Paco got in touch with the person who most influenced his future as
much personally as professionally, Sven V=E4th, who soon discovered Paco to=
 be
very talented and introduced him in his Cocoon Booking agency. Paco was the
first Spanish DJ to play for this prestigious agency.

In 2001 Paco decided to migrate away from House music, moving closer to
Techno. From then on his career has gotten better and better, leading him t=
o
the best clubs and festivals in the world. Being at home in both House and
Techno, as well as in the fusion between them, Paco Osuna understands his
sets as an "in-crescendo"-journey causing variations of tension that drive
the dancefloor crazy. The combination of this factor and his unquestionable
technical skills has led to Paco being considered one of the most solid
promises of the international scene.
